<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toys R Us Earns Fall 18 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARAMUS, N.J. (AP) -- Toys R Us Inc.'s fourth-quarter earnings  
fell 18 percent from a year ago as the nation's largest toy 
retailer lost business to discount chains like Wal-Mart. 
</P>
<P>
	Paramus, N.J.-based Toys R Us also struggled amid weakness in  
the toy industry worldwide, with a lack of blockbuster toys -- 
except for Furby and a few others -- driving consumers to stores. 
</P>
<P>
	For the fourth-quarter ended Jan. 30, Toys R Us earned $310  
million, or $1.23 a diluted share, compared with earnings of $378 
million, or $1.32 a share, during the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding a $13 million charge, the company earned $323 million,  
or $1.28 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The charge is related to an agreement to settle third-party  
claims in legal actions relating to allegations in 1996 that Toys R 
Us pressured its suppliers, including Hasbro and Mattel, not to 
ship its most popular toys to discount clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter were $4.94 billion, down from $4.98  
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the decline in earnings, Toys R Us' results topped  
Wall Street analysts' estimates. Its stock closed down 56 1/4 cents at 
$17.37 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive officer Robert Nakasone attributed the weak  
results to strong comparisons a year ago, when there was lots of 
buying of virtual pets, action figures and video systems and games. 
</P>
<P>
	But the retailer also faces growing competition from discount  
stores like Wal-Mart and Target, which offer many of the same 
products at cheaper prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us closed 90 stores and cut 3,000 jobs last year and  
decided to revamp its store format to make it easier to navigate 
and to add more bargain items, electronics and children's clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	The `C-3' design will be implemented in 200 new stores in 1999  
and 325 more stores in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year, Toys R Us lost $132 million, or 50 cents a share,  
compared with earnings of $490 million, or $1.70 a share, a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 results include a restructuring charge of $508 million.  
Excluding the charges, net income was $376 million, or $1.41 a 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales were $11.17 billion, up slightly from $11.04 billion in  
1997. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
