<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Final Four Is Maryland's Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Len Elmore and Len Bias never made it.  
Neither did Buck Williams or Walt Williams. Joe Smith and John 
Lucas fell short, too. 
</P>
<P>
	All-America players at Maryland, all of them. And there's one  
other link -- none of them played in a Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, it's Steve Francis' turn to try to take the Terrapins to a  
place they've never reached. Expected to go far in the NCAAs, they 
begin their bid Thursday in the first round of the South Regional 
against last year's tournament darling, Valparaiso. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no added pressure,'' Francis said before practice  
Wednesday. ``We're not here for a vacation, we're here to play 
basketball. Hopefully, we have six games to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The explosive guard sparked No. 5 Maryland the whole season,  
averaging 17.2 points in his first year since transferring from a 
junior college. The Terrapins are seeded second, but many predict 
they will emerge from the South, not top seed Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know there were times when expectations were so high that it  
was tough on our players. Hopefully, we learned from that,'' coach 
Gary Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before, we were always the team that would sneak up on  
somebody,'' he said. ``This year, we usually had the higher ranking 
when we played good teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland and Valparaiso play in the first of four games at the  
Orlando Arena, followed by Louisville vs. Creighton. At night, St. 
John's takes on Samford and then Indiana plays George Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Maryland and Valparaiso have never met, the Terps know  
all about their 15th-seeded opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the whole basketball world learned about Valpo in last  
year's tournament. In a play epitomizing March Madness, the 
Crusaders stunned favored Mississippi when Bryce Drew -- son of 
coach Homer Drew -- hit a buzzer-beating 3-pointer for a 70-69 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everyone heard the story. Coach Drew and his son, the  
Cinderella story of last year's tournament,'' Maryland senior Laron 
Profit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Valpo went on to reach the round of 16, beating Florida State  
before losing to Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	``We received a lot of attention for that,'' coach Drew said.  
``People now know we're 50 miles from Chicago. Most people now know 
how to pronounce Valparaiso, with a long `a,''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryce now plays in the NBA for the Houston Rockets and last  
year's last-second play -- called ``Pacer'' -- has been replaced by a 
new one, just in case. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a different play this year,'' Homer said. ``It's called  
`Houston.' I think you can see why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A team looking to become this year's Valpo is 14th-seeded  
Samford, making its first NCAA appearance. Billing themselves as 
``Southern-Fried Princeton,'' the Bulldogs run the same kind of 
deliberate offense as their Ivy League idols. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jimmy Tillette has patterned his style after Princeton,  
talking to its coaches and watching game films. Last week, he even 
traveled to New Jersey to watch the Tigers play Penn. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Samford will face a tough test in much more athletic St.  
John's. The Red Storm led the Big East in scoring in their first 
year under coach Mike Jarvis, but have not won an NCAA tournament 
game since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana also is looking for some redemption as coach Bob  
Knight's team has lost five of its last six tournament games. The 
Hoosiers are coming off last week's 16-point loss to Illinois in 
their first Big Ten tournament game. 
</P>
<P>
	George Washington is led by 5-foot-4 Shawnta Rogers, the  
Atlantic 10 player of the year. The Colonials already have had a 
tough time -- because of bad weather, their plane was delayed 
several hours out of the Washington area. 
</P>
<P>
	Creighton is 8-1 against teams in this year's tournament.  
Louisville, however, last month beat a more formidable force -- for 
the first time ever, the NCAA overturned a postseason ban and let 
the Cardinals play. 
</P>
<P>
	Penalized for a recruiting violation, coach Denny Crum's team  
was freed because of a procedural error. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we found out we were going to play, the kids have been  
pretty focused,'' Crum said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
