<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mo., Va. Execute Convicted Killers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POTOSI, Mo. (AP) -- A prisoner whose case inspired a Vatican plea  
that his life be spared was put to death early today for killing a 
prison guard during a 1983 riot. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy Roberts, 46, was executed by injection at Potosi  
Correctional Center, muttering ``you're killing an innocent man'' 
before he died at 12:07 a.m. His fate was sealed after Gov. Mel 
Carnahan rejected a clemency request. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours earlier, George Quesinberry Jr., 37, was executed by  
injection in Jarratt, Va., for killing company owner Thomas Haynes 
during a botched burglary at Tri-City Electrical Supply Co. in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want my family to know I love them,'' Quesinberry said.  
``And to the victim's family, I am sorry for what I've done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six weeks ago, Carnahan commuted convicted killer Darrell  
Mease's death sentence to life in prison after a personal request 
from Pope John Paul II, who visited St. Louis in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor last month refused to halt the execution of  
convicted killer James Rodden. The Vatican did not intercede on his 
behalf, but did write to Carnahan last week seeking mercy for 
Roberts. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts said he was nowhere near Tom Jackson, 62, when the guard  
was stabbed to death by inmates at the Moberly Training Center for 
Men. Other guards say Roberts held Jackson while two inmates 
stabbed him to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys questioned why eyewitnesses didn't initially  
name Roberts, who they say had no blood on him after the stabbing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
