<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Digs Out From Snowfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many of the 270,000 federal workers in the  
capital stayed home Wednesday and schools and many businesses were 
closed as the city dug out from its biggest snowfall in three 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Washingtonians shoveled and salted their way out from under more  
than 8 inches of snow that fell downtown. Up to a foot fell in some 
suburbs -- the most since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wish I had gotten a Jeep,'' said John Smithson as he  
dug his sports car out of a high drift caused by snowplows early 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The snowfall was a political, as well as a physical, challenge  
for commuters. The city's new mayor, Anthony Williams, had pledged 
to improve inefficient city services -- such as snow removal. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams pronounced the city's response a success Wednesday,  
even though hundreds of secondary city streets were untreated and 
unplowed. Main streets through downtown were generally clear by the 
morning rush hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to look at how fast we're getting to the residential  
streets,'' Williams said when asked why 196 contract trucks that 
could have supplemented municipal efforts were never requested. 
</P>
<P>
	The Public Works Department mobilized 280 workers and 103 trucks  
in the first hours of the snowfall Tuesday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal workers were allowed to take a day of leave because of  
the snow, and many other businesses closed or kept short hours 
Wednesday. Schools across the region were closed. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Health and Human Services Department, which administers  
federal child care programs, spokesman Campbell Gardett said many 
workers who made it to the office apparently could not get a sitter 
for their school-age children. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see a lot of children here with their parents -- perhaps a  
real world view of child care,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
