<DOCNO> APW19990310.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 16:41:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals Want To Make Most of NCAA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Coach Denny Crum and Louisville had to beat  
an undefeated opponent just to get a chance to play in the NCAA 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	The seventh-seeded Cardinals, who face Creighton on Thursday  
afternoon in the first round, last month became the first team ever 
to have the NCAA overturn a postseason ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt it was justified,'' Crum said. ``It was easy to  
envision us winning the appeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An NCAA appeals committee cited ``procedural error'' in the case  
of recruiting violations by former Louisville assistant Scooter 
McCray. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee said Louisville and McCray were not adequately  
warned about the severity of the violations, and that may have 
altered their defense. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling made the Cardinals eligible for postseason play just  
four weeks before the start of the Conference USA tournament. 
Louisville, given a second chance by the committee, rattled off 
eight victories in its next 11 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we found out, the kids became focused,'' Crum said.  
``They came out and worked hard every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How far Louisville (19-10) can advance in the tournament will  
depend on Crum's ability to get his players on the same page. Crum 
has done it before, with his 42 tournament victories ranking him 
third in tournament history. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've played some pretty good basketball,'' Crum said. ``Our  
biggest problem is that we need everyone to play well on the same 
night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth-year senior Cameron Murray was glad to get a chance to  
play at least one more game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great feeling to have everything behind us,'' Murray  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals feature an up-tempo offense similar to Creighton.  
</P>
<P>
	``They're really balanced and all five of their guys have the  
potential for big games,'' Creighton coach Dana Altman said. ``We 
don't want to run up and down with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Creighton (21-8), which last was in the NCAAs in 1991, takes a  
six-game winning streak into the game. The Bluejays earned an 
automatic bid by winning the Missouri Valley Conference tournament 
last week in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is overlooking us,'' said Creighton's Rodney Buford,  
one of 12 players in the 92-year history of the MVC to score 2,000 
points. ``They don't know what kind of program we have and what 
kind of athletes we have. We have a lot of hard-working guys, and 
you can't take that for granted.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
