<DOCNO> APW19990310.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:26:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nevada Court OKs Action Vs. Tyson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) -- Boxer Mike Tyson lost a round in a  
court battle involving refund demands from up to 2 million people 
who paid $49.95 to watch the pay-for-view television fight between 
Tyson and heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nevada Supreme Court ruled that a number of suits filed  
against Tyson and promoter Don King could go forward as a 
nationwide class-action suit in Clark County District Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, in a brief order Tuesday, refused to overturn the  
order of District Judge Gene Porter that the suits could be 
considered a class action for Nevada residents and those in other 
states. Court records say this could include up to 2 million 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson, now serving time in a Maryland jail for assault, was  
disqualified in the third round of the June 28, 1997 bout after 
twice biting Holyfield. More than 30 suits were filed across the 
nation by disgruntled viewers who, according to court documents, 
suggest Tyson threw the fight. They want their money back on 
grounds that he was guilty of misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the suits were consolidated into a nationwide  
class-action suit in New York. In late 1997, Porter agreed to 
certify the case as a nationwide class action. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Tyson and King appealed to the Supreme Court,  
arguing that Porter abused his discretion by certifying a duplicate 
suit in Nevada as a class action when one existed in New York. The 
same issues were raised in both cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the unhappy fight fans said Tyson and King failed to  
demonstrate ``any irreparable damage they will suffer or identify 
any abuse of discretion'' by Porter. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice T. Charles Ramos of the New York Supreme Court on Oct.  
22, 1998 dismissed the complaint in that state and denied the TV 
viewers any right to discovery. 
</P>
<P>
	J. Colby Williams, Las Vegas lawyer for the class action in  
Nevada, said Ramos' ruling is being appealed in New York, where the 
Supreme Court is the lowest of three court levels. He said lawyers 
have agreed to put a hold on the Nevada action until the issue is 
resolved in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 10:36:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> '20 Dates' Born From Rejection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The idea for ``20 Dates'' was born out of  
rejection. 
</P>
<P>
	Not rejection by women, although that came later.  
</P>
<P>
	We're talking about rejection by directors, producers and anyone  
else it takes to get a part in a movie or to sell a script. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the motivation for Myles Berkowitz, whose  
documentary-style film, ``20 Dates,'' is being released by Fox 
Searchlight. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a dream come true, although he is wary.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've just gone through 15 years of rejection, and the only way  
I survived them was to try not to get too depressed, try not to 
commit too much to any single 'no,''' Berkowitz says. ``So now that 
I'm getting 'yeses,' I've got to keep an even keel or else 
everything will go out of whack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a cold, rainy day in Manhattan. Berkowitz lives in Los  
Angeles, but he feels right at home. He was born and raised in New 
York. He attended the University of Pennsylvania, where he studied 
political science and marketing. After graduation, he studied 
acting with John Strasberg and appeared in several off-Broadway 
productions. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, he moved to Los Angeles ``to break into the movies.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I didn't want to make movies,'' says Berkowitz.  
``Sometimes I feel like I was bitten by a vampire at night. I can 
only tell you that when I was in college, one night I went to a 
midnight screening of 'The Graduate,' and I said, 'this is the 
greatest thing that I have ever seen. I want to make a movie like 
that.' And that's what got me into the movies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The years rolled by. Hollywood scarcely noticed him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I woke up one day in L.A. and I realized, 'Wow, I've been here  
for 12 years and I'm failing,''' says Berkowitz, 36. ``And it was 
the crossroad of my life, really, in that it seemed very clear to 
me that I actually may not get my dream, it may not come true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's when he decided to make his own film.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've spent all this time trying to get into other people's  
movies or trying to sell a script so that other people could make 
the movie, and I thought, 'You know what? If I fail, I fail. But at 
least I want to go down fighting, I want to go down actually making 
a movie, and then if nothing happens with it, at least I'd know I 
gave it my best shot and I'd be able to move on with my life.' 
</P>
<P>
	``But I didn't think I'd be able to move on unless I made a  
movie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berkowitz had been married -- briefly -- and was recently  
divorced. 
</P>
<P>
	He reasoned: Why not pursue two goals at once? He put together  
$60,000 to make the film and started going out on dates. 
Specifically, ``20 Dates'' -- which proved a sticking point when he 
met Ms. Right and she wanted him to wrap things up. (His major 
financial backer also grew restless.) 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with the prospect of losing Ms. Right, Berkowitz plunged  
on. 
</P>
<P>
	``Would you see a film called '17 Dates'?'' he asks, with a  
touch of disbelief in his voice. ``If you were to ask me back then 
when I started, what was more important, the girl or the movie, I 
would say the movie. Absolutely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the film, he demonstrates his lack of dating skills  
as he tries almost anything to meet -- and impress -- women. 
</P>
<P>
	This includes bungee jumping (``the worst thing I've done in my  
entire life''); posing as a photographer at a wedding (``I used to 
crash weddings all the time in Los Angeles -- this was nothing new 
to me''); and borrowing a small child to attract women on the beach 
(it was his agent's son). 
</P>
<P>
	Then he met Elisabeth Wagner, who sold linens in a shopping mall  
and studied at UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	The two clicked.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the project got away from me,'' Berkowitz says with  
a laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	Still determined to remain faithful to his project, Berkowitz  
continued to date other women. 
</P>
<P>
	``A date is a very emotional experience,'' he says. ``It's a  
very intense three to four hours with a beginning, a middle, an 
end. It's got humor, it's got tragedy, it's got tension. It's got 
anything you can ask for in a drama or a comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's also got a lot of raw emotions.''  
</P>
<P>
	That might explain why several of his dates were unhappy when he  
told them a hidden camera had taped their evening together. (We're 
talking lawsuits and personal injury here.) 
</P>
<P>
	Berkowitz made it through ``20 Dates'' -- the last three under  
Wagner's watchful eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he spent a year editing more than 130 hours of video for  
the 88-minute film. 
</P>
<P>
	And what started out as ``a mean, little vicious comedy about  
dating'' became a romantic comedy with a happy Hollywood ending. 
</P>
<P>
	Berkowitz proposed marriage -- and Wagner accepted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 12:45:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Launches Web Site To Sell Autos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- You can't kick the tires, but you can take a  
virtual tour of a General Motors Corp. showroom on the automaker's 
new Web site, which was launched Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prospective buyers can go on line to get details about every GM  
make and model, independent third party competitive comparisons and 
access to the new vehicle inventories of nearly 6,000 dealerships. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers also can apply online for financing, send electronic  
messages to a dealer to get the best purchase price on the exact 
vehicle they want, and schedule a test drive. 
</P>
<P>
	GM introduced its GM BuyPower service in October 1997 in  
California, Oregon, Washington and Idaho and expanded it to the 
entire country Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``GM BuyPower puts consumers in control of the car buying  
process. It was obvious to us this one-of-a-kind service should be 
made available to all consumers searching for a more convenient way 
to shop and buy at their own pace,'' said Ann Noel Blakney, 
BuyPower's national director. 
</P>
<P>
	Several rival automakers, including Ford Motor Co., BMW and  
Nissan, already quote car prices on their Web pages. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GM BuyPower services are available on the Internet at  
www.gmbuypower.com. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
