<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Snow Storm Blankets East, Midwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Marian Andersen was just about to move the last of her red and  
yellow snow shovels at Guse Hardware from a display wall into the 
store's basement when the storm hit. 
</P>
<P>
	With Minneapolis blanketed under 16 inches of snow, Andersen's  
shovels were in demand once again. ``That's what we're here for,'' 
she said with a smile Tuesday as she watched a customer walk out 
with a new shovel. 
</P>
<P>
	From the Plains to the East Coast, a lot of people were reaching  
for shovels today. The storms that began in the Midwest snarled 
traffic, knocked out power and shut down airports and businesses as 
they churned to the east Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	School districts in Virginia and Maryland were closed again  
today as light snow continued to fall. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first major snowstorm of the season for Washington,  
D.C., leading the House to postpone Tuesday's floor votes, delaying 
flights in and out of Dulles and Ronald Reagan National airports, 
and delaying a memorial service for the late Supreme Court Justice 
Harry A. Blackmun. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's beautiful, but it does make extra work,'' said Ruth  
Burkholder as she shoveled the red brick sidewalk outside her baked 
goods store in Sharpsburg, Md., which received about 5 inches of 
snow. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told my mother February was so nice, now we're making up for  
it in March,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a foot of snow fell in Iowa, while parts of Indiana,  
Ohio and Maryland had more than 10 inches and northern Georgia 
labored under a layer of ice 2 inches thick. Traffic-related deaths 
were blamed on the storm in at least six states. 
</P>
<P>
	The snow tapered off in the most areas by Tuesday afternoon, but  
a foot of snow possible by tonight in the West Virginia mountains 
and other areas, including Baltimore, were getting a fresh coat of 
snow this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're reloading the salt trucks and sending them back out,''  
said Rose Mulhausen, a spokeswoman for the Maryland Highway 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve-year-old Daniel Warden avoided a science test when his  
Dayton, Ohio, school was closed Tuesday. Instead, he went sledding 
with his father. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a big science test today and I wanted to get it over  
with, but there's always tomorrow,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only scattered snow was predicted today in Ohio, to the relief  
of many. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice at certain times -- white, clean, pure,'' Russell  
Carson said as he took a break from clearing his driveway in the 
Dayton suburb of Moraine. ``But ... right now, we're looking 
forward to spring -- nice warm weather.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
