<DOCNO> APW19990310.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 12:35:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lake Placid Lands Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Turner Sports has announced the first Winter  
Goodwill Games will take be held at Lake Placid, N.Y., next Feb. 
17-20. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be competition in seven sports -- bobsled, figure  
skating, luge, skiing, ski jumping, snowboarding and short track 
speedskating. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are excited about expanding the Goodwill Games into a  
winter sports franchise,'' said Harvey Schiller, president of 
Turner Sports. ``The Winter Goodwill Games are a great addition to 
TNT's sports lineup, and they will allow another group of athletes 
a chance to compete for Goodwill Games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lake Placid, which hosted the 1932 and 1980 Winter Olympics,  
beat out Lillehammer, Norway, for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous Summer Goodwill Games have been televised on TBS, but  
Turner's other network, TNT, will carry 16 hours of Winter Goodwill 
Games programming. 
</P>
<P>
	A $20 million renovation project has already begun to rebuild  
the Lake Placid bobsled and luge tracks, which have fallen apart 
since the 1980 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The Goodwill Games were the idea of media mogul Ted Turner, who  
began the event in 1986 in response to the Cold War boycotts of the 
1980 and 1984 Olympic Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2001 Summer Goodwill Games are scheduled for 12 days in the  
fall in Brisbane, Queensland, Australia. It will involve 12 sports 
-- basketball, swimming, beach volleyball, track cycling, boxing, 
track and field, diving, triathlon, figure skating, weightlifting, 
gymnastics, rhythmic gymnastics and surf lifesaving. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles' Kamieniecki Makes Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Scott Kamieniecki doesn't have much  
to show for his 1998 season -- two wins and a scar on his neck. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a long year,'' he said Wednesday. ``A very long year.''  
</P>
<P>
	After Kamieniecki started 30 games and went 10-6 in 1997, the  
Baltimore Orioles rewarded the right-hander a $6.1 million, 
two-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Kamieniecki didn't provide much of an initial return on their  
investment, pitching in only 12 games last year and taking three 
trips to the disabled list during a horrid, injury-plagued season 
in which he went 2-6 with a 6.75 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't pitch after Aug. 21 and underwent surgery to repair a  
herniated disk in his neck in September, an operation that ended 
his season and left him with a two-inch scar. 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, Kamieniecki is healthy again and projected to be  
the fourth starter in the Orioles' rotation. His bid to return to 
the form he exhibited in 1997 began in earnest Wednesday when he 
pitched two innings against the Boston Red Sox -- his first 
appearance against outside competition in seven months. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers looked good -- two innings, no runs, two hits and two  
walks. But Kamieniecki was critical of virtually every facet of his 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I might have thrown 35 or 40 pitches; maybe four or five where  
I wanted to,'' he said. ``I was expecting a little better than 
that. I don't how I didn't give up any runs, as bad as I was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When someone suggested that the poor showing could be attributed  
to the fact that he hadn't pitched competitively in months, 
Kamieniecki dismissed the notion with a wave of his hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have any physical problems. There are no aches or  
pains and everything has gone pretty well,'' he said. ``Hopefully I 
just had a bad day. This is the worst, by far, the last four to six 
weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Orioles manager Ray Miller was looking for three innings but  
pulled the plug after two. After a discussion with Kamieniecki 
outside the Baltimore dugout, he sent the pitcher to the bullpen to 
take a few more throws. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Miller, Kamieniecki will be treated carefully until  
he proves he's completely healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm certainly going to conscious of pitch-counts with a guy  
who had neck surgery,'' Miller said. ``If he progresses, he'll 
probably start the season as a six-inning pitcher because of the 
problems he had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, unlike Kamieniecki, liked what he saw Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``First of all, Kammy is angry every day he pitches,'' Miller  
said. ``I saw some first-pitch breaking balls, some 2-0 fastballs 
... If he continues to pitch and get people out, he'll have a spot 
in the rotation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
