<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torre Cancer Dampens Straw's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry sat in the New York  
Yankees dugout Wednesday, surrounded by a throng of reporters, 
quietly talking about his return from colon cancer surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	This was supposed to be Strawberry's day, the afternoon the  
popular Yankee, whose illness inspired his team last October, made 
his return to the lineup earlier than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	But less than 25 feet away from Strawberry sat Joe Girardi,  
explaining the reaction he and his teammates had to the news that 
manager Joe Torre has prostate cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hardest thing to understand is why,'' Girardi said about  
30 minutes after he broke the news to his teammates playing a 
split-squad game against the Boston Red Sox. ``The first thing that 
went through my mind is, `What's next?' You see Darryl coming back, 
and then you hear Joe has cancer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Girardi said Torre told him, Paul O'Neill and David Cone the  
news in the same way he manages the club: businesslike and 
unemotional. For the most part, Torre's players handled the news 
the same way. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I understand, it is a good cancer to have,'' Derek  
Jeter said. ``There's no good cancer, but it is the best to have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees have grown all too accustomed to dealing with death  
and illness in recent years. David Cone's aneurysm and the death of 
Torre's brother Rocco and heart transplant for his brother Frank 
colored the 1996 championship season. 
</P>
<P>
	The past few months have been filled with stories of  
Strawberry's cancer, Joe DiMaggio's battle with lung cancer that 
ended in his death Monday, Catfish Hunter's fight with Lou Gehrig's 
Disease and former farmhand Mike Lowell's diagnosis with testicular 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cancer is a terrible word,'' O'Neill said in Bradenton, where  
the other half of the Yankees played. ``It's a scary thing for 
everybody. The main concern is to take care of this as soon as 
possible. Hopefully, he'll have a full recovery. This is life, not 
baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The news was particularly difficult for Strawberry, who only one  
day earlier spoke of his excitement of convincing Torre to let him 
return to the lineup one week early. Strawberry went 1-for-4 in his 
debut, but his mind was clearly on his manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really couldn't get as motivated as I would have been,''  
Strawberry said. ``It is truly devastating when it happens. You ask 
how much can a person take. We as players are dedicated to our 
manager. We just have to go out and dedicate the season to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Yankees didn't learn of Torre's illness until  
Wednesday, Strawberry said he sensed his manager wasn't feeling 
right in recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wasn't as upbeat as he has been,'' Strawberry said. ``He  
was acting kind of different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre spent the day at his spring home in Tampa. There was no  
immediate word on what his course of treatment would be. But owner 
George Steinbrenner said he expected Torre back early next month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joe will be able to handle it,'' Steinbrenner said. ``He is a  
very courageous man. He should be back in 30 days, thanks to the 
miracles of modern-day medicine.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
