<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs ATM Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The spirit of bipartisanship is starting to  
fray within the House Banking Committee as it labors to draft 
legislation to knock down Depression-era barriers separating the 
financial services industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the conciliatory mood shifted Wednesday, the panel  
managed to overwhelmingly approve a compromise provision requiring 
ATM surcharges to be clearly disclosed at the teller machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The 48-1 vote attached the surcharge measure to sweeping  
legislation that would allow banks, securities firms and insurance 
companies to merge and get more deeply into each other's 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	But several hours later, some lawmakers started pushing divisive  
proposals. Rep. John LaFalce of New York, the committee's senior 
Democrat, angrily warned Republicans that ``the chances for passage 
of this bill will come to an end'' if they tried to choke off 
debate on amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee was to try again today, after adjourning its  
second all-day drafting session Wednesday without completing work 
on the bill -- for which the Clinton administration has indicated 
its strong support. 
</P>
<P>
	The ATM surcharge measure, sponsored by LaFalce, Committee  
Chairman Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, and Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., 
was a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier attempt to ban the surcharges outright, pushed by  
Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont, the House's lone independent, gave 
way to the milder disclosure measure. 
</P>
<P>
	It would require clear disclosure of the surcharges, which come  
on top of charges by customers' own banks for using a machine 
operated by another bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically:  
</P>
<P>
	--The fact that double charges are imposed on people who aren't  
customers of that bank would have to be posted in a sign on the 
teller machine. 
</P>
<P>
	--The surcharge amount would have to be specified on the screen  
after consumers log in. Consumers would have to be given the chance 
to terminate their transaction before paying the surcharge. 
</P>
<P>
	--When issuing ATM cards to customers, banks would have to  
provide a warning that surcharges may be assessed by other banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Many banks currently do at least some of those things  
voluntarily at the ATMs they operate. 
</P>
<P>
	The sole dissenting vote came from Rep. Judy Biggert, R-Ill.,  
who said she believed the banks could sufficiently police 
themselves in operating automated teller machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department's Antitrust Division last year started  
looking into whether the nation's largest ATM networks are 
illegally preventing small banks from eliminating the double 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups oppose the surcharges, which have been banned by  
Connecticut and Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Thursday, the Senate Banking Committee voted along party  
lines to approve and send to the full Senate a bill to overhaul the 
financial services laws proposed by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and 
opposed by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In its current form, it would face a White House veto because  
Clinton believes the bill fails to protect consumers and would hurt 
community lending laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 12:35:44 </DATE_TIME>
