<HEADLINE> Ariz. Governor Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Gov. Jane Hull was in the hospital Wednesday with  
a kidney infection she first noticed on a weekend trip to Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is uncomfortable, but alert and working,'' spokeswoman  
Francie Noyes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hull, 63, checked into Good Samaritan Regional Medical  
Center on Tuesday evening, Noyes said. The governor and her 
husband, a doctor, became concerned because she was so nauseous she 
couldn't take antibiotic pills without vomiting, Noyes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors put Mrs. Hull on intravenous antibiotics and fluids at  
the hospital, and she should be released within a day or two, Noyes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's dealing with state business over the phone, but we're  
trying to get her some rest so she can recuperate,'' Noyes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hull took office in 1997 after the bank fraud conviction of  
former Gov. Fife Symington. She fell ill Saturday while in the Gulf 
of California port of Puerto Penasco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
