<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 10:16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Groups Lobby on Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As President Clinton and Republicans lay out  
their plans to overhaul Social Security, interest groups are 
hardening their positions and increasing political pressure by 
aiming big-money campaigns at American workplaces and living rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's lots of activity. It's going to continue, it's going  
to grow,'' said Roger Hickey of the Institute for America's Future, 
who is working with a $500,000 budget to coordinate the lobbying 
efforts of groups opposed to major changes in the retirement 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the labor, civil rights and women's groups involved, the  
AFL-CIO is in the midst of a 50-city tour of rallies, dropping 
leaflets at workplaces around the country and considering a 
national advertising campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, workers may soon find handouts in their  
in-boxes or stuck on bulletin boards from chief executives involved 
in a competing campaign. They want to promote legislation that 
would divert some of the Social Security taxes now deducted from 
paychecks into personal retirement accounts that people could 
invest in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance of business and conservative groups, led by the  
National Association of Manufacturers, is planning to make the 
handouts available on the Internet. Television and radio ads are 
also in the works, and the business alliance's budget to reach out 
beyond Washington will surpass the $500,000 or so it plans to spend 
lobbying lawmakers directly. 
</P>
<P>
	Such activity by interest groups could play a positive role,  
helping to educate people about different options, said Carolyn 
Lukensmeyer, director of Americans Discuss Social Security, a 
nonpartisan project to encourage national debate. 
</P>
<P>
	But with a presidential election next year, large-scale  
advertising and grassroots campaigns also have the potential to 
threaten chances for any bipartisan compromise on Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the idea is to use sound bites to frighten people, it's  
destructive,'' said Lukensmeyer. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has suggested a complicated plan that would  
use federal budget surpluses to help the economy grow so that in 
the future, the nation can afford to pay the Social Security 
benefits promised to baby boomers. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican congressional leaders also want to use surpluses to  
shore up Social Security, but would prefer to use them to finance 
the transition to a new, partially privatized retirement system 
they say will ultimately be less expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides say they are willing to negotiate a compromise.  
</P>
<P>
	But interest groups opposed to big changes have been emboldened  
by the support for the White House plan shown in public opinion 
polls. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does give them an upper hand in bargaining,'' said John  
Rother, public policy director for AARP. The organization of older 
people supports the concept of using general revenues for Social 
Security, also an element of Clinton's plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The unions and other traditional Democratic supporters thus are  
in less of a mood to compromise, seeing a chance to win back 
Congress in the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Committee to Preserve Social Security and Medicare,  
an advocacy group on retirement and other senior citizen issues, 
recently released an inch-thick report, based on a sophisticated 
computer simulation, seeking to show that most Americans would get 
lower retirement benefits under a private accounts system. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, the Securities Industry Association,  
representing Wall Street investment firms, recently sent letters to 
lawmakers offering help in designing a private accounts system. And 
other supporters of a partially privatized system are trying to 
match the formidable grassroots power their adversaries boast. 
</P>
<P>
	Through a site on the Internet, the conservative group Economic  
Security 2000 is seeking out supporters for private accounts, and 
has already forwarded tens of thousands of e-mail messages to 
Capitol Hill and the White House in a campaign dubbed ``The 
Billion-Byte March.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now the group is following up to see if the same people want to  
get involved in more traditional activities, such as visiting 
lawmakers' offices or writing letters to local newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that our side has been too complacent on the  
grassroots side thus far,'' said spokeswoman Hillary Beard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 12:54:28 </DATE_TIME>
