<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Decision Due on Italy Court-Martial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Marine Corps is nearing a decision on  
whether to go ahead with the court-martial of a second Marine 
aviator in the fatal and politically charged Italian Alps ski 
gondola accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision is for Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of Marine  
Forces Atlantic, and could come as early as today, senior Marine 
officers said in interviews Tuesday. Pace's decision comes on the 
heels of the acquittal by a military jury last Thursday of Marine 
Capt. Richard J. Ashby, 32, of Mission Viejo, Calif., who was the 
pilot of the EA-6B Prowler involved in the accident Feb. 3, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Prowler was flying too low and too fast when it sliced a  
cable holding the ski gondola, sending the 20 people inside to 
their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ashby acquittal triggered immediate speculation that the  
case would be dropped against his navigator, Capt. Joseph 
Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y., who has the same charges lodged 
against him. Jury selection in the Schweitzer court-martial is 
scheduled to begin March 18 at Camp Lejeune, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Marine officials said Tuesday a possibility remains that Pace  
will decide to proceed with the case against Schweitzer. 
</P>
<P>
	One alternative, the officers said, speaking on condition they  
not be identified, would be to drop the criminal case and go 
directly to administrative action that could include removing 
Schweitzer and Ashby from the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marines felt stung by criticism from the Italian government  
and victims' relatives who insist that Ashby's acquittal means he 
and the rest of his crew have escaped accountability. The Marines 
are intent on ensuring that the two be held responsible, if not 
criminally culpable. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Pace decides not to proceed with a court-martial of  
Schweitzer and drop an obstruction of justice charge remaining 
against Ashby, both men would be likely to face nonjudicial 
punishment that probably would end their flying careers. 
</P>
<P>
	Both, for example, will face a Field Flight Performance Board  
inquiry to evaluate their performance in light of the gondola 
incident and possibly recommend they not fly again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
