<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Delay in Ending IOC Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The conclusion of an IOC investigation into the  
Salt Lake City scandal has been delayed again. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Rogge, a member of the IOC's inquiry commission, said  
today the panel's report was still being finalized and might not be 
released until next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel will recommend expulsions, warnings or exonerations  
for 19 IOC members still under investigation for alleged misconduct 
stemming from Salt Lake's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission had planned to complete its report by the end of  
last week, but then said its recommendations would be released by 
the middle of this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said the panel held a conference call Tuesday night and  
plans to hold another tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we will finalize everything,'' he said by telephone  
from Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said the report, which he described as lengthy, will then  
have to be translated from English into French before being sent to 
the IOC executive board for action. 
</P>
<P>
	While the board had been expected to hold a conference call this  
week, Rogge said those plans could be scrapped for ``practical 
reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said the board might not deal with the panel's  
recommendations until its formal meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland, 
Monday and Tuesday on the eve of the two-day IOC general assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said some executive board members will be traveling to  
Switzerland in the next few days and president Juan Antonio 
Samaranch might not be able to reach them by phone before the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge denied the delays indicated the commission was divided or  
undecided on some of the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is absolute consensus,'' he said. ``The only issue has  
been that we've received more and more (written) material as a 
result of our requests to members and the Salt Lake organizing 
committee. We only received some of the documents in the last few 
days. You need to look at those materials.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the inquiry panel, IOC vice president Dick Pound,  
said Monday that one member's case remain to be resolved. He 
declined to identify the member. 
</P>
<P>
	The most sensitive case is that of South Korea's Kim Un-Yong,  
the IOC executive member and highest-ranking official implicated in 
the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim has been accused of using his influence to get lucrative  
jobs in television and entertainment for his children. He has 
vigorously denied any wrongdoing, hired a New York law firm to 
defend him and suggested he is the victim of an internal plot to 
undermine his chances of becoming IOC president. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine IOC members resigned or were ousted in the first phase of  
the Salt Lake inquiry that was completed in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The current probe involves three members -- including Kim -- who  
remained under investigation after the first phase, plus 16 others 
who were cited in a Salt Lake ethics report released last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
