<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Failed To Stop China Spying  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It took top national security officials almost  
a year to determine there were ``serious problems'' requiring 
security changes at nuclear weapons labs after receiving a 1996 
briefing about possible espionage. National Security Adviser Sandy 
Berger said he received a ``very preliminary'' briefing in 1996 
that China may have obtained critical nuclear warhead information 
from the Los Alamos laboratory in New Mexico. But only after a more 
detailed briefing in July 1997 were the problems involving China 
and the labs brought into sharp focus, he said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Italians Seek NATO Base Review  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italy's premier today said NATO bases were necessary  
for national security but that the alliance's agreement will have 
to be reviewed if no one is punished for the ski cable car tragedy. 
Premier Massimo D'Alema, who has called Capt. Richard Ashby's 
acquittal last week on 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter 
``unacceptable,'' said he expects Ashby's superiors to be held 
responsible. ``The real problem is not to eliminate the bases, but 
to better define their roles,'' D'Alema said. Some Italian 
politicians have demanded the bases be closed. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA To Boost Airport Security  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal audit found inadequate safeguards  
for secured areas at the five of nation's biggest airports, 
prompting the Federal Aviation Administration to launch a security 
crackdown. A Transportation Department official briefed the House 
Appropriations Committee today, reporting that undercover personnel 
could enter restricted areas through emergency exits and penetrate 
air cargo facilities. Some were even able to board planes. FAA 
officials will look into compliance by the nation's 78 largest 
commercial airports and their airlines for controlling secured 
areas and their ability to keep out unauthorized personnel. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Peace Plan Hits Snag Again  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright urged  
Congress to delay votes on Kosovo until peace talks are completed, 
suggesting the warring sides would interpret a lack of U.S. resolve 
as ``a green light to resume fighting.'' But House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert rejected her appeal and scheduled a debate for tomorrow on 
a resolution on the possible deployment of U.S. troops. Peace talks 
between the ethnic Albanians and Serbs resume Monday. However, 
prospects for success seemed to dim today when U.S. envoy Richard 
Holbrooke failed to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic 
to sign onto the deal. 

</P>
<P>
	China Will Not Devalue Currency  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese banking officials Thursday doused renewed  
speculation about a possible devaluation of the Chinese currency. 
During the annual session of the national legislature, People's 
Bank of China Gov. Dai Xianglong told reporters that there are no 
plans to allow the value of the yuan to decline in 1999. Dai was 
rebutting a report in Thursday's Financial Times that cited a 
senior government official saying decisions to devalue the yuan 
would depend on whether China can maintain acceptable levels of 
economic growth and social stability. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Floats Independent Counsel Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans today floated a plan to let  
the independent counsel law expire and place investigations of 
high-level government officials under an assistant attorney 
general. Rep. George Gekas suggested the plan in a letter to 
Attorney General Janet Reno. Under the proposal, the chief of the 
Public Integrity Section would be subject to Senate confirmation 
and appointed for a fixed term that would extend beyond the 
electoral cycle. 

</P>
<P>
	New Rules Simplify Medicine Labels  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore planned to announce new  
regulations tomorrow requiring that all over-the-counter medicines 
have easier-to-read labels. More consumer-friendly labels ``will 
give Americans the information they need to prevent tens of 
thousands of unnecessary hospitalizations that occur each year,'' 
Gore said. Most drugs should carry the new label within two years. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Start Up  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks opened slightly higher Thursday,  
boosted by a surge on Wall Street. The Nikkei rose 5.43 points to 
15,485.43 in early trading. In New York earlier today, the Dow 
industrials rose 79.08 points to 9,772.84, a record close. 

</P>
<P>
	Penguins Snap Losing Streak  
</P>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Kip Miller scored with 2:11 left in  
overtime as the Pittsburgh Penguins rallied from a two-goal, 
third-period deficit to beat the Carolina Hurricanes 3-2 tonight 
and end a season-high, six-game winless streak. Miller scored his 
17th of the season as Hurricanes goaltender Arturs Irbe was trying 
to cover up the puck in the crease. Pittsburgh has an NHL-high six 
victories and 21 points in overtime games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
