<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Do You Have Too Much Company Stock? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Senior management has long been rewarded with  
company stock or stock options. Now it's commonplace for employers, 
particularly in high-tech industries, to reward many, if not all, 
of their employees with company stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet there are risks in loading up on company stock, particularly  
in retirement plans, warns an expert on the subject at the College 
for Financial Planning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It often makes a lot of sense at the time to obtain the  
stock,'' says Bryan Schmitt, an academic associate at the College. 
``But if you accumulate a large amount of company stock, it can 
become a disproportionate share of your net worth, and that can 
create risks, particularly after you retire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Obtaining company stock is attractive to many employees, Schmitt  
concedes. For example, it's common for companies to use their own 
stock instead of cash to match employee contributions to 401 (k) 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, according to Hewitt Associates, company stock accounts  
for one-third of the total value of assets in 401(k) plans that 
offer it. Employees also can typically buy the stock in a purchase 
plan or be awarded stock options at a discount. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond the benefits of tax deferral and acquiring stock or  
options at discounts, many employees like obtaining company stock 
because it is stock they are familiar with, Schmitt says. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are downsides.  
</P>
<P>
	``The risk with obtaining a lot of company stock is that you  
have a lot riding on a single investment in a single industry,'' 
Schmitt says. If the company falters, it means not only your job 
may be at risk, so might your nest egg. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt says the risk is even worse for retirees who may still  
own a lot of their former employer's stock. Their pot of gold is 
tied up in that one stock. ``They don't have the option of changing 
jobs if the stock falters,'' Schmitt says. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, it's easy to point to people who have made small or  
large fortunes owning their company stock. However, for every 
Microsoft or Intel, there are companies like Boston Market whose 
stock drops in value. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the big gains made by the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index  
and the Nasdaq in 1998 were generated by a relatively small number 
of companies. Most of the other companies made only modest gains or 
even lost value. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt recommends that retirees and employees, particularly  
those approaching retirement, systematically sell off some of their 
company stock and buy other investments in order to diversify their 
portfolio and lower their overall risk. Because holders of company 
stock typically track their stock closely, they often know about 
good times to sell. 
</P>
<P>
	You may have to work around potential selling restrictions.  
Companies often don't allow you to dispose of the stock for a 
certain period of time, particularly in the case of stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	If you can't sell some of the stock for a while, be sure the  
rest of your investments are not too similar to your company's 
stock, Schmitt suggests. 
</P>
<P>
	Taxes may be another concern. It's not a worry if the stock is  
still inside a retirement plan where its sale won't incur taxes. 
But even taxable stock will probably receive favorable capital 
gains rates if you have held the stock at least a year, Schmitt 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt cautions that if you sell company stock it's best to use  
the proceeds to buy an asset that's not related to the industry 
you're in, Selling Microsoft and buying Intel doesn't help your 
diversification much. 
</P>
<P>
	If you are ready to retire and you have a lot of company stock  
in your retirement plan, don't automatically roll the plan proceeds 
into an individual retirement account, Schmitt says. 
</P>
<P>
	You have the option of taking the stock out as part of a lump  
sum. You'll pay regular income taxes on the stock, but only on the 
value of the stock at the time it was put into your account. 
</P>
<P>
	Any appreciation in the value of the stock since then is not  
taxed until you sell it, and then it will be taxed only at the 
capital gains rate. If you keep the stock until your death, it will 
pass to your heirs at its current market value, avoiding capital 
gains taxes entirely (though not necessarily estate taxes). If you 
roll the stock into an IRA instead, you'll pay regular income taxes 
on it when you withdraw it. 
</P>
<P>
	The risk with this strategy is that you remain heavily invested  
in a single stock. So before taking this approach, you'll want to 
consult with your financial planner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
