<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army Pilots On Trial for Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) -- A dubious report and clashing eyewitnesses  
are the weak foundation for claims that reckless flying by two Army 
helicopter pilots led to a crash that killed their wives, a defense 
lawyer says. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Doug Andrews said Tuesday that the Army based its case  
on shaky evidence, and blamed mechanical problems for the accident 
in the Bahamas. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots, Chief Warrant Officer David Guido and Chief Warrant  
Officer Daniel Riddell, are charged with 27 military crimes, 
including negligent homicide, stemming from the crash July 6 on 
Grand Exuma Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Their wives, Pam Guido and Rebecca Riddell, died when the UH-60  
Blackhawk helicopter crashed into a dense forest. They were not 
authorized to be aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Six witnesses testified Tuesday at an Article 32 hearing, which  
is similar to a civilian grand jury and will determine whether 
there is sufficient evidence to warrant a court martial. 
</P>
<P>
	One witness said the helicopter technically should have been  
grounded because it was seven months overdue for a routine weight 
check. 
</P>
<P>
	But Andrews, Riddell's lawyer, said the craft had just been  
repaired. He said the prosecution was based on a questionable 
preliminary report and testimony of two people who initially didn't 
even agree on the direction the aircraft was flying. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Warrant Officer Lee Stryker, a maintenance pilot from Fort  
Bragg, N.C., also said investigators could find no mechanical 
problems that could have contributed to the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired Lt. Col. William Bryson, who helped investigate the  
crash, testified that he believed the accident was caused by a 
``pitch-back attack,'' a maneuver that causes the helicopter to 
abruptly change directions by spinning the tail around 180 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitch-back attacks are used in combat to return quickly to a  
target or to get behind and shoot an enemy aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was not authorized for the UH-60 in that environment,''  
Bryson said. 
</P>
<P>
	A third soldier, Sgt. William Westgate, a mechanic aboard the  
helicopter, claims he suffered brain damage in the crash. His case 
would be heard separately if Army doctors decide he is competent to 
participate in his own defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
