<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Lifetime of Poking Pays Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YELLOW SPRINGS, Ohio (AP) -- Over the past 32 years, Suzanne Bosl  
has been pierced with large-bore needles, held her breath in an 
underwater tank, spit into test tubes and even endured ice-cold 
cakes of glycerin on her skin. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bosl says any discomfort was worth being part of the ``Fels  
family,'' a group of test subjects for perhaps the largest and 
longest-running study of human growth, body composition and risk 
factors or heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fels Longitudinal Study began in 1929 in this southwest Ohio  
village. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was initially funded by Samuel Fels of the Fels soap  
company in Philadelphia at the request of his friend Arthur Morgan, 
then president of Antioch College in Yellow Springs. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, about 1,200 people are in the study, most of them still  
living in southwest Ohio. Studied from birth, the first 
participants turn 70 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosl's husband was a test subject, and she became one when she  
married him because the researchers are interested in genetic 
factors. The couple's seven children and two grandchildren are also 
part of the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosl's children were examined every six months, even if  
researchers had to arrange to pick them up at their homes or pay 
air fare. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are so interested in keeping that constant data,'' said  
Bosl, 57, of Spring Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Such studies may take on increasing importance as the U.S.  
population ages. Dan Perry, executive director of Alliance for 
Aging Research in Washington, said there is a real advantage to 
having a study that goes back 70 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen percent of Americans are currently over 65, and that is  
expected to hit 20 percent in 30 years. There are 60,000 Americans 
100 years or older, a group that has been doubling in size every 10 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our society has never experienced such a large proportion of  
our people in the upper age ranges,'' Perry said. ``I think it's 
enormously important to be measuring changes in human beings as 
they age, in a systematic and scientific way. We're in uncharted 
territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fels study is funded primarily by the federal government. A  
recent $5.5 million grant from the National Institutes of Health 
will allow the research to continue for at least another five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The study initially researched the growth and development of  
children and then followed them into adulthood. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a healthy population of individuals who were identified  
at birth and studied since then,'' said Roger Siervogel, director 
of Wright State University medical school's division of human 
biology, which now conducts the study. ``It is probably the unique 
aspect. They were not selected for any specific diseases or 
anything like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 30 researchers and support staff do their work inside a  
one-story, red brick building that features state-of-the-art 
treadmills, X-ray tables that scan bones and tissue, an underwater 
tank that measures fat content and the ``Bod Pod,'' a futuristic 
cocoon that uses air pressure to check body composition. 
</P>
<P>
	The study's findings have been cited in hundreds of scientific  
journals. They have been used to: 
</P>
<P>
	-- establish growth charts used throughout the United States and  
recommended by the World Health Organization for children up to 3 
years old; 
</P>
<P>
	-- gauge the effects of smoking on pregnant women;  
</P>
<P>
	-- conclude that high cholesterol and blood pressure in children  
are likely to follow them into middle age; 
</P>
<P>
	-- develop a method to evaluate the growth of premature babies;  
</P>
<P>
	-- confirm the accuracy of using the body mass index in children  
to predict the risk of obesity later in life. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosl said she is kept informed of the study's findings through  
newsletters. She said she feels part of an important research 
effort and plans to stay in the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosl is examined by the researchers every two years. She is  
usually paid $50 for the four-hour session. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never felt as though I was a guinea pig or anything  
other than a respected participant,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Siervogel said researchers treat the test subjects well and that  
few have dropped out of the study. 
</P>
<P>
	``It cost millions of dollars just to get the data from one  
person throughout their life,'' said Siervogel. ``We don't want to 
do anything that would make them think twice about coming in the 
next time. If we lose a person, we've lost a lifetime's worth of 
data. It's not like you can go down to the supermarket and get 
somebody else to do it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
