<HEADLINE> Harvard Expels Student for Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Harvard University faculty voted to  
dismiss a student who admitted to sexually assaulting a classmate, 
as debate flared over whether the school treated a date rape case 
seriously enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Several hundred students protested outside the building where  
faculty members voted to dismiss D. Drew Douglas, a decision 
reached Tuesday evening after professors rejected a lesser 
punishment of withdrawal that would have allowed him to petition 
for readmission. 
</P>
<P>
	One demonstrator held aloft a sign that read ``Harvard coddles  
rapists but won't hold survivors' hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy it was dismissal and not withdrawal,'' said  
student Anna Baldwin, 20. ``But Harvard still has a long way to go 
in dealing with sexual violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas and the woman were friends when they spent a night  
together. The woman later complained to the college's 
administrative board, which investigated and found the 
then-sophomore had committed an act of rape. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas and the woman agreed that he assaulted her while she  
slept, according to The Boston Globe, which cited unidentified 
faculty members. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas pleaded guilty in a criminal court last year to battery  
and indecent assault, or improper sexual touching. Douglas was 
sentenced to five years probation, including 18 months under house 
arrest at home in Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas lawyer James Sultan said his client's life already has  
been devastated. ``His career at Harvard is over,'' Sultan said. 
``His name is now being dragged through the mud by people 
furthering a political agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Approximately 250 of the 650 Arts and Sciences faculty members  
voted and chose dismissal by a wide margin, said Sally Baker, a 
school spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas could be readmitted only with another vote by faculty  
and if new evidence emerged, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some students accused Harvard of failing to act swiftly in the  
case, pointing out that academic dishonesty brings dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	But several professors said considering withdrawal was  
appropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rape ... ranges from date rape to brutal assaults to gang  
rapes,'' said psychology professor Daniel Gilbert, one of five 
faculty members who proposed withdrawal. ``They are all heinous, 
but there are differences.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
