<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Charged in Arms Export Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A federal grand jury indicted two men on charges  
they tried to illegally export missile-guidance equipment to China. 
</P>
<P>
	Collin Xu, 33, also known as Collin Shu, a naturalized Canadian  
citizen who lives in Montreal, is accused of violating the Arms 
Export Control Act, conspiracy and money laundering. He faces up to 
65 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Yi Yao, 33, of Beijing, is also accused of violating the export  
act. He could face up to 10 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men, indicted Tuesday, allegedly conspired to buy  
military fiberoptic gyroscopes from a Massachusetts manufacturer 
and ship them to a Beijing firm by way of Xu's Canadian company, 
Lion Photonics Canada of Montreal, without notifying the State 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Xu's firm, along with Lion Photonics Inc. of Beijing, owned by  
Yao, also are charged with export violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Massachusetts firm was unaware of the scheme and faces no  
charges, according to the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gyroscopes can be used in navigational systems for missiles and  
aircraft guidance systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
