<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Has No Plans for Devaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's central bank governor on Thursday doused  
renewed speculation about a possible devaluation of the Chinese 
currency, saying Beijing has no plans to allow the value of the 
yuan to decline in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	There is a ``fundamental basis'' for maintaining the stability  
of the country's currency and there are no plans to explore a 
possible devaluation of the yuan, People's Bank of China Gov. Dai 
Xianglong told reporters at a press conference during the annual 
session of the national legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	Dai noted that China maintains a favorable balance of payments  
and steady export flows. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese yuan, which isn't freely convertible, is backed by  
China's approximate $149 billion in foreign exchange reserves, the 
second highest in the world behind Japan. China also recorded a 
trade surplus of $43.6 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dai rebutted a report in Thursday's edition of the Financial  
Times that cited a senior government official saying decisions to 
devalue the yuan would depend on whether China can maintain 
acceptable levels of economic growth and social stability. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Chinese authorities have long denied any devaluation is  
imminent, the caveats added to the nation's no devaluation pledge 
give the authorities more room to move, the Financial Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Chinese leaders have repeatedly stressed their belief  
that a devaluation would do more harm than good. A devaluation 
could prompt competitive devaluations elsewhere in Asia by 
countries trying to boost their export competitiveness by making 
the dollar value of their products cheaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 06:17:55 </DATE_TIME>
