<HEADLINE> Farmer Charged With Starving Herd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- A farmer who apparently was overwhelmed  
by financial problems is charged with neglecting his cows, leading 
to the deaths of 47 of them. 
</P>
<P>
	John D. Garvin, 31, of Rutland, was arrested Sunday, one day  
after state police discovered the animals had died, apparently from 
starvation. Another 33 in poor condition were turned over to 
another dairy farmer for care, state police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Garvin is charged with 80 counts of torturing, injuring or  
overdriving animals, a misdemeanor. 
</P>
<P>
	Trooper John Poggi said state police found ``an awful scene'' at  
Garvin's farm 75 miles north of Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Some dead cows had half-born calves, and many of the dead  
animals -- as well as a couple of live ones -- were frozen into two 
or three feet of manure that covered the barn floor. 
</P>
