<HEADLINE> Jurgensen Named USA Today Editor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Karen Jurgensen, a 17-year veteran of USA  
Today and editor of the editorial page, has been selected to 
succeed the retiring David Mazzarella as the newspaper's editor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Karen Jurgensen has played many important roles in helping  
develop USA Today's content since its founding in 1982 and offers 
the editing breadth and leadership skills necessary for the next 
era of the newspaper's growth,'' president and publisher Tom Curley 
said Tuesday in announcing her appointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurgensen, 50, joined the newspaper at its founding in 1982. She  
has held several editorial positions, including senior editor for 
special projects, managing editor for cover stories and editor of 
the Life section. She began her journalism career at the Charlotte 
(N.C.) News and worked later for the Miami News. 
</P>
<P>
	She announced that she will be replaced as editorial page editor  
by Brian Gallagher, 50, who has been the page's deputy editor since 
1991. Gallagher, who is the son of the late Wes Gallagher, former 
president and general manager of The Associated Press, began his 
career with Gannett's Westchester Rockland newspaper group in 1971. 
He is a former managing editor of the Gannett News Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazzarella, 60, headed USA Today's international operations  
before becoming editor in 1994. He will continue at the newspaper 
until the end of the year as senior vice president for strategic 
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
