<DOCNO> APW19990310.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Leader's Future in Question </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- When the Czech Republic joins NATO  
on Friday, a dream will come true for President Vaclav Havel. 
</P>
<P>
	The longtime advocate of NATO's eastward expansion says he  
considers the alliance's embrace of the Czech Republic, which 
enters along with Hungary and Poland, his main achievement. 
</P>
<P>
	But with that quest now behind him, the once-beloved Havel may  
be in danger of becoming an icon time left behind -- his popularity 
sinking, his health in question, his wife a target of criticism and 
his ideas increasingly out of touch with those of ordinary people. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes when I hear him talking about the new global  
responsibility or about the political climate here in our country, 
I have the feeling he lives on a different planet,'' says Jarmila 
Hlavata, 67, a retired teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts suggest the ``historic mission'' of the dissident  
playwright-turned-president, long a symbol of the fight against 
communism, may be over. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been nearly a decade since Havel was swept into office on a  
wave of adulation during the Velvet Revolution. After more than 
four decades of communism, Czechs united behind their first 
democratically elected president. 
</P>
<P>
	They adored Havel for his moral authority and rejoiced that his  
fame abroad boosted their country's image. 
</P>
<P>
	Today he remains highly respected abroad. But at home, where the  
people's revolutionary enthusiasm is long gone, his role is 
diminishing. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's popularity among Czechs, once at 82 percent,  
dropped below 50 percent for the first time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting his nation into the alliance hasn't done a thing to help  
his standing -- only half of Czechs support NATO membership. 
Opponents include diehard communists as well as people who question 
the need to join another military alliance after the collapse of 
the Warsaw Pact. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts say NATO isn't the reason for Havel's drop in  
support. 
</P>
<P>
	``Times have changed,'' Ivan Jemelka wrote in Lidove Noviny, the  
country's prominent daily. ``Citizens have started to rely more on 
themselves and they have less need for a leader, even in the good 
sense of the word.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Havel's special historical mission is probably over,'' he  
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Havel acknowledges the change.  
</P>
<P>
	``I headed the country so long, and I was revered for such a  
long time, that it had to end one day,'' he told the French daily 
Le Figaro last month. 
</P>
<P>
	But the challenge of what to do for the rest of his term, which  
ends in January 2003, may be difficult. Havel has repeatedly said 
he has no intention of becoming a ``mere wreath-layer.'' Attaining 
Czech membership in the European Union may be his next goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The constitution gives him only very limited powers, but Havel  
still is trying to implement his visions in Czech policy. Results 
are debatable. 
</P>
<P>
	His recent attempt at organizing a roundtable of parliamentary  
parties to settle political squabbles has met only partial success: 
The country's second-strongest party, the Civic Democratic Party of 
former Premier Vaclav Klaus, has not signed on. 
</P>
<P>
	Media criticism, once unthinkable, is now steady. Serious  
newspapers question his political visions; tabloids and television 
focus mainly on his private life and his wife of two years, Dagmar. 
</P>
<P>
	Havel accuses sensationalist journalists of unfair attacks on  
him and his family. But it seems the whole nation has an aversion 
to Dagmar, who he married in January 1997 -- less than a year after 
his first wife Olga died of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	While Olga kept a low profile and didn't even talk about her  
charity work, outspoken Dagmar is always visible -- and audible. She 
has even tried, unsuccessfully, to have first lady made an official 
post. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, she shocked Czechs by whistling with her fingers -- a  
particularly rude action here -- in response to an ultranationalist 
lawmaker's remarks during a nationally televised program. Her 
husband defended her, but many complained that Dagmar was no lady. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's mainly Havel's own ideas that make Czechs wonder what  
he can offer them. 
</P>
<P>
	He acknowledges his failure to improve the nation's political  
and moral climate -- his main goal after winning reelection a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this sphere, the situation did not improve, it's rather  
worse,'' Havel conceded last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
