<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:44:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MacLeod Resigns As Notre Dame Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- The question dogged John MacLeod for  
several years: When's your time going to be up? 
</P>
<P>
	The answer came Tuesday when the Notre Dame basketball coach  
resigned after just three winning seasons during his eight years at 
the school. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everything is in place for Notre Dame to make a  
positive move,'' MacLeod said. ``I appreciated the opportunity to 
work here at Notre Dame, and I wish the best for the young men who 
are part of the program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement wasn't entirely unexpected after the Irish  
dropped five of their last seven to finish 14-16 overall and eighth 
in the Big East with an 8-10 record. They were picked by conference 
coaches to finish 12th in the 13-team league. 
</P>
<P>
	Freshman David Graves, at home in Lexington, Ky., on spring  
break, said he hadn't expected the announcement and wasn't sure 
whether MacLeod was forced out. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know, because the last couple years it's always  
been, `Is he going to leave? Is he going to stay?''' he said. 
``You're not surprised, but it's kind of a shock when you finally 
hear it. You feel bad for him and his family, but we've still got 
business to take care of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Mike Wadsworth made the announcement Tuesday  
night after returning from a trip to Florida to meet with MacLeod. 
He refused to discuss the circumstances surrounding MacLeod's 
departure, insisting the coach requested that Wadsworth limit what 
he said to what was in the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	But MacLeod, 61, told The Associated Press in an interview  
Friday that he expected to be back as coach despite the team's 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes I do. I really do,'' MacLeod said Friday. ``There's  
nothing written in stone. I'm not sitting here thinking I'm not 
going to be here. I'm going on a recruiting trip tomorrow. We've 
been working our tails off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wadsworth said he hoped to have a new coach in place by the  
April 7 signing date for basketball recruits and was already 
compiling a list of potential candidates with his staff, but he 
revealed no names. 
</P>
<P>
	He said only that he wanted to find someone who was a good fit  
for Notre Dame's basketball program as well as the university's 
image. 
</P>
<P>
	``Notre Dame is a university with a particular culture that  
doesn't suit all people,'' Wadsworth said. ``As a result, we'll be 
looking for a head coach that would be someone that has the 
potential to bring us to the top level nationally, but most 
particularly would be a very good fit for Notre Dame, will come to 
Notre Dame embracing what Notre Dame stands for, and if we can find 
that kind of matchup I think we'll have a good selection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MacLeod has often been criticized for poor recruiting, but his  
last class pulled in Big East rookie of the year Troy Murphy and 
Graves, both of whom started most of the season. A third freshmen, 
Harold Swanagan, saw plenty of playing time, and the three are 
expected to be a strong nucleus for next year's team. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, six players have left the Notre Dame program the last  
three seasons for a variety of reasons, and a seventh missed most 
of the year because of academic problems. That left only one 
scholarship player on the roster from the class of 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Wadsworth said the university hasn't contacted most of the  
players, who are on spring break this week, but the staff would 
complete that this week, as well as calling recruits. 
</P>
<P>
	Graves said it wasn't likely that he would transfer, but he will  
wait for Notre Dame to name a successor before making a final 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made a commitment, and I'm going to stick to that  
commitment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	MacLeod's Notre Dame teams had a 106-124 mark, and his only  
winning years were 18-15 in 1991-92, his first at the school, 15-12 
in 1994-95 and 16-14 in 1996-97. MacLeod had the Fighting Irish in 
the NIT in 1992 and 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	He is the only coach in school history to lead the team at least  
five seasons and still register an overall losing record. 
</P>
<P>
	MacLeod arrived at Notre Dame in 1991 after 18 seasons in the  
NBA with Phoenix, Dallas and the New York Knicks. His combined 
record in the NBA was 707-657 and his teams went to the playoffs 11 
times, four reaching the conference finals. He was coach at 
Oklahoma before moving to the NBA, finishing with a 90-69 mark in 
six seasons there. 
</P>
<P>
	Notre Dame moved into the Big East for the 1995-96 season, and  
the Fighting Irish have never had a winning season in the league, 
with an overall conference mark of 27-45 and an 0-4 record in the 
Big East tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	MacLeod was selected as Big East coach of the year in 1997 and  
had players honored by the league the last two seasons, Pat Garrity 
as player of the year in 1998 and Murphy as newcomer of the year 
this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
