<DOCNO> APW19990310.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 07:17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Chided Over Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With crime down significantly nationwide,  
Attorney General Janet Reno says state and local law enforcement 
agencies do not need as much help from the federal government to 
fight lawlessness. 
</P>
<P>
	But key members of Congress think otherwise and accused the  
Clinton administration Tuesday of trying to pressure them with 
proposals to cut more than $1.4 billion from community law 
enforcement programs next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., chairman of the Senate Appropriations  
subcommittee that funds the Justice Department, contended the cuts 
were made to put the panel in the ``untenable position'' of having 
to find money elsewhere to pay for the programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's $21 billion budget request for fiscal 2000  
would eliminate a $250 million juvenile accountability block grant 
and a $523 million local law enforcement block grant, and reduce 
grants for state prisons by nearly $650 million. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the department is seeking $600 million to  
expand an existing community policing program to help states hire 
up to 50,000 additional police officers over five years. The 
program, known as COPS, is nearing its original goal of putting 
100,000 police officers on the nation's streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregg criticized the proposed cuts in programs that he says  
worked. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears to me it was done in order to put us ... in the  
untenable position of having to go out and find the money to put 
back in those programs, because you know we supported those 
programs,'' he said. ``And you've made politically attractive 
choices at the expense of this committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reno noted that crime was down significantly nationwide. The  
violent crime rate has declined by more than 20 percent over the 
past six years and the murder rate has reached its lowest level in 
three decades, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the proposed budget still includes funds for community  
law enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think state and local law enforcement should become  
too dependent on federal law enforcement, and there is a point 
where we draw the line,'' Reno said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the administration would accept a budget passed by  
Congress that included the proposed reductions, Reno signaled that 
it would. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have got to make a judgment as to how we use precious  
federal resources. And if you approve the president's budget, he'll 
sign it,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregg said the subcommittee may go along with the administration  
on cutting the programs, but he said it would not recommend 
expanding COPS. Funds intended for new officers would be spent 
elsewhere, such as on border patrols, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, criticized the  
lack of money in the budget for hiring 1,000 Border Patrol agents. 
A 1996 immigration law authorized the hiring of 5,000 border agents 
through 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still woefully short of the number of Border Patrol  
agents,'' Hutchison said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said recruiting was becoming a problem. A decision also was  
made to delay new hiring because the nearly 9,000-person force is 
largely inexperienced and needs time to develop the necessary 
expertise, she said. As of last month, nearly half of all agents 
will have been on the job for no more than three years, Reno said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
