<DOCNO> APW19990310.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:30:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Eyes Saab Buy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The head of General Motors Corp.'s European  
operations believes the No. 1 automaker's new model offensive will 
result in an increased share of the European market and higher 
profits this year even as overall sales are expected to decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael J. Burns, president of GM-Europe, said in an interview  
with The Associated Press that new Opel models, increased 
availability of diesel engines and an expanded product line of 
U.S.-built vehicles should help GM exceed last year's sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the chief executive of Saab Automobile AB said  
Tuesday at the Geneva International Motor Show that GM will begin 
talks on buying the 50 percent of Saab it doesn't already own. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit-based GM acquired half of Saab from the Swedish holding  
company Investor AB for $600 million in 1989 and has an option to 
buy the remaining half during the six months beginning July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with Dow Jones Newswires and financial cable  
network CNBC, Saab CEO Robert Hendry said talks would begin in July 
and suggested that Saab may not come cheap, given the automaker's 
recent sales gains and improving balance sheet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saab's good performance makes both parties want to keep their  
shares,'' Hendry said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM operates in Europe under the Opel, Vauxhall and Saab brands.  
It had 11.5 percent of the market in Western Europe last year, with 
sales up slightly over 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, GM's European operations earned $419 million on sales  
of $25 billion. Burns said he hopes to double earnings this year 
with increased availability of its bestseller, the redesigned Opel 
Astra subcompact, the redesigned Vectra sedan and the spring 
introduction of the new Zafira, a small minivan. 
</P>
<P>
	GM and other automakers have high hopes for the compact minivan  
market, which is about to be flooded with new entries from Asian 
automakers. GM estimates the segment will increase from 2 percent 
of the total European car market to more than 10 percent by the 
middle of the next decade. GM plans to build 200,000 Zafiras in 
2000, its first full year of production. 
</P>
<P>
	Opel also unveiled the Opel Speedster, a concept version of a  
roadster that's expected to go into production within two years. 
Hendry, who is chairman of Adam Opel AG as well as CEO of Saab, 
left open the possibility that the Speedster eventually could be 
exported to North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Hendry also said Opel was considering adding a flagship luxury  
sedan to its lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	GM, which has had little success with North American exports to  
Europe, keeps trying. In the last few weeks it began rolling out 
the Oldsmobile Alero compact, which is rebranded for the European 
market as the Chevrolet Alero. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker sold only about 13,500 Chevys and Cadillacs in  
Europe last year. While that was up sharply, it still represents a 
fraction of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something we've not done as good a job with,'' Burns  
said. ``We're making good progress, but the numbers are fairly 
small. That clearly has a lot of potential if we get the right 
product. It's all about the product.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
