<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rules on Alabama Senate Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- The partisan dispute that has paralyzed  
the Alabama Senate is still stuck in politics. 
</P>
<P>
	A Democratic judge ruled the Republican lieutenant governor  
broke the law by pushing through new Senate rules to increase his 
power. The issue now goes to the state Supreme Court -- where 
Republicans hold a 5-4 majority. 
</P>
<P>
	Circuit Judge Charles Price said Tuesday that Lt. Gov. Steve  
Windom had no right to pass the new Senate rules on a voice vote, 
over the loud objections of 18 Democratic senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Windom immediately appealed Price's ruling, saying the judge  
violated the separation of powers by weighing in on a legislative 
matter. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court agreed to hear arguments on Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	That means the Senate standoff could continue at least three  
more days, eating up more than one-third of the 30 meeting days the 
Legislature is allotted each year. 
</P>
<P>
	The battle began in November, when Windom became the first  
Republican elected lieutenant governor in Alabama this century. 
That also set him up to be presiding officer of the Senate, which 
had been controlled by the Democrats for more than 100 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alabama Constitution gives the lieutenant governor only two  
duties: presiding over the Senate and voting in case of a tie. But 
the Senate has traditionally let the lieutenant governor appoint 
Senate committees and decide which committee considers each bill. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the Democrats stripped the incoming Windom of most  
of his power in a session presided over by Gov.-elect Don 
Siegelman, a Democrat who was still lieutenant governor at the 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Windom snatched the power back on the Legislature's opening day  
by gaveling through new rules on an unrecorded voice vote while 
ignoring the shouts and shaking fists of Democrats demanding a roll 
call. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Democrats have sued Windom and boycotted the Senate.  
The standoff has prevented the Senate from considering any 
legislation, including the state budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're reaching the point of no return,'' said Siegelman's  
chief of staff, Paul Hamrick. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
