<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                  *Princess Al-Anoud bint Abdel Aziz    	
</P>
<P>
	RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Princess Al-Anoud bint Abdel Aziz,  
the first wife of King Fahd, died Monday. She was in her 70s. 
</P>
<P>
	Palace officials said the princess died in Los Angeles, where  
she was believed to have lived for the past three years while being 
treated for a disease that affected her spinal cord and kidneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Anoud and Fahd were married as teen-agers. The mother of five  
of Fahd's sons, she was the youngest sister of the wife of Saudi 
Defense Minister Prince Sultan, a brother of King Fahd. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Anoud's father was from the al-Jelawi tribe, which supported  
Fahd's father, King Abdel Aziz, at the start of a campaign in 1902 
to unite the Arabian Peninsula, which led to the formation of Saudi 
Arabia. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Adolfo Bioy Casares    	
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Adolfo Bioy Casares, an Argentine  
writer known for his use of fantasy and his collaborations with 
literary giant Jorge Luis Borges, died Monday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Bioy Casares met Borges in 1932 and began a lifelong  
collaboration. Together, they edited a literary magazine, 
``Inopportune.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His 1940 novel, ``The Invention of Morel,'' is considered his  
finest work and was translated into 19 languages. Other works also 
included ``The Dream of Heroes'' in 1954 and ``Diary of the War of 
the Pig,'' a 1969 political satire. 
</P>
<P>
	Bioy Casares and Borges wrote together under a variety of pen  
names, collaborating on a series of social satires and lampoons. 
</P>
<P>
	Bioy Casares received the Cervantes Prize in 1990, the highest  
honor bestowed by Spain on writers in the language. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Peggy Cass    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Peggy Cass, who frequently appeared on ``The  
Jack Paar Show,'' and who was a 1957 Tony winner for her portrayal 
of Agnes Gooch in ``Auntie Mame'' on Broadway, died Monday at the 
age of 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Agnes Gooch was Mame's young secretary. Ms. Cass won a Tony for  
the role on stage and was nominated for an Academy Award for the 
film musical ``Auntie Mame'' starring Rosalind Russell. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Cass made regular appearances on ``The Jack Paar Show'' in  
the late 50's and early 60's. She also a regular on the television 
quiz shows ``To Tell the Truth'' and ``Keep Talking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Movie credits included ``The Marrying Kind'' (1952), ``Gidget  
Goes Hawaiian'' (1961) and ``If It's Tuesday, This Must Be 
Belgium'' (1969). 

</P>
<P>
                          *Robert T. Conley    	
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Robert T. Conley, president of the Union  
Institute since 1982, died of a heart attack Tuesday. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Union Institute was founded in 1964 by the presidents of 10  
small colleges as the Union for Experimenting Colleges and 
Universities. 
</P>
<P>
	Students, most of whom are in their 30s and 40s, design their  
curriculum in conjunction with a faculty mentor. Students learn by 
working one-on-one with professors and communicate mainly by 
computer and phone. 
</P>
<P>
	Conley received a bachelor's in chemistry from Seton Hall  
University in 1953, and a master's (1955) and doctorate (1957) in 
chemistry from Princeton University. Before moving to Union 
Institute, he was the first lay president of Seton Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Conley has been credited with guiding the Union Institute out of  
financial difficulty, increasing its enrollment and expanding its 
facilities. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Paul L. Geibel    	
</P>
<P>
	CORTLAND, N.Y. (AP) -- Paul L. Geibel, president and treasurer of  
the Cortland Standard Printing Company, died Monday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Geibel worked for 54 years at the Cortland Standard, one of five  
independent newspapers remaining in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Muscatine, Iowa, Geibel began as an advertising  
salesman at the Standard in 1945 after serving in the Navy during 
World War II. Geibel was promoted to publisher and president in 
1973. In 1986, he handed his publishing duties to his son-in-law, 
Kevin R. Howe, but continued on as president until his death. 
</P>
<P>
	Geibel is survived by three children and six grandchildren.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Roger Rouse    	
</P>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Former light heavyweight boxer Roger Rouse  
died Sunday of Alzheimer's disease. He was 64. 
</P>
<P>
	A football standout at Anaconda and the University of Montana,  
Rouse took up boxing while recovering from a knee injury. He won a 
Golden Gloves title in 1954 at Chicago and accepted a boxing 
scholarship at Idaho State. 
</P>
<P>
	He was twice NCAA champion and became a member of the 1956  
Olympic boxing team. Rouse turned professional in 1958 and became 
the No. 1 light heavyweight contender in 1965. He fought for the 
light heavyweight championship of the world three times, losing 
once to Dick Tiger and twice to Bob Foster. 
</P>
<P>
	He was inducted into the Idaho State Hall of Fame in 1977.  
</P>
<P>
	He retired from boxing in 1972.  

</P>
<P>
                         *Herman L. Weisman    	
</P>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Herman L. Weisman, a former New  
York prosecutor who took on the likes of mobsters Lucky Luciano and 
Bugsy Siegel, died Sunday at 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Weisman was a Harvard Law graduate who won appointment to  
special posts in the New York attorney general's office. 
</P>
<P>
	He helped prosecute members of Murder Inc., a gang of contract  
killers organized by Luciano and Siegel. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in private practice, Weisman counted Eleanor Roosevelt  
among his clients. 
</P>
<P>
	He also served as president of several Zionist organizations.  

</P>
<P>
                             *Eric Wolf    	
</P>
<P>
	Irvington, N.Y. (AP) -- Eric Wolf, known as an innovative  
anthropologist who challenged established cultural assumptions, 
died of liver cancer Sunday. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf helped set trends for future anthropological work by  
drawing on archaeology, history and other fields to trace diverse 
cultural development, as in his 1959 book on Mexico, ``Sons of the 
Shaking Earth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Through books like his 1964 ``Anthropology'' and  
``Peasants''(1966) Wolf issued challenges to the established 
methods of his field. He explored cultures as they split and 
changed in order to dispel ethnic stereotypes, and studied 
nonconforming elements of given societies. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last book, ``Envisioning Power: Ideologies of Dominance  
and Crisis,'' (1999) Wolf drew parallels between the Nazi and Aztec 
rises to power. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf taught briefly at several universities including Illinois,  
Yale and Virginia, and spent nine years at the University of 
Michigan before joining City University of New York in 1971. 
</P>
</TEXT>
