<HEADLINE> Bush Abortion Stance Challenged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans lined up against the potential  
presidential candidacy of George W. Bush are challenging the Texas 
governor's stance on abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer, who is among those seeking the GOP nomination, said  
Tuesday that Bush is being far too vague. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see how a 'compassionate conservative' can be  
ambiguous about protecting unborn children,'' said Bauer. ``Clearly 
the governor hasn't thought this issue through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said Monday he would back a constitutional amendment to  
outlaw most abortions if more voters supported it. But he said, 
``America is not ready to ban abortions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As leaders, our role must be to help shape public opinion, not  
simply react to it,'' responded Bauer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., another presidential candidate, said the  
abortion issue will require concrete stances from candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe it is a moral issue and you can't tiptoe around  
moral issues,'' said smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Kennedy, national political director for Lamar Alexander's  
presidential bid, said Bush's comments illustrate his lack of 
political experience on the national level. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way he fumbled this issue indicates why he may not be  
ready to play in the big leagues of national politics,'' Kennedy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Opinsky, spokesman for Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said  
Bush's vague positions on key issues like abortion have helped keep 
him popular so far in the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
