<DOCNO> APW19990310.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 02:23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Tokyo Stock Prices Up / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen on today as Japan's  
key stock index soared to a seven month high. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell to 120.54 yen in late afternoon trading, down  
1.22 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo, and less than its late New 
York level of 121.00 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average jumped 383.30  
points, or 2.54 percent, to 15,480.00, its highest close since 
15,626.42 on August 10. It was the second day of dramatic gains. On 
Tuesday, the index climbed 317.65 points, or 2.15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally helped boost demand for the yen, traders said. After  
trading as high as 121.44 yen early today, the dollar sank to as 
low as 120.29 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market doesn't have much appetite for further (dollar)  
buying now,'' said Koichi Kubo, assistant general manager for the 
forex group at Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank in Tokyo. ``Market sentiment is 
that it is still top heavy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some investors had been betting recently that the yen could  
weaken if central bankers implemented policies designed to lower 
interest rates at a board meeting on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower Japanese interest rates would reduce the return to  
investors on everything from bank deposits to government bonds and 
could lead many of them to sell yen to move their money to 
countries where rates are higher. 
</P>
<P>
	But by today more investors doubted that the Bank of Japan would  
ease rates further, dealers said, leading the yen to rebound 
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices rose as investors welcomed Sony's  
announcement Tuesday that it would undertake aggressive 
restructuring, including cutting 17,000 jobs over four years and 
making three majority owned affiliates into fully owned 
subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony is seen as a leader among Japanese firms and its move  
fueled optimism that other Japanese companies would also become 
more aggressive about restructuring traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony's stock skyrocketed 910 yen ($7.47), or 8.3 percent to  
11,850 yen, after a rally of 8.9 percent Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overall market's sentiment has improved substantially,''  
said Masaru Arai, general manager at Ryoko Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 24.96 points, or 2.15 percent, to 1,187.47. The 
TOPIX rose 14.76 points, or 1.29 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading on the main section of the Tokyo exchange was estimated  
at 982 million shares, up sharply from 594.94 million shares 
Tuesday, and the highest since 1.251 billion shares traded last 
Sept. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising issues overwhelmed declines 900 to 302, while 112 issues  
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 131.80 yen, down  
from 132.28 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.680 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.700 percent, 
driving its price up to 100.96 yen from 100.80 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
