<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Addresses Salvador Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR (AP) -- President Clinton today promised ``justice  
and fairness'' for Central Americans under U.S. immigration laws 
but stood firm against illegal migration, saying it ``undermines 
the control of our borders.'' In a speech to El Salvador's 
legislative assembly, which aides billed as the centerpiece address 
of his four-day tour through the region, Clinton lauded El 
Salvador's rebirth from the bloody political strife of the 1980s. 

</P>
<P>
	Dole Announces Exploratory Panel  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole, the former American Red  
Cross leader who has worked in the administrations of five 
presidents, today announced she has formed an exploratory committee 
to see if she can raise enough money for a presidential bid. The 
wife of former GOP hopeful Bob Dole said she has found ``a great 
American yearning'' that she hoped to fill with a campaign for the 
White House. 

</P>
<P>
	Jordan King: Aid Will Solidify Ties  
</P>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Jordan's new king told Defense Secretary  
William Cohen today that a $200 million U.S. defense aid package 
will solidify already strong ties between the United States and 
Jordan. Cohen held a 90-minute meeting and luncheon with King 
Abdullah after wrapping up a six-nation tour of friendly Persian 
Gulf states that was notable for the absence of official 
expressions of support for the nearly daily U.S. airstrikes on 
Iraq. 

</P>
<P>
	Tear Gas Used in Ecuador Protest  
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Riot police used tear gas to break up more  
than 100 protesting workers in Ecuador's capital today, the first 
day of a nationwide strike to protest economic reforms. Unions have 
threatened to paralyze Ecuador if President Jamil Mahuad does not 
back down on reforms that have caused prices to soar and a bill now 
in Congress that calls for deep public spending cuts. 

</P>
<P>
	Prince Charles Tours Argentina  
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Prince Charles toured the local  
branch of Lloyd's of London and geared up to play polo after a 
violent protest marred his visit to Argentina. Police arrested 58 
demonstrators after an angry throng tried to march last night on 
the luxury hotel where Charles dined with President Carlos Menem. 
The visit was to be one of reconciliation with Argentina by 
Charles, the most senior member of British royalty to visit the 
country since the 1982 war for the Falklands Islands. 

</P>
<P>
	Doctors Urge More Hockey Padding  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Young hockey players should wear better neck  
and chest padding to protect against rare but catastrophic blows 
that can trigger cardiac arrest or strokes, doctors recommended 
today. Dr. Barry Maron of the Minneapolis Heart Institute said he 
knows of 12 cases over the last 15 years in which young male hockey 
players died suddenly on the ice after being struck by hockey pucks 
or fists. 

</P>
<P>
	German Sex Stores To Offer Stock  
</P>
<P>
	HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- Germany's best-known erotic shop is  
going public with a stock offering. Beata Rotermund, owner of the 
Beata Uhse sex shops, said she plans to sell shares in her 
enormously successful erotic business beginning in May or June to 
finance expansion with the goal of making it the biggest in the 
world. The deal will be handled by Commerzbank, Germany's 
third-largest. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Higher; Dow Up 65  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow industrials were  
up 65.76 to 9,759.52. NYSE advancers led decliners 1,539-1,316. The 
Nasdaq index was up 4.44 to 2,397.38. 

</P>
<P>
	Joe Torre Has Prostate Cancer  
</P>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- New York Yankees manager Joe Torre has  
prostate cancer and left the World Series champions today to 
undergo treatment. It was not immediately clear how advanced the 
disease was or how long Torre will be away. The Yankees also did 
not say who will manage in his place. Torre, who led the Yankees to 
a record 125 victories last season, will undergo treatment at Johns 
Hopkins University in Baltimore. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KATHLEEN SAMPEY  
</P>
</TEXT>
