<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Leaving Weak Sports Legacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Amateur sports fans are disappointed in the work  
of a foundation designed to bolster Atlanta's Olympic heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 2 1/2 years since the Olympics ended, the tax-exempt Georgia  
Amateur Athletics Foundation has awarded only two grants totaling 
$20,000 for youth golf programs, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution 
reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The athletic legacy for the games has basically been nil, and  
that has really been unfortunate,'' said Dennis Berkholtz, 
president of the national team handball federation, which relocated 
to Atlanta in hopes of benefiting from the city's Olympic legacy. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period, however, the foundation has spent nearly $1  
million to buy the personal Olympics memorabilia of its chairman, 
Billy Payne, who founded the organization more than 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Payne, who headed the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games,  
said the foundation has ``an admirable record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It has hosted sporting events and given grants for a multiple  
number of years,'' Payne said. ``The process was interrupted when 
the bid was accepted. Now that everybody has got a second wind, we 
are going to pick it back up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation, which hired its only staff member, executive  
director Linda Stephenson, in January 1998, is planning to open an 
Olympic museum. It has a collection of memorabilia and archived 
documents that are being held at the Atlanta History Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The two $10,000 grants were made last fall to the East Lake  
Community Foundation for its junior academy and the Friends of John 
A. White Park for First Tee for inner-city kids. 
</P>
<P>
	Both programs were connected to Payne or his board members, the  
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Payne says the foundation has been occupied with the process of  
examining the memorabilia and records, which will go into the 
museum, when it gets built. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports activists would like to see more done for athletes.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've already got a beautiful (Centennial Olympic) park, and  
I'm glad we've got it,'' said Steve Kearney, president of USA 
Badminton. ``But what is that going to do for the sports? I'd also 
like to have a gym I could play in and teach kids in. The athletes 
are the legacy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
