<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baerga: Don't Judge My Waistline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Carlos Baerga says people should scrutinize  
his performance, not his waistline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why don't they say anything to Tony Gwynn?'' says Baerga, who  
signed with the St. Louis Cardinals during the offseason. ``Why 
don't they say anything to Cecil Fielder? Why don't they say 
anything to other players? ``Let's talk about hitting, fielding, 
something like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why? Because conditioning was among the factors blamed for  
Baerga's decline in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga, listed at 5-foot-11 and 215 pounds, was a dominant  
player and a three-time All-Star with the Cleveland Indians in the 
early 1990s. During a four-year stretch from 1992-95, he topped 
.300 each season, twice drove in 100 runs and had 90 RBIs another 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Indians traded him to the New York Mets in 1996, his  
production declined rapidly. The last two seasons, he totaled 16 
homers and 105 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	His earning potential also has swooned. After finishing a $21.4  
million, six-year contract last year, he signed a $1.25 million, 
one-year contract with the Cardinals. Plus, the money is not 
guaranteed if the Cardinals don't like what they see and cut him in 
spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to see him play a little more,'' general manager  
Walt Jocketty said. ``It looks like he's going to be able to hit, 
we've just got to worry about defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga said nobody needs to worry about anything.  
</P>
<P>
	``I worked hard this winter to come back ready to take a job  
here,'' he said. ``That's why I'm here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga blamed his problems on a succession of minor injuries.  
Baerga, a switch-hitter, hit just .204 last year when batting 
right-handed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things just happened,'' he said. ``It's not bad luck. A lot of  
players go through slumps and injuries, they can take away your 
hitting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he's only 30 and compared his situation to that of Eric  
Davis, another new Cardinals player. Davis retired in 1994 because 
of a herniated disc in his back and in 1998 rebounded from colon 
cancer with a .327 average, 28 homers and 89 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``For two or three years, Eric Davis wasn't the same, and now  
he's back,'' Baerga said. ``People have to realize we're human 
beings and we go through situations. If you're strong, you can go 
up again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Baerga has no doubt he'll make it with the Cardinals,  
the team is playing it safe. There are several stopgap candidates 
in camp, including Pat Kelly, David Howard and Placido Polanco, 
while youngsters such as 1997 first-round pick Adam Kennedy 
continue to develop. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing in life is going to be given to you,'' Baerga said.  
``I know I have to work hard to get this job.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 14:35:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calcavecchia To Defend Honda Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORAL SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) -- When Mark Calcavecchia won last  
year's Honda Classic, tears welled in his eyes as his children 
rushed onto the 18th green in jubilation. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a memory he would love to relive.  
</P>
<P>
	Calcavecchia will defend his title in the tournament beginning  
Thursday at the TPC at Heron Bay. He likes his chances, even though 
he hasn't played well lately. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to the Honda,'' Calcavecchia said. ``The  
way the course is set up, it's right up my alley. They've elevated 
some tees, and the fairway bunkers are smaller.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calcavecchia, a West Palm Beach resident who attended the  
University of Florida, hopes to get his game together in his home 
state. He struggled during the PGA Tour's West Coast swing and 
faded after an opening-round 68 to a 4-over 292 at last week's 
Doral-Ryder Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been playing terrible,'' he said. ``I'm like 160th on the  
tour in putting. The greens are a lot smoother (at Honda). That 
gives me something to look forward to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calcavecchia will be part of a field that includes five of the  
world's top 10 players. Among those competing are Mark O'Meara, 
Colin Montgomerie and Nick Price. 
</P>
<P>
	One player who doesn't expect to win this week is 10-time tour  
winner Mark McCumber, who has made just one cut since 1996. But 
McCumber, recovering from a mysterious malady that caused numbness 
in his legs and left hand, was encouraged to win a team event 
Tuesday at TPC at Heron Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	McCumber split $9,000 with teammate Ben Bates.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's my first check in over a year,'' McCumber said with a  
smile. ``I have no expectations of putting it all together this 
week. I'm rusty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calcavecchia sounds more optimistic, partly because of his past  
success at Honda. He also won the event in 1987, then joined golf's 
upper echelon two years later by winning the British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	At that point, his life changed: People began paying him for  
tournament appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't pay me that much money to show up and play golf,''  
he said then. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 10 years since his British Open title, he has won six  
times. At Honda a year ago, he shot a final-round 65 to finish at 8 
under par. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having my kids run out there last year, that was one of the  
highlights of my career,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Calcavecchia stayed hot for the rest of the tour's Florida  
swing, tying for fourth at the Bay Hill Invitational in Orlando and 
taking fourth at The Players Championship in Ponte Vedra Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes this week's tournament can start a similar streak.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think I have a slight advantage coming in because I know I  
can play the course,'' he said. ``I like the greens, and I've won 
the tournament. But then again, everybody has two or three things 
they can count as advantages.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
