<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Contraceptive Sponge Brought Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Today Sponge, the most popular  
over-the-counter contraceptive for women before it was pulled off 
the market in 1995, is headed back to U.S. drugstores. 
</P>
<P>
	A newly founded New Jersey company, Allendale Pharmaceuticals  
Inc., told The Associated Press on Wednesday it has bought the 
Today Sponge from its previous manufacturer and hopes to begin 
selling it again by fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still a great need for the sponge,'' said Allendale  
chief executive Gene Detroyer. 
</P>
<P>
	He plans to formally announce the Today Sponge's return at a  
contraceptive meeting in San Francisco this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	It was good news for family planning groups.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're pleased and excited that it's coming back,'' said Susan  
Tew of the Alan Guttmacher Institute, which says there aren't 
enough contraceptive choices for American women. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women need different methods at different points in life. ...  
Certainly it's not for everyone,'' Tew cautioned. ``But those 
contraceptive sponge users loved that method'' before Today 
disappeared in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration said there was never any  
problem with the Today Sponge's safety, a position the agency 
reiterated on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, then-manufacturer Whitehall-Robins Healthcare decided  
it would cost too much to upgrade the old manufacturing plant where 
it made the sponge to meet stringent government safety rules. FDA 
inspectors were concerned about high bacteria rates they discovered 
in air and water at the factory. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite outcry by women's groups, the company quit making the  
sponge rather than upgrade the factory to solve the bacteria 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	No contraceptive sponge has been sold in the United States  
since. Women in France, Canada and a few other countries can buy 
competing sponges made abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the FDA never revoked the Today Sponge's approval,  
getting it back on the market should be a quick process, said 
Allendale co-founder Robert Staab. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home Products, parent company of Whitehall-Robins,  
confirmed Wednesday that it is notifying the FDA of the change in 
ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Allendale then must have its own sponge factory, outside  
Philadelphia, inspected for safety in order for the FDA to allow 
sales to resume. Staab said the factory already manufactures 
medicines for large U.S. drug companies in compliance with FDA 
rules, so he expects no problems with approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 116,000 American women were using Today in 1995. That's a  
small proportion of the 38 million women who used some 
contraception that year; sterilization and the pill were the No. 1 
and 2 choices then and now. 
</P>
<P>
	But Today was the most popular choice that did not require a  
doctor's visit. The only other woman-controlled nonprescription 
choices are spermicidal foams or suppositories and the female 
condom. Unlike those options, the sponge can be inserted up to 24 
hours before sex and doesn't require repeat applications for 
repeated intercourse. 
</P>
<P>
	With its low risk of side effects, the sponge was attractive to  
women who had problems with prescribed hormonal contraceptives or 
had difficulty with more complex inserted devices. 
</P>
<P>
	But its appeal was limited by a relatively high failure rate,  
about 10 percent in women who had never borne children and somewhat 
higher in women who had gone through childbirth, Tew noted. 
</P>
<P>
	The donut-shaped device, coated in the spermicide nonoxynol-9,  
is simply pushed up the vagina to cover the cervix. It has a loop 
to grasp for removal, and comes with warnings not to leave it in 
for more than 30 hours to avoid a low risk of infection. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroyer would not reveal how much his private company paid to  
buy the Today Sponge. But he noted that at Today's peak, it brought 
in about $17 million in sales a year, and said he is confident of 
recouping the investment. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 14:16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 79, Hits New High / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes shot to record highs today as oil  
stocks rose with oil prices, but concerns about earnings at 
technology companies limited the advances in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	At 4 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 79.08 at 9,772.84, surpassing its previous record close of 
9,736.08, set last Friday. The Dow is now up 6.4 percent for the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators, which lagged the blue chip market for  
most of the day, narrowed the gap late in the session. The Standard 
&AMP; Poor's 500 index also set a record, adding 7.00 to finish at 
1,286.84, above its previous record close of 1,282.73 set just last 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite ended in positive territory but was  
hampered by ongoing nervousness about technology company earnings. 
The Nasdaq added 13.07 to finish at 2,406.01, still shy of its 
all-time closing high of 2,510.09 on Feb 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were sharply higher, following reports that a Saudi  
official said the world's oil producers are close to an agreement 
to cut production to shore up prices. Oil prices had already been 
rising, pushing oil stocks higher. The Dow components were led 
higher by Chevron, up more than 3 points. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont was another big winner among Dow shares, up more than 4  
points after the company said it would issue separate stock that 
will track the performance of the life-sciences portion of the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer-related stocks sank after retailer Computer Associates  
was downgraded by Morgan Stanley, which cited concerns about softer 
near-term demand for computers, increasing competition, and a 
potential peaking of margins. Computer Associates' shares were down 
nearly 6 points near the close. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq Computer fell in leading New York Stock Exchange volume,  
and its competitor, Dell Computer, declined in leading Nasdaq 
volume. Dell dropped even after the computer maker announced that 
it had agreed with Amazon.com to offer linked Web sites and 
customized content. Amazon's shares climbed more than 6 points, 
along with other Internet-related shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks got another boost as Ralph Acampora, director of  
technical research at Prudential Securities and a well-known market 
bull, told a group of Belgian traders that U.S. equities, 
especially blue-chip Dow components, are in the ``early stages of 
another bull market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acampora said low inflation, low interest rates, the technology  
revolution and a peacetime economy are all supporting stocks, and 
the fact that blue-chip companies are leading the market means 
``the market's telling me that it wants to go up, because it's led 
by quality.'' He predicted that the Dow will climb as high as 
11,500 sometime in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Pradilla, chief investment strategist at SG Cowen  
Securities, agreed that technical factors in the market are 
favorable. He said that while investments from Japan are 
temporarily sidelined by the end of Japan's fiscal year at the end 
of this month, there is still ``tremendous'' interest on the part 
of Japanese investors in U.S. stocks and bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Interest rates in Japan are essentially zero, and there is  
tremendous interest in U.S. securities,'' Pradilla said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bullish implications of having a lot of cash on the  
sidelines is clashing with some bearish concerns as well, Pradilla 
said, namely, that stocks are very fully priced and analysts don't 
expect earnings this year to be knocked out of the park. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have this tug-of-war between very favorable liquidity in  
the background, but nobody can say stocks are undervalued,'' 
Pradilla said. ``And earnings are going to be OK, but you're going 
to get some unpleasant exposure (to earnings declines) as the year 
goes on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds were lower, with the 30-year Treasury off 13/32 at 5.56  
percent. The higher rates didn't disturb bank stocks, however. 
Citigroup shares rose. 
</P>
<P>
	According to preliminary calculations, the Dow Jones industrial  
average rose 79.08 to 9,772.84. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 7.00 to 1,286.84,and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index climbed 13.18 to 2,406.12. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,676 up, 1,344 down and 545 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 832.58 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
793.05 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 3.55 to 606.48 , and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.69 to 715.14. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies aded 1.92 to 401.12.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
