<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Ends Nissan Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- In the end, Nissan Motor Co's. mountain of debt  
apparently was too high for DaimlerChrysler AG to overcome in its 
quest to become a dominant world automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler announced Wednesday it ended talks toward  
acquiring a large stake in Japan's second-largest automaker. 
Although officials did not specify in detail what caused the talks 
to fail, Nissan's debt, estimated to be as high as $37 billion, 
clearly was an obstacle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they looked at the situation and were intimidated by  
the amount of debt they had to assume,'' said analyst Nick 
Lobaccaro of Merrill Lynch. ``And the restructuring of Nissan's 
operations would have required a lot of management time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler co-chairman Juergen Schrempp hinted that the  
management issue was a factor. The company formed in November when 
Daimler-Benz AG acquired Chrysler Corp. is still in the process of 
merging its far-flung operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have emphasized that the integration of Daimler and  
Chrysler has utmost priority in our current business activities,'' 
Schrempp said in a statement. ``We discussed our options of a 
potential partnership very openly and in a very friendly 
atmosphere, but finally decided not to pursue a participation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler spokesman Steve Rossi said at the Geneva  
International Motor Show ``a possible relationship would not be as 
quick to realize as we would have hoped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came after Schrempp met in Tokyo with Nissan  
president Yoshikazu Hanawa. DaimlerChrysler said it would neither 
buy an equity stake in Nissan nor pursue an outright purchase of 
Nissan Diesel, its commercial truck subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan released a statement saying it would consider more  
limited cooperative ties with DaimlerChrysler while continuing to 
seek another partner for a broader capital linkup. The companies' 
joint ventures in commercial and light trucks will continue. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief executive of Renault SA, meanwhile, said the French  
automaker was continuing to talk to Nissan about such a linkup. 
Louis Schweitzer said at the Geneva show that there was no deal yet 
and referred to Renault's statement of March 1, in which the 
automaker said Nissan would offer a good strategic fit. 
</P>
<P>
	Renault primarily serves the European market and is considerably  
smaller than DaimlerChrysler, but has ambitions of becoming a more 
global automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrempp had made no secret of his desire to acquire an interest  
in the big Japanese automaker to expand its global reach. Analysts 
expect DaimlerChrysler to explore other possible acquisition 
targets, such as Mitsubishi Motors Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan has been staggering under an estimated $22 billion to $37  
billion in debt, exacerbated by weak sales in its home market of 
Japan and in the United States. DaimlerChrysler was believed to 
have been seeking between 30 percent and 40 percent of Nissan. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'd have to be very cautious approaching that situation,''  
Lobaccaro said. ``There has to be some reconciliation with the 
creditors before an investor could see an up side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler, the world's fifth-largest automaker, was  
considering Nissan as a way to strengthen its position against the 
larger General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co., Toyota Motor Corp. and 
Volkswagen AG, which have broader stakes in Asian markets. 
</P>
<P>
	What happens next for Nissan is unclear, said Lincoln C.  
Merrihew, an analyst with DRI/McGraw-Hill. He said there might be 
deals that Nissan turned down while still negotiating with 
DaimlerChrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any potential buyer is going to have to wonder what  
DaimlerChrysler saw that made them not want to go forward,'' he 
said. ``Then their next question is whether DaimlerChrysler's 
interpretation was incorrect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Merrihew said a Renault merger or buyout would go with  
conventional industry wisdom that good deals happen between 
companies with as little overlap in products and geography as 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``Renault might make sense geographically,'' he said. ``A lot of  
European brands would like to be in America right now. It's a 
large, stable market, and the only one.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 12:35:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Sends Steel Bill to House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House committee, under pressure to respond  
to a surge in steel imports, sent a quota bill to the full House on 
Wednesday even though a majority of the panel members opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means Committee reported the bill ``adversely'' on  
a voice vote, meaning a majority of its members opposed the measure 
but agreed to let the House consider it. A vote by the full House 
is expected as early as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure is likely to draw considerable support from  
steel-state Republicans eager to help struggling steelworkers who 
believe import limits are needed to prevent additional U.S. 
layoffs. But the bill faces a troubled future in the Senate and 
with the administration, which threatened a veto Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the move was a win for the steel industry, the  
committee debate -- and its unfavorable recommendation -- highlighted 
rifts within Congress about how best to tackle the increase in 
imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Even some Democrats who agreed that the steel industry needed  
legislative help believe the quota measure goes too far and would 
violate international trade agreements, as established under the 
World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot seek to use the WTO to enforce international rules  
of law regarding trade, as we currently are in many cases, while at 
the same time advancing a proposal which is clearly in violation of 
those rules,'' said Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich., ranking Democrat on 
the Ways and Means trade subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO recently ruled against the European Union regarding U.S.  
complaints involving bananas and beef from cattle that use growth 
hormone. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics also argue that quotas could lead to market distortions,  
shortages of certain types of steel and increased prices, hurting 
steel consumers in the automobile, appliance and construction 
industries. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Phil English, R-Pa., a supporter of the bill, said  
strong sanctions are needed to ``send a strong message to the 
international community that Congress is not willing to roll over 
and be a patsy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House leaders urged the committee's chairman, Rep. Bill Archer,  
R-Texas, to report the bill out unfavorably because of fears that 
its supporters would use parliamentary tactics to force a vote 
anyhow and disrupt normal procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would limit foreign-made steel imports to their  
pre-July 1997 levels, before worldwide conditions began changing to 
boost imports dramatically. The measure also would set up an import 
notification system to improve tracking of shipments into the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of layoffs and bankruptcies at three U.S. steel  
companies have been blamed on the import surge. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is considering steel tariffs of as much as 71  
percent against Japan and Brazil after issuing a preliminary ruling 
in favor of the domestic industry's complaints that those countries 
have dumped steel in U.S. markets at prices below production costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 14:07:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vicar Favored for Florida Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Carl Nafzger listened closely as owners,  
trainers and jockeys discussed what it would take for an upset in 
Saturday's Florida Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	As the trainer of Vicar, the 3-1 morning-line favorite for the  
$750,000 race at Gulfstream Park, Nafzger shook his head and 
smiled. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone's talking about a surprise,'' Nafzger said at  
Wednesday's post position draw. ``I hope to heck there are no 
surprises.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were a few on Wednesday, though, as a larger-than-expected  
field of 11 3-tear-olds were entered in the 1 1-8 mile Florida 
Derby. Among them was the impressive filly Three Ring, who then 
drew an unfavorable outside post and may be withdrawn later in the 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The No. 10 post position didn't enhance our cause,'' trainer  
Edward Plesa Jr., said a day after declaring his filly would run 
only if she drew an inside post. ``I'm not going to say now that 
we're not going to run. I will consult with the owner, assess the 
field and then decide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No filly has won the Florida Derby. Three Ring, with four wins  
in seven career starts, is coming off a 14 3-4-length romp in the 
Davona Dale on Feb. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Other last-minute entries were long shots First American and  
Casanova Star. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar will be in familiar company Saturday as five of the horses  
he beat in the Fountain of Youth on Feb. 20 are back for another 
shot at the Wild Again colt owned by James Tafel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, who lost by a neck in the Fountain of Youth, leads  
the charge, which includes Certain (third), Grits'N Hard Toast 
(fourth), Casanova Star (eighth) and Aly's Alley (ninth). 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Marquard, breeder and owner of Aly's Alley, expects his  
colt to run much better than he did three weeks ago, especially 
after drawing the No. 11 post . 
</P>
<P>
	``He was too anxious after being off for 3 1/2 months,'' Marquard  
said. ``He seems to do better from the outside, so we hope to give 
you all a pleasant surprise .'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aly's Alley left from the No. 13 post when he finished second in  
the Breeders' Cup Juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	After Vicar rebounded from his fifth-place finish in the Holy  
Bull on Jan. 16 to take the Fountain of Youth, Derby fever gripped 
Nafzger once again. In 1990, he trained Kentucky Derby winner 
Unbridled, who won the Florida Derby leading up to his win at 
Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We couldn't be happier with him'' Nafzger said. ``He just  
keeps getting better. I saw what I wanted to see in his last work. 
We wanted him to relax and listen to his rider. He's a pretty happy 
horse right now. I think we have something special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shane Sellers will be aboard Vicar for the third straight race,  
and he's seen a great deal of improvement. In the Holy Bull, Vicar 
was held off the pace and didn't respond well, but he grabbed the 
lead in the Fountain of Youth and held off Cat Thief. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just want to keep him relaxed,'' Sellers said. ``If he's  
comfortable on the lead, OK. If not, I'd rather be on the outside 
staking a horse or two and being in control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Derby is just one of several Derby preps at three  
tracks this weekend, with trainer Bob Baffert's brigade of horses 
set to run in California and Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Baffert sends out current Derby favorite Exploit  
and Prime Timber in the San Felipe at Santa Anita and the filly 
Silverbulletday in the Fair Grounds Oaks; on Sunday, he's got 
Answer Lively -- the 2-year-old champion -- and General Challenge in 
the Louisiana Derby and the filly Excellent Meeting in the Santa 
Anita Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert nearly captured the Triple Crown the last two years,  
winning the Derby and Preakness with Silver Charm in 1997 and with 
Real Quiet in the 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Derby field, from the rail out, with jockeys and  
odds: Valid Trefaire (Jose Santos, 15-1); Cat Thief (Pat Day, 4-1); 
Certain (Kent Desormeaux, 6-1); Adonis (Jorge Chavez, 10-1); Vicar 
(Sellers, 3-1); Casanova Star (Mike Smith, 20-1); Wondertross (8-1, 
Jerry Bailey); Grits'N Hard Toast (Robbie Davis, 8-1); First 
American (Jose Velez, 20-1); Three Ring (John Velasquez, 5-1); and 
Aly's Alley (Edgar Prado, 15-1). 
</P>
