<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scouts Check Out Royals' Appier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAINES CITY, Fla. (AP) -- They're checking out Kevin Appier the  
way a careful buyer studies a used car. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Mets were there Wednesday, kicking his tires so to  
speak. So were the Houston Astros, and the Baltimore Orioles, and 
the Boston Red Sox and the Texas Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Altogether, a dozen major league teams had scouts watching  
Wednesday, paying very close attention to the one-time ace 
right-hander who is coming off shoulder surgery and is very much 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	In his second impressive start of the spring, the 31-year-old  
right-hander allowed one hit in three shutout innings against the 
Los Angeles Dodgers, striking out two and giving every indication 
he's fully recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of batters did make solid contact. Gary Sheffield sent  
center fielder Carlos Beltran almost to the wall in the first 
inning and Angel Pena hit a pretty good shot to left in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	But all in all, it was a very good audition for Appier, whose  
$4.8 million salary the cash-strapped Royals are eager to unload. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two guys hit balls hard, but I'm a little bit ahead of where  
I'd usually be at this time because instead of just refining my arm 
speed, just getting it back,'' said Appier, a notoriously slow 
starter in the spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to actually create arm speed this year, so I'm a little  
further along on endurance. I think I'll probably gain some 
velocity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In five innings this spring, Appier has given up just two hits  
and one walk. 
</P>
<P>
	The shoulder, injured during a fall after the 1997 season, is  
pain free. He underwent the surgery almost exactly a year ago and 
made just three appearances with the major league club in 
September. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels better than it has in years,'' he said. ``I threw the  
slider for the first time today and it felt pretty good. I was 
keeping the ball down better. I had better control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia, Cleveland, Toronto, Anaheim, Pittsburgh, Oakland  
and the Los Angeles Dodgers were among those who sent scouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Appier was Kansas City's opening day starter from 1991-97 and  
ranks among the club's career top 10 with 105 wins, a 3.34 ERA, 247 
starts, 31 complete games and 10 shutouts. His 1,373 strikeouts are 
the club record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I'll get traded because all the rumors are out  
there,'' Appier said. ``But there's a possibility of not being 
traded because I've heard things aren't progressing. I've heard a 
lot of different things. I might go. I might stay.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
