<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:48:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Check Out Exxon-Mobil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission will closely  
examine the Exxon-Mobil oil merger, especially how it will affect 
competition in the Northeast, Gulf Coast region and California, a 
senior commission official said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Exxon and Mobil face each other at just about every level of  
the industry ... in many parts of the country,'' especially in 
those regions, William Baer, director of competition at the FTC, 
told a congressional hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously a transaction of this size alone merits our close  
attention,'' said Baer. 
</P>
<P>
	Exxon agreed in December to acquire Fairfax, Va.-based Mobil for  
$73.7 billion in stock, combining the biggest U.S. oil companies 
and reuniting two of the biggest pieces left by the 1911 government 
breakup of John D. Rockefeller's Standard Oil empire. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal still awaits government approval, and federal  
regulatory agencies -- the FTC as well as the Securities and 
Exchange Commission -- testified Wednesday before the House Commerce 
energy and power subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that the oil industry is rapidly consolidating, Rep. Tom  
Bliley, R-Va., the Commerce panel chairman, said, ``It is important 
that we take a look at these mergers -- what is driving them and how 
they will impact consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee was scheduled to hear from the chairmen of both  
Exxon and Mobil on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Baer said that the FTC's investigation ``is still at an early  
stage'' and no conclusions have been reached on the effects of the 
merger on competition or whether it would violate any antitrust 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the focus of potential competitive problems will be  
in the Northeast, the Gulf Coast and California where the two 
companies go head-to-head in refining and retail sales at gasoline 
stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Hakes, head of the federal Energy Information  
Administration, told the subcommittee that the two oil giants 
overlap in marketing and refinery operations, especially in the 
Gulf Coast region. 
</P>
<P>
	``While Exxon and Mobil account for less than 12 percent of U.S.  
(refining) capacity, they control 18 percent of the Gulf Coast 
capacity,'' said Hakes. That's comparable to the BP-Amoco refining 
capacity in the Midwest, a merger that has been approved, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In retail marketing, the two companies ``have the largest  
overlap in ... the Northeast,'' said Hakes. The two companies 
control more than 15 percent of the branded retail gasoline 
stations in Northeastern states, he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
