<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 19:42:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Halfway House Inmates Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Law enforcement officials cannot find about  
180 people who have walked away from halfway houses in the nation's 
capital over the past 14 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics from the office of the District of Columbia Trustee  
for Court Services and Offender Supervision show about 50 of the 
escapees were convicted criminals ordered to live in halfway houses 
as part of their sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	The other 132 escapees were awaiting trial on various charges  
when they walked away. Many are accused of committing violent 
crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	The district's six halfway houses can accommodate a total of 546  
people at any given time. Five of them are run by private 
companies. District officials operate just one. 
</P>
<P>
	A recently formed task force consisting of Justice Department  
officials and local leaders is studying halfway house escapes in 
the district and trying to come up with solutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Chief Judge Eugene Hamilton, appearing before the  
district's city council Wednesday, called the facilities absolutely 
essential'' to the criminal justice system. 
</P>
<P>
	``These halfway houses have to be administered and supervised  
and run in an orderly manner,'' he said. ``That just has not been 
the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some officials insisted that the problem is rooted in the court  
system. More than two-thirds of the escapees had been sent to the 
halfway houses while awaiting trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 23:42:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Chief Calls `Fearful' Sponsors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The bosses of the biggest sponsors of the  
Olympics have been getting a sales pitch from the embattled boss of 
the games. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch, in an unusual move to gain  
support for the scandal-scarred International Olympic Committee, 
has called the chairmen and CEOs of several top-level corporate 
backers to pledge reforms in the wake of the Salt Lake bribery 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	``He initiated the call to our vice chairman, John Alden, and we  
expressed our concerns,'' said UPS spokeswoman Susan Rosenberg, 
among the marketing officials who confirmed the exchanges 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she did not know of any similar calls since UPS became  
an Olympic sponsor in the summer of 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Another official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said  
Samaranch made the calls ``just to discuss the situation 
tete-a-tete'' with the top decision-makers of $50 million sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was made to allay fears'' that the IOC is not committed to  
changes in its membership and operations, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one more IOC member is expected to be expelled as an  
internal investigation of alleged wrongdoing in Salt Lake City's 
winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games moves slowly toward a 
conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	Seiuli Paul Wallwork of Western Samoa, an IOC member since 1987,  
will be ousted under the recommendation of the six-man panel, 
Olympic sources familiar with the case told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, also said  
that a few of the 19 IOC members still under investigation in the 
Salt Lake City case would be exonerated. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallwork, never in a leadership position in the IOC, was named  
in a Utah ethics report last month that said his wife, Julia, 
borrowed $30,000 from Salt Lake City bid chief Tom Welch ``to help 
a friend in a serious situation.'' The report said the money, 
withdrawn by Welch from his children's' trust fund, was repaid. 
</P>
<P>
	The expected expulsion of Wallwork was reported Wednesday by the  
Chicago Tribune and confirmed by sources to the AP. At least two 
international newsletters that report on the Olympics also said 
Wallwork would be expelled. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC commission, headed by vice president Dick Pound of  
Canada, was still working on its report Wednesday, and it was 
uncertain when it would make its recommendations to the ruling 
executive board. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound was unavailable for comment, with telephone messages left  
at his Montreal office not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	But another commission member, Jacques Rogge of Belgium, said  
the report might not come until next Monday, when the executive 
board meets in Lausanne, Switzerland, prior to a special IOC 
general assembly dealing with the Olympics' worst corruption 
scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pound commission's initial phase ended in January, with nine  
members expelled or resigning and another three under 
investigation, including South Korean executive board member Kim 
Un-yong, the highest ranking IOC delegate implicated so far. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no word on whether the commission has decided Kim's  
fate on allegations that he used Olympic connections to help secure 
lucrative jobs for his children in broadcasting and entertainment . 
</P>
<P>
	Another high-profile case, meanwhile, appeared to be headed for  
no more than a warning. 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Coles, an IOC member from Australia, was expected to be  
censured for accepting travel to ski resorts and the Super Bowl, 
the Olympic sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	The marketing officials said Samaranch took the initiative to  
call sponsors over the last two weeks as he prepared for an 
extraordinary IOC general assembly to deal with the scandal, which 
has rocked the world's biggest sports event. 
</P>
<P>
	The calls were upbeat and filled with pledges to clean up the  
corruption and never let it happen again, according to the 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those called was M. Douglas Ivester, chairman and CEO of  
he Coca-Cola Co., one of the IOC's oldest sponsors. Ivester told 
Samaranch that the IOC must ``modernize'' its organization. 
</P>
<P>
	If was not known if Samaranch called John Hancock president  
David D'Alessandro, his most public critic among the leaders of 11 
corporations in The Olympic Program, the highest level of 
sponsorship of the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Word of Samaranch's phone calls came as The Wall Street Journal  
reported that some sponsors were making contingency plans in case 
the IOC failed to make major changes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal said the plans included scaled-backed Olympic ads,  
replacing the Olympics with sponsorship of other sports and 
possible legal action against the IOC. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
