<DOCNO> APW19990310.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Slick Floor Delays Suns-Mavs Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas-Phoenix NBA game was delayed 70 minutes  
Tuesday night because of a mysterious substance that made the 
Reunion Arena floor slick. 
</P>
<P>
	Suns and Mavericks players warmed up four times while workers  
feverishly mopped the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Mavs public relations director Tony Fay said the floor became  
slick ``because of a solvent dropped on it while it was stored 
after Sunday's Dallas Stars hockey game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a joke,'' said center Chris Anstey of the Mavericks.  
``There was one spot they couldn't get up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mavericks president Terdema Ussery said postponing the game was  
no option. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had to play tonight,'' he said. ``There was no date left  
where it could be made up. It's impossible because of the schedule. 
We had to play this game even it was midnight. We just wanted to 
make sure it was safe for the players. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a film on the floor and it wasn't condensation,''  
Ussery added. ``I walked on the floor and almost fell down. Part of 
the problem is that the players were stepping in the compound and 
tracking it around. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a strange one. We don't know what happened. Believe me  
we are looking into it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix players used rubbing alcohol to clean the bottom of  
their shoes. The Mavericks just changed shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ussery added ``there's a possibility we could be fined by the  
league office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team announced that each fan at the game would be given two  
free tickets for a future contest. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been problems with the Reunion Arena floor before. In  
October, 1984 a Mavs preseason game with Philadelphia was canceled 
because of bad footing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
