<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibit Examines Id, Ego of Shoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pinched and pointed. Flat or phat.  
</P>
<P>
	Women who choose plain pumps or techno urban sneakers are doing  
more than just expressing their fashion sense. They're baring their 
souls, or is it soles? 
</P>
<P>
	``Shoes are one indication of your personality and your mood,''  
says Valerie Steele, author and curator of the Fashion Institute of 
Technology's exhibit, ``Shoes: A Lexicon of Style.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 160 pairs of designer and name brand shoes gathered by  
Steele and co-curator Laird Borrelli at The Museum at FIT examines 
``the social psychology of women's shoes'' and will amuse any woman 
who has ever squeezed her square feet into pointed pumps or 
teetered on stiletto heels. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoes are ``like music,'' says Steele. ``What you wear creates a  
sort of mood or evokes a specific set of associations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So let us delve into the id and ego of shoes.  

</P>
<P>
	HIGH HEELS: ``They have considerable symbolism as a sign of  
femininity and fashion, of sexiness and status,'' Steele says. 
They're also bunion makers and back breakers, according to 
podiatrists and chiropractors. 
</P>
<P>
	But Borrelli, whose favorites on display are a pair of  
fire-engine red Gucci's with five-inch stiletto heels, says women 
have always suffered in the name of fashion -- and for good reason. 
</P>
<P>
	``They make our legs look better.'' Besides, the twentysomething  
woman adds, ``If you have a date, you're NOT thinking about 
bunions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stiletto section, which includes fetish shoes with  
seven-inch heels and many, many straps, is particularly 
interesting, says Steele. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're fascinating. On the one hand they're very girlie. I  
mean, they're ultra-feminine,'' Steele says. ``On the other hand 
they're quite fierce looking. After all they're named after a kind 
of dagger.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOOTS: or ``power footwear for the fashion commando.''  
</P>
<P>
	``They tend to be identified with images of people who are  
powerful,'' Steele says. Boots are both aggressive and defensive, 
and when designers add accoutrements like four-inch heels and 
zebra-fur, ``women get the added feeling of sexual power.'' Think 
Amazon warrior princess in high-heeled jackboots. 
</P>
<P>
                            	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANDALS: Strappy or flat, well-heeled or sparkling, sandals have  
been equated with nakedness since the dawn of time. Steele says 
they fell out of favor in prudish medieval times but reappeared in 
the 1920s and became a favorite of groups like the suffragettes. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then sandals have largely been associated with leftist,  
progressive-thinking types. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are some sandals that give a totally different image,  
like the pair in the exhibit covered in what looks like jagged 
pieces of barbed wire. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't you love them! Aren't they savage looking?'' Steele  
coos. ``But look, it's just plastic!' 
</P>
<P>
	OK .... On to sneakers.  
</P>
<P>
                            	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	SNEAKERS: Fans tend to fall into three categories.  
</P>
<P>
	Techno urban warriors (i.e. pierced, skateboarding kids) favor  
``big, clunky, outrageous-looking platform sneakers.'' They are 
different from sports people, who have a pump-up-the-sneaker, `what 
have you done for us lately' mindset, Steele says. 
</P>
<P>
	Both have views that differ vastly from the third,  
back-to-basics, group called anti-techs, who live by the motto that 
picking out a sneaker should not be harder than programming a VCR. 
``They're the `I can't take it anymore so I'm going back to my 
plain white Converse or Keds' people,'' Steele says. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SEX AND SHOES: Why say anything more? Oh, all right.  
</P>
<P>
	This group shows how masculine styles like oxfords and loafers  
have pirouetted over the years into women's closets. 
</P>
<P>
	But Steele is quick to point out that many styles we think of as  
being feminine were also once worn by men. Remember the official 
portrait of France's funky Sun King, Louis XIV, wearing his red 
high-heeled shoes? 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Steele, a cultural historian specializing in fashion, believes  
the exhibit will interest any woman with ... feet. ``Studies have 
shown that a majority of women are unusually interested in shoes.'' 
She says the average woman owns 12 pairs of shoes while those on 
the Imelda Marcos end of the shoe horn have anywhere from 100 to 
200 pairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Steele is the author of several fashion books including a  
companion book, ``Shoes: A Lexicon of Style'' (Rizzoli, $40), 
published to coincide with the exhibit. She claims she's on the 
modest end of the scale with about 50 pairs of designer shoes in 
her closet. 
</P>
<P>
	Borrelli is clearly a shoe enthusiast.  
</P>
<P>
	``Shoes are delightful as objects,'' Borrelli sighs. ``They're  
precious. You only need to pick up a shoe, hold it, try it on. ... 
I mean, we've all gone into Saks and put on stilettos or a pair of 
shoes that we couldn't afford or would never really wear and 
discovered that for five minutes you can be someone else. Right?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ahem.  
</P>
<P>
	Reminded that not ALL women are slaves to their soles, the shoe  
mavens were offered proof of anti-shoeites among us. 
</P>
<P>
	The first piece of evidence produced was a grubby, olive green  
flat that had been resoled three times. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh my! Oh my! What a sad shoe!' Steele exclaimed, producing an  
audible gasp. Borrelli tried to be kinder. ``It looks like an old 
friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The owner ``must feel safe and secure in them,'' Steele said,  
her hands still clasped in amazement to the sides of her face. 
</P>
<P>
	Next came a pink-and-white striped sneaker with polka dot trim.  
</P>
<P>
	``If this is an adult person, I think she needs help,'' Steele  
clucked. Again, Borrelli tried to rationalize. ``They could work in 
a country garden setting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Never, says Steele, vehemently shaking her head. ``It's  
sub-Laura Ashley.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly swiveling in her chair, Steele blurted, ``They're not  
yours are they?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit, which is free to the public, runs through April 17.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
