<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Reps. Eye Mack's Senate Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican Sen. Connie Mack's decision to  
retire after two terms has triggered an explosion of interest among 
members of the Florida House delegation in both parties, raising 
the prospect of a free-for-all election next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those taking a look at a race for Mack's Senate seat are  
Republican Reps. Bill McCollum, Mark Foley and Joe Scarborough. 
Veteran Rep. Porter Goss hasn't ruled out making a bid. Nor has 
Rep. Charles Canady, who sounds more reluctant than the others, 
even though he had decided to leave the House at the end of the 
term. 
</P>
<P>
	Among House Democrats, Reps. Peter Deutsch, Bob Wexler and Jim  
Davis have all expressed interest in running. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Democratic Rep. Bill Nelson, now state insurance  
commissioner, has also been mentioned as a potential contender. 
Among Republicans, Charlie Crist, who lost to Sen. Bob Graham in 
1998, is viewed as a potential contender. 
</P>
<P>
	There's an added dynamic in Florida that could cause the field  
of candidates to swell even further: More than 60 members of the 
Legislature are term-limited and cannot seek re-election in 2000, 
meaning there's a significant population of politicians looking for 
new offices to run for. One of them, state Senate President Toni 
Jennings, has been mentioned as a potential contender for the 
Senate seat Mack is giving up. 
</P>
<P>
	It's likely that the field will be winnowed considerably before  
next year's filing deadline, and some House members will opt for 
relatively easy re-election campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a $5 million entry fee for the primary,'' says Foley,  
remarking on the cost of campaigning in a state with more than a 
million primary voters and five or six distinct television markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, says Scarborough, ``it's going to be chaos in Florida.''  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Mack is the first Republican to announce plans to retire rather  
than run again next year, although two other GOP senators haven't 
yet made their plans known. One is John Chafee, 76, a moderate from 
Rhode Island. If he runs, he'd be a solid bet for re-election. 
Democrats are talking up Secretary of State James Langevin, 34, in 
a wheelchair since a gun accident that occurred when he was a 
teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	If Chafee retires, though, Democrats would have a strong chance  
of picking up a seat in a state with a strong Democratic tradition. 
Langevin aside, second-term Democratic Rep. Bob Weygand is all but 
certain to run if Chafee retires. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bill Roth, R-Del., chairman of the tax-writing Finance  
Committee, has also been quiet about his electoral plans. At 77, 
he's completing a fifth term. Democrats have been courting Gov. Tom 
Carper, a former House member, to run. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Republicans hold a 55-45 majority in the current Senate,  
and must defend 19 of the 33 seats on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats were stunned recently when two veteran senators,  
New Jersey's Frank Lautenberg and Nevada's Richard Bryan, announced 
plans to retire. They quickly contacted other Democratic senators -- 
Virginia's Chuck Robb, New Mexico's Jeff Bingaman and Wisconsin's 
Herb Kohl among them -- to make sure there weren't additional 
surprises in store. All three offered reassurances they intend to 
run for new terms, according to party sources. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	House Democrats are courting Mark Shriver, a member of the  
Maryland Legislature with an impressive political pedigree, to 
challenge GOP. Rep. Connie Morella in a congressional district in 
suburban Washington, D.C. Shriver's uncle is Sen. Edward M. 
Kennedy, D-Mass., and a cousin, Rep. Patrick Kennedy of Rhode 
Island, is chairman of the House Democratic campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Shriver had lunch with his cousin recently at a Capitol Hill  
restaurant and said in a brief interview the two talked ``about 
life and the meaning of life.'' Shriver added he was ``having 
conversations with people but I don't have it (making a 
congressional race) on my agenda right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the lunch, Shriver has met with Democratic  
officials who are hoping to engineer the takeover of the House in 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Kennedy said, ``It goes without saying we're very  
interested in having a strong candidate run in that race,'' and 
said he intends to talk with other potential contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	That includes Ralph Neas, a former civil rights lobbyist who  
lost to Morella in 1998 and plans to run again. Kennedy said he 
doesn't intend to unfairly favor his relative in fielding a 
candidate in the district. But other Democrats, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity, said they believe Shriver is better 
positioned to make a strong challenge to Morella. 
</P>
<P>
	Morella, one of the most moderate Republicans in the House, has  
triumphed by substantial margins since her first relatively narrow 
election in 1986. Her name has come up as a potential contender for 
the Senate in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
