<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA To Fix Hubble Telescope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Astronauts will rush to the Hubble  
Space Telescope this fall -- eight months early -- to fix its 
deteriorating pointing system. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA approved the emergency repair mission on Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are one failure away from losing all science on the Hubble  
Space Telescope,'' said Ed Weiler, head of NASA's space science 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	By splitting the originally planned June 2000 mission into two  
parts -- one in October and the other in late 2000 or early 2001 -- 
Hubble's science program hopefully will be preserved and the 
astronauts' chores will be more manageable, Weiler said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we had waited until June 2000, there is a very reasonable  
chance that we could lose three, four or even more months of 
science,'' Weiler said. ``This is a rather good insurance policy 
we're buying here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The extra mission will cost NASA $75 million more than what's  
already been budgeted. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Hubble's six gyroscopes, needed for pointing and  
stability, have failed since astronauts' last service call, in 
1997. And a third gyroscope suffered a partial breakdown a month or 
two ago and is considered unreliable. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronomers need at least three perfect gyroscopes to conduct  
observations throughout the universe. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the $2 billion telescope would be safe in orbit without  
any working gyroscopes, NASA does not want to risk losing any 
valuable science time. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a so-called spacecraft emergency where we're in  
danger of losing the entire mission or the entire spacecraft,'' 
Weiler said. ``You can think of it more as a science emergency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hubble -- NASA's so-called crown jewel of observatories -- was  
launched in 1990 with a misshapen mirror. Spacewalking astronauts 
corrected the telescope's vision in 1993, restoring Hubble to a 
world-class instrument able to see to the fringes of the universe, 
and returned in 1997 to add or replace 11 major parts. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides replacing all six gyroscopes in October, spacewalking  
astronauts will install a new computer, radio transmitter, guidance 
sensor and data recorder, and fix peeling insulation. 
</P>
<P>
	During their second visit, the same astronauts will equip Hubble  
with new solar panels, an advanced camera and a newfangled cooling 
unit for an infrared camera that has run out of the frozen nitrogen 
needed for observations. 
</P>
<P>
	The four astronauts who will do the repairs have been training  
since last summer and can easily accommodate the early flight, 
officials said. One of the four worked on Hubble in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA will have to rearrange the shuttle flight schedule to  
squeeze in the Hubble mission. Those details have yet to be worked 
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 14:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs ATM Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Banking Committee, tapping into  
consumer anger, overwhelmingly approved a measure that would 
require ATM surcharges to be disclosed clearly at teller machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel voted, 48-1 on Wednesday, to attach the measure to  
sweeping legislation it was drafting that would remove 
Depression-era barriers between banks, securities firms and 
insurance companies by letting them merge. 
</P>
<P>
	A consumer activist, meanwhile, criticized a closed-door meeting  
Tuesday between Senate Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, 
R-Texas, and lobbyists from the three industries. Gramm discussed 
with the industry representatives how they could lobby senators on 
his financial overhaul bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too bad he doesn't call us in, to get the consumer  
perspective across to him,'' said Mary Griffin, insurance counsel 
for Consumers Union. ``We wish we had that kind of access.'' She 
criticized the bill's lack of a provision that would require banks 
to provide low-cost, ``no frills'' checking accounts for people of 
modest means. 
</P>
<P>
	Christi Harlan, a spokeswoman for Gramm, said, ``He got together  
with the people who care deeply about financial services 
modernization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sole dissenting vote in the House banking panel came from  
Rep. Judy Biggert, R-Ill., who said banks could police themselves 
sufficiently in operating automated teller machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The ATM surcharge measure, sponsored by committee Chairman Jim  
Leach, R-Iowa, and its senior Democrat, Rep. John LaFalce of New 
York, was a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	It would require clear disclosure of the surcharges, which come  
on top of charges by customers' own banks for using a machine 
operated by another bank. The double charges would have to be 
posted on the ATMs and on the terminal screen after consumers log 
in. Consumers would have to be given the chance to terminate their 
transaction before paying the surcharge. 
</P>
<P>
	Many banks already do those things voluntarily.  
</P>
<P>
	But surveys by the consumer organization U.S. Public Interest  
Research Group indicate that 10 percent to 15 percent of ATMs 
nationwide do not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 11:35:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	March 10  
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles Times, on moviemakers and copycat crimes:  
</P>
<P>
	For 15 years or more, crime victims and their families have  
brought lawsuits seeking to hold filmmakers or television networks 
liable for copycat crimes -- acts of violence possibly inspired by 
violence on the screen. Each of those lawsuits ultimately failed, 
and for good reason. The 1st Amendment's guarantee of free speech 
is properly broad, and the Supreme Court has permitted restrictions 
only when speech is intended to incite or produce lawless action. 
</P>
<P>
	So it is disappointing that the court ruled Monday that a  
lawsuit against director Oliver Stone for his film ``Natural Born 
Killers'' can go forward. Stone, Time Warner and others involved in 
making the 1994 movie were sued by the relatives of Patsy Byers, a 
convenience store clerk in rural Louisiana who was shot and 
seriously wounded in March 1995. She died later of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony at trial brought out that the shooter and her  
accomplice had watched a videotape of Stone's movie time and again 
before shooting Byers. They subsequently committed a killing and 
were convicted. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, personally provocative, is surely a tempting target. His  
movies, including ``Platoon'' and ``Natural Born Killers'' are 
unabashed in their depiction of bloody, senseless violence. ... But 
to hold him and those associated with him legally responsible for 
the acts that others commit makes about as much sense as excusing a 
murder defendant on the ground that his mental capacity was 
diminished because he ate too many Twinkies. 

</P>
<P>
	March 6  
</P>
<P>
	Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal, on former Justice Harry A. Blackmun:  
</P>
<P>
	``I fear for the future. The signs are evident and very ominous,  
and a chill wind blows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thus wrote U.S. Supreme Court Justice Harry A. Blackmun, then 80  
years old, in dissenting against his colleagues when in 1989 they 
voted 5-to-4 to uphold a Missouri law restricting access to 
abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision that day did not overturn the landmark  
abortion-rights opinion Blackmun had written 16 years earlier ... 
in fact, the court in 1992 reaffirmed Roe vs. Wade's central 
premise that women have a constitutional right to abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	But the words of Justice Blackmun, who died earlier this month  
at the age of 90, are worth noting because of their prescience in 
today's terms. 
</P>
<P>
	The ominous winds Blackmun envisioned have indeed blown across  
America, taking the form of ugly rhetoric fueling threats of bombs 
and anthrax. Deaths of doctors have had a nationwide chilling 
effect on women's access to abortion; doctors perform them at great 
personal and political risk. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 5  
</P>
<P>
	The Times-Picayune, New Orleans, on Monica Lewinsky :  
</P>
<P>
	The impeachment trial ended the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal as a  
legal and constitutional issue, but the sense of absurdity lingers. 
That, perhaps, is why tens of millions of Americans tuned in 
Wednesday evening to watch the president's ex-girlfriend telling 
all to Barbara Walters. 
</P>
<P>
	It was quite a spectacle. Monica Lewinsky, was by turns  
telegenic and weepy, apologetic and self-justifying. But beyond all 
that, she was a clear product of the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, if Ms. Lewinsky hadn't talked so much about her  
parents, you might have thought she had sprung spontaneously from 
the silliest, undercurrents of today's popular culture. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Having shown her undergarment to the leader of the free world  
and described the gesture three years later as ``small'' and 
``subtle,'' Ms. Lewinsky might still need a reality check. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Ms. Lewinsky seemed clued-in enough to recognize the  
preposterousness of her own situation. ... 
</P>
<P>
	All the elements of 1990s self-absorption were there:  
self-exploration, self-revelation and self-deprecating humor. Ms. 
Lewinsky's underlying message Wednesday night was, ``Isn't everyone 
fascinated by me?'' And, embarrassingly enough, we are. 
</P>
<P>
	March 8  
</P>
<P>
	Akron Beacon Journal, on Supreme Court and schools:  
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Supreme Court seems to have the same view of public  
schools as the rest of society: If there's a problem, the schools 
should handle it. 
</P>
<P>
	After a while, the costs of such fixes stretch school budgets,  
and needed dollars struggle to reach the classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Wednesday's high court ruling increases that strain by  
requiring public schools to pay for specialized, expensive, 
one-on-one nursing care for severely disabled students. 
</P>
<P>
	No one suggests that severely disabled children be kept at home,  
in isolation. 
</P>
<P>
	However, if we keep foisting on individual districts the  
responsibility to underwrite all such specialized costs, districts 
could find they must cut education programs in order to make ends 
meet. 
</P>
<P>
	At that point, all children lose.  

</P>
<P>
	March 8:  
</P>
<P>
	The News-Journal of Daytona Beach, Fla., on land mines:  
</P>
<P>
	As delegations from 133 nations gathered last week in Geneva to  
celebrate the inaugural of the international treaty to ban land 
mines, word arrived that two children were killed and six others 
seriously wounded when a land mine exploded in northern Rwanda. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Conspicuously absent from the Geneva ceremony was a delegation  
from the United States. No American should feel comfortable. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Tens of millions of anti-personnel land mines (are) planted  
worldwide. ... In peacetime they kill and maim far more civilians, 
especially children, than combatants. Land mines were the leading 
cause of U.S. casualties in the Vietnam War. ... During the Korean 
War, more American land-mine casualties were caused by U.S. 
defensive minefields than by the enemy's mines. ... 
</P>
<P>
	If such tragedy is ever to be reduced or eliminated, the effort  
will have to include the leadership of the globe's only remaining 
superpower. 

</P>
<P>
	March 10  
</P>
<P>
	Newsday, Long Island, N.Y., on Medicare:  
</P>
<P>
	With the Washington spotlight on Social Security and tax cuts,  
Medicare is getting all the attention of a bit player who arrives 
at a theater just as Madonna and Leonardo DiCaprio step into a 
swarm of paparazzi. That's too bad. Medicare, like the anonymous 
extra, could use the buzz. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old health insurance program for the elderly will  
dip into the red in 2008, even before it is hit by a tidal wave of 
baby boomer retirements. As the Commission on the Future of 
Medicare works toward a salvage plan, some things are clear: The 
time for reform is now. An accelerated moved into managed care is 
inevitable, but fee-for-service should remain an option for current 
recipients. And a prescription drug benefit is desirable, but it 
could break the bank. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 4  
</P>
<P>
	The Sun, Lowell, Mass., on the 2000 presidential campaign:  
</P>
<P>
	If you take a gander at your calendar, you will find that the  
month is March and the year is 1999, quite a distance from the 
presidential election in November 2000. But there is money to 
raise, there are organizations to put in place, there are crowds to 
excite. ... 
</P>
<P>
	George W. Bush, the governor of Texas, said that, while he would  
shortly announce the official formation of an exploratory 
committee, he would not make a final decision about running until 
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the hesitancy, virtually everyone assumes he's a  
candidate, and not a few of these people, especially Bush's fellow 
GOP governors, are rallying around him and cheering him on. The 
hope, apparently, is to help him achieve an insurmountable 
advantage now and thus thwart internecine bloodletting later. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a strategy with risks. It's true that Bush has a  
fresh-faced likableness akin to that of President Clinton, that he 
has a famous name, that he seems to have done well administering 
the affairs of Texas and that he scores high in the polls. But, on 
the national scene, he is untested, and the polls of the moment are 
unreliable predictors of the future. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 9  
</P>
<P>
	St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times, on Joe DiMaggio:  
</P>
<P>
	Dying just before the beginning of the 1999 Major League  
Baseball season was Joe DiMaggio's final act of dignity. DiMaggio 
slipped away before the New York Yankees' Opening Day, when he was 
scheduled to throw out the ceremonial first ball. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Known for the grace with which he played the game and lived his  
life, the Yankee Clipper retired from baseball in 1951, saying he 
had slowed and didn't want to deliver less than his best. Through 
decades of retirement, he never showed the world anything less than 
his best. 
</P>
<P>
	You didn't have to be a Yankees' fan to be crazy about Joe  
DiMaggio and the way he played baseball. You didn't even have to 
have seen him play. He was baseball, and you could share the 
legend. As the Yankees' centerfielder, DiMaggio was defined by his 
elegant bearing and his effortless hits and catches as much as by 
his stats. ... 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio was a shy, private man who shunned the limelight,  
especially during and after his short marriage to screen legend 
Marilyn Monroe. When she died in 1962, eight years after they 
called it quits, he sent roses to her crypt for years afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	To the very end of his life, he maintained the dignity and quiet  
mystique that defined his years in the limelight. Those are the 
human stats. Combine them with his baseball greatness, and it is 
hard to say so long to Joe DiMaggio. 

</P>
<P>
	March 10  
</P>
<P>
	EL Pais, Madrid, on the restart of Chernobyl's reactor:  
</P>
<P>
	The restart of Chernobyl's reactor, a relic of the Soviet era,  
after not having worked for a couple of months because of failures 
in its different systems is not a decision that only affects the 
Ukraine habitants. It involves the whole world, specially Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The government of Ukraine justifies the reopening of Chernobyl  
on the country's economical difficulties and also says that nothing 
obliges the government to close the nuclear power plant. 
</P>
<P>
	But everything indicates that Ukraine's aim is to use Chernobyl  
as a blackmail so that the West continues to contribute financially 
and pay for the construction of two other new nuclear power plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The argument of the economical problems is real, but something  
as serious as nuclear contamination is no excuse enough to try to 
blackmail the West. ... 

