	March 10  
</P>
<P>
	Le Matin, Lausanne, Switzerland, on French tainted blood trial:  
</P>
<P>
	In the contaminated blood case, the French court of justice has  
given a ruling which is neither one thing nor the other, in other 
words unsatisfactory. 
</P>
<P>
	But it could not have done otherwise, and we knew that before  
the trial began. Why? For many reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, the court itself was open to doubt. This was a  
ULO -- an Unidentified Legal Object -- a hybrid created from 
professional magistrates and parliamentarians, banning the victims 
from taking civil action. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The only thing which is certain is that the three ministers  
concerned never deliberately aimed to kill people. The 
administrative system was never thought of as authorizing the 
contamination of hemophiliacs and those receiving transfusions. 
</P>
<P>
	What is unacceptable is the economic logic which put price above  
public health. In this respect, it is close to other scandals such 
as that of Mad Cow Disease. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 9  
</P>
<P>
	Dagens Nyheter, Stockholm, on EU-American trade war:  
</P>
<P>
	Between the EU and the USA a peculiar and silly war about  
bananas is going on. The EU introduced restrictions on the imprt of 
bananas from Latin America. The cause was that France wanted to 
favor banana imports from its formerly colonies in Africa. The 
United States filed a complaint of restraint of trade with the 
World Trade Organization, GATT's successor as world trade's police 
department. The EU has ignored the WTO's judgment. Now the United 
States has introduced 100-percent tariffs on a number of imported 
goods from EU countries. That doesn't appear so dangerous. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The banana war reflects an old and unfortunate protectionist  
tradition on both sides, maybe foremost among some parts of the EU. 
... What's at issue is the WTO's authority. If the EU and the 
United States disregard the WTO's demand to abolish trade 
hindrances, the WTO will find it difficult in the future to 
liberalize trade in agricultural products and mediate an 
international investment agreement. 

</P>
