	March 9  
</P>
<P>
	Sueddeutsche Zeitung, Munich, on Slobodan Milosevic:  
</P>
<P>
	Slobodan Milosevic has achieved one thing during his more than  
ten years as leader of the Serbian people: He has made Belgrade the 
western capital of evil. The demoralized and impoverished citizenry 
has not deserved this. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond dispute, however, is that the source of all Balkan crises  
in this decade can be traced to Belgrade. The result is that when 
politicians visit Belgrade it is only to threaten. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbians have little room to negotiate. From Belgrade to  
Kosovo and into Bosnia they have adopted a strategy of 
uncompromising refusal. This is dangerous for the region as a 
whole. 
</P>
<P>
	Few demands have been made of Serbia: They should tolerate NATO  
troops in Kosovo, accept the dismissal of President Poplasen, and 
relinquish their control of Brcko, a strategically important city. 
</P>
<P>
	If Belgrade still does not cooperate, the time of diplomatic  
threat will be over, and the only thing threatening everyone will 
be an emergency. 

</P>
<P>
	March 9  
</P>
<P>
	La Repubblica, Rome, on Iranian president Khatami's visit to  
Italy: 
</P>
<P>
	Iranian dissidents in exile as well as Italian citizens are  
rallying in Rome to protest human rights violation in Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	The protests are not ill-founded, but if the target is Iran's  
President Mohammed Khatami, in Italy on a three-day visit, then 
there is a misunderstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Hosting him in Rome, Italy's government officials -- as well as  
the pope -- are not receiving the hangman of repression or the 
champion of an authoritarian ideology, but the man who did his best 
in the last two years to extend civil rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Iran's theocracy is still a long way from reaching a standard of  
freedom and democracy which is acceptable for the Western world. 
But Khatami started off in that direction with the support of 
millions of Iranian voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Khatami will hardly finish Iran's liberalization process. But  
thanks to him, it is now possible to start dreaming of a ``spring'' 
of the Iranian revolution. 

