	March 9  
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Telegraph, London, on balloon landing:  
</P>
<P>
	Another balloon crashes. Yet again, at some cost to the Japanese  
taxpayer, the emergency helicopters are deployed. This time our 
heroes contrive to ditch in the Pacific. Last time it was some 
Andean peak, and the time before that it was the Irish Sea. What is 
it about these hot air escapades that leaves one's natural 
enthusiasm so -- well -- deflated? It is not that ballooning is 
pointless. So are many great feats of human endeavour. 
</P>
<P>
	No, the problem of the Great Balloon Prang, as a piece of  
theater, is just that it happens too often. Hardly a week passes 
but we are invited to chew our nails as Richard Branson (for it is 
usually he) gives a tense, slitty-eyed commentary into the 
satellite minicam at 10,000 ft, all about how the chemical 
conveniences have failed, or how the wrong kind of ice has formed 
on his titanium cocoon, or how he risks being shot down by Chinese 
MiGs. One has the impression that the ether is pullulating with 
millionaires in their hugely sponsored, ego-sized puffballs, 
alternately ascending like rockets because someone let go of a 
guy-rope, or sinking with vast exhalations into the drink, before 
emerging to give macho, bearded press conferences. 
</P>
<P>
	It is time for the balloonists to realize that the world is not  
as impressed by their derring-do as they seem to think we are. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 6  
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Shimbun, Tokyo, on China:  
</P>
<P>
	(Prime Minister) Zhu Rongji emphasized that he would continue to  
carry out the `three reforms' of state enterprises, government 
machinery and financial service. But the road ahead is bumpy. 
</P>
<P>
	State enterprises continue to expand their losses. The number of  
the unemployed reached 6.2 million at the end of last year. In 
addition, 6 million workers were temporarily laid off and are still 
jobless. The reorganization of the government will cost another 3 
million people their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform creates instability in Chinese society. There were  
reports of farmers and workers taking to the streets in many parts 
of the country. Chinese authorities are wary of the people giving 
vent to their discontent. The government stepped up its crackdown 
on the democracy movement at the end of last year, and Xu Wenli and 
other dissidents who tried to organize the Chinese Democratic Party 
were sentenced to more than 10 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	It is wrong to suppress human rights. If the people's  
dissatisfaction is repressed, it could eventually explode. Although 
Zhu has a reputation of being an expert in managing the economy and 
of a man who gets things done, it appears he will have a difficult 
time carrying out reforms and maintaining stability at the same 
time. 
</P>
