<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Money for Clinton Museum Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Just days before President Clinton is  
due in his native Hope, Arkansas lawmakers rejected a $500,000 plan 
to make improvements at his boyhood-home-turned-museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Sandra Rodgers, D-Hope, rushed from the House chamber after  
the House defeated her bill Tuesday and cried in the Capitol hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want President Clinton to know that they don't support  
him, that's fine with me, I'll try to convey that message for 
him,'' said Ms. Rodgers, her voice breaking. ``I'm just really 
mad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many representatives who opposed the bill said it had nothing to  
do with Clinton, but with the source of the money. The project 
would have been funded immediately, instead of having to compete 
later with other projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which needed 75 votes in the 99-member House, was  
defeated 41-8. Most members, not wanting to appear opposed to 
Clinton, either didn't vote or cast a ``present'' vote. 
</P>
<P>
	One representative said he opposed the funding because he  
opposes Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have voted for impeachment, and I think he has  
disgraced our state in a lot of ways,'' said Rep. Jim Bob Duggar, 
R-Springdale. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rodgers had hoped to have the funding approved before  
Friday, so she could present Clinton with a copy of the legislation 
when he makes his first visit to his birthplace home. Clinton is 
attending the dedication of the Virginia Clinton Kelly Memorial 
Garden in memory of his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum, which opened in June 1997, has received about $1  
million in donations from individuals and corporations. Executive 
Director Becky Moore said the state money would have sped up work 
so that the museum could be part of the national park system. 
</P>
<P>
	The $500,000 would have funded a 40-seat theater, computer room,  
board room, gift shop expansion and relocation of the director's 
office at the tourist center next to Clinton's home. Some of the 
money also could be used to spruce up the grounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
