<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:54:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report Probes Atlanta, Amateur Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A tax-exempt nonprofit foundation supporting  
Atlanta's Olympic legacy has spent only $20,000 to bolster amateur 
sports in the 2 1/2 years since the Atlanta Olympic Games, The Atlanta 
Journal-Constitution said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation has given grants of  
$10,000 each to two youth golf programs, but spent almost $1 
million to buy the personal memorabilia of its chairman, Billy 
Payne, who founded the organization more than 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The athletic legacy for the games has basically been nil, and  
that has really been unfortunate,'' said Dennis Berkholtz, 
president of the national team handball federation, which relocated 
to Atlanta in hopes of benefiting from the city's Olympic legacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Payne, who headed the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games,  
says the foundation has ``an admirable record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It has hosted sporting events and given grants for a multiple  
number of years,'' Payne said. ``The process was interrupted when 
the bid was accepted. Now that everybody has got a second wind, we 
are going to pick it back up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation has plans for an Olympic museum. It has a  
collection of memorabilia and archived documents that are being 
held at the Atlanta History Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The two $10,000 grants were made last fall to the East Lake  
Community Foundation for its junior academy and the Friends of John 
A. White Park for First Tee for inner-city kids. 
</P>
<P>
	Both programs were connected to Payne or his board members, the  
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me and a lot of people that their objective is get  
the museum built, and that's a legacy, but that's not a legacy for 
kids and sport,'' Berkholtz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Payne says the foundation has spent much time beginning the  
process of looking into the memorabilia and records. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have spent thousands of hours on the museum feasibility  
study,'' Payne said. ``Those are fundamental and appropriate 
undertakings and ones that we are proud of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sports activists would like to see more done for athletes.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've already got a beautiful (Centennial Olympic) park, and  
I'm glad we've got it,'' said Steve Kearney, president of USA 
Badminton. ``But what is that going to do for the sports? I'd also 
like to have a gym I could play in and teach kids in. The athletes 
are the legacy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:58:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy Meets With Yugoslav Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Senior U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke  
began crisis talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic 
today, pushing for a Kosovo settlement even as Yugoslav forces 
pressed an offensive in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke huddled with fellow Western envoys and ambassadors of  
the six-nation Contact Group before entering the president's palace 
at midday for talks aimed at breaking down Milosevic's resistance 
to a U.S.-drafted peace plan. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Holbrooke warned that Milosevic could be on a  
``collision course'' with NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are only a few days away from a tragedy of even greater  
dimensions,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But there has been no hint of a softening in the Yugoslav stance  
in the face of Western threats. 
</P>
<P>
	Army troops and Serb police pushed ahead with an operation to  
establish control of an ethnic Albanian-populated area along 
Kosovo's southern border with Macedonia, and the U.N. refugee 
agency said it had reports of at least four villages burning in the 
hilly areas along the border. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 2,000 people have died and hundreds of thousands have  
been displaced in a year of fighting between Yugoslav troops and 
ethnic Albanian rebels. Albanians make up 90 percent of the 
population in Kosovo, a province in the Yugoslav republic of 
Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Kosovo Liberation Army rebels are seriously  
considering signing the peace plan in coming days, the Serb-led 
Yugoslav government opposes it -- especially the provision for a 
deployment of some 28,000 NATO troops to police the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav forces backed by tanks and other heavy weapons have  
been sweeping through villages along the border across from where 
NATO forces are gathering, sending as many as 4,000 more ethnic 
Albanian villagers fleeing, according to the U.N. High Commissioner 
for Refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Aid workers today were trying to evacuate residents of three  
villages in rocky, remote hills near the border -- afraid to flee 
because of the overwhelming Yugoslav military presence in the area, 
including Serb tanks and armored personnel carriers on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	In the village of Kotlina, surrounded on three sides by Yugoslav  
forces, about 600 people waited tensely today while an estimated 
400 others were in nearby woods. One house had been hit by mortar, 
and aid workers said the Serbs had destroyed seven or eight houses 
near the village the previous day. Several people were reported 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	``They feel they're essentially trapped in their own village,''  
said UNHCR spokeswoman Paula Ghedini. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in the troubled province, there were reports of  
continuing clashes in the northern Podujevo area between Serb 
forces and the rebels, with each side accusing the other of 
provoking the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds more people have been displaced by the fighting between  
Vucitrn and Mitrovica. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation is essentially deteriorating rather than  
improving ahead of the resumption of peace talks,'' said UNHCR 
spokesman Kris Janowski in Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	Shooting also was reported along the Malisevo-Lapushnik road  
today, and one policeman was wounded, said spokesman Dieter Wulf of 
the international monitoring force run by the Organization for 
Security and Cooperation in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting to the north of Pristina on Tuesday left five Serbian  
policemen dead, ethnic Albanian rebels said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate indication whether the  
Holbrooke-Milosevic talks would run longer than a day, as they did 
last October when he brokered an informal cease-fire agreement and 
substantial withdrawals by Yugoslav forces. 
</P>
<P>
	That agreement, however, has been systematically violated by  
both sides and has all but collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace talks that produced little progress toward a settlement  
last month are set to resume outside Paris on Monday, but envoys 
are trying to win pledges from both sides beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA has indicated it may reluctantly sign the deal that  
gives ethnic Albanians broad autonomy, but not the independence 
they seek. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfgang Petritsch, the European Union mediator for Kosovo, said  
before meeting Holbrooke this morning that the ethnic Albanian 
rebels are ``very, very close to signing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Up to 95 percent is a done deal and they want to make sure  
that their last commander is on board,'' Petritsch said. 
</P>
<P>
	But KLA spokesman Jakup Krasniqi told the Albanian-language  
newspaper Kosova Sot in remarks published today that chances for 
the rebels to sign are ``50-50.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the KLA signature is still being discussed, and depends  
on an announced visit to Washington by their delegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
