<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dole Plans Exploratory Committee  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole is expected to announce  
this hour that she is forming an exploratory committee for the 2000 
GOP presidential nomination. Mrs. Dole said earlier that it is high 
time the nation's leaders restore voters' faith in their 
government. That was among the themes the former U.S. labor and 
transportation secretary touted in a TV ad that was to accompany 
her expected announcement. 

</P>
<P>
	Joe Torre Has Prostate Cancer  
</P>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- New York Yankees manager Joe Torre was  
diagnosed with prostate cancer and has left the World Series 
champions to undergo treatment. ``I feel fine,'' the 58-year-old 
manager said today, ``and I am looking forward to taking care of 
this problem and getting back to work.'' It was not immediately how 
advanced the disease was or how long Torre will be away from the 
team. Torre, who led the Yankees to a record 125 victories last 
season, will undergo treatment at Johns Hopkins University in 
Baltimore. 

</P>
<P>
	Student Found Dead on NYC Sidewalk  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A graduate student from Kansas who was working  
with battered women was found dead on a Brooklyn sidewalk with a 
kitchen knife in her back. Police believe robbery was the motive 
for the Monday night attack on Amy Watkins, 26, who was studying 
for her masters in social work while working with victims of 
domestic violence in the Bronx. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Address Salvador Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR (AP) -- President Clinton begins the third day of  
his Central America tour with an address to the Salvadoran 
Legislative Assembly. He'll give a tip of his hat to the transition 
this nation has accomplished since a 1992 peace agreement. Sunday's 
democratic, presidential elections served as a fresh reminder of 
the progress El Salvador has made since it buried 70,000 of its 
people in 12 years of civil war. 

</P>
<P>
	Tear Gas Used in Ecuador Protest  
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Riot police used tear gas to break up more  
than 100 protesting workers in Ecuador's capital today, the first 
day of a nationwide strike to protest economic reforms. Unions have 
threatened to paralyze Ecuador if President Jamil Mahuad does not 
back down on reforms that have caused prices to soar and a bill now 
in Congress that calls for deep public spending cuts. 

</P>
<P>
	Dalai Lama Assails China  
</P>
<P>
	DHARMSALA, India (AP) -- Tibetan exiles burned an effigy of  
China's president today and maroon-robed monks led thousands of 
protesters in a march marking an uprising 40 years ago against 
Chinese rule in Tibet. In the northern Indian city of Dharmsala, 
the Tibetan people's spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama, spoke to 
4,000 Tibetans and international observers -- including Hollywood 
actors Richard Gere and Goldie Hawn. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Official Warns of Alcoholism  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Alcoholism among Russian teenagers in on the rise,  
and drinking problems continue to afflict millions of Russians, a 
top health official said today. Some 2.5 million people, or nearly 
2 percent of Russia's 146.3 population, are officially registered 
alcoholics, but the actual number is probably much higher, Deputy 
Health Minister Gennady Onishchenko told a news conference. 

</P>
<P>
	America West Talks To Resume  
</P>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Stalled contract negotiations between  
America West Airlines and its flight attendants' union are set to 
resume next week in an effort to avoid a strike when a required 
cooling-off period expires. The 2,400 flight attendants, without a 
contract for four years, are free to strike beginning at 10:01 p.m. 
March 19, and their leaders have said they plan random stoppages if 
there still is no deal. 
</P>
<P>
		   Stocks Higher; Dow Up 55  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EST, the Dow industrials were  
up 55.50 to 9,749.26. NYSE advancers led decliners 1,533-1,235. The 
Nasdaq index was up 4.31 to 2,397.25. 

</P>
