<HEADLINE> Wheat Gains, Corn Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures prices advanced early today on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while corn was mixed and soybeans were 
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures rose mainly in technical buying ahead of the U.S.  
Agriculture Department's latest supply and demand report, due on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans retreated after prices for competing Malaysian palm oil  
declined overnight, suggesting world demand may be weakening once 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn traded both sides, finding strength on continued  
expectations for smaller spring plantings and steady export 
business, but showing weakness amid expectations for bumper South 
America crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.78 1/4 a bushel; May  
corn was unchanged at $22.1 1/4 a bushel; May oats were unchanged at 
$1.07 a bushel; May soybeans fell 3 1/2 cents to $4.69 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures retreatd on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
live cattle were mixed and feeder cattle retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle fell .10 cent to 68.42 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle rose .15 cent to 72.72 cents a pound; April lean logs 
fell .35 cent to 42.20 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .43 
cent to 51.17 cents a pound. 
</P>
