<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 10:36:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Julia Sweeney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Five years ago, Julia Sweeney thought her  
life was on the right track. Leaving the cast of ``Saturday Night 
Live,'' she had a new house and a new movie coming out based on her 
SNL character, the androgynous ``Pat.'' Even her divorce was 
amicable. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, as she recalls in her one-woman show, God said, ``Ha!''  
</P>
<P>
	Her brother Mike got terminal cancer and moved into Sweeney's  
house. Their parents moved in as well. Sweeney was barely coping 
with it all when suddenly she had a personal crisis that hit from 
nowhere. Meanwhile, the movie, ``It's Pat,'' bombed. 
</P>
<P>
	A comedian by training, Sweeney dealt with her struggles by  
performing, venting on stage at The Uncabaret club in West 
Hollywood, then constructing a full-length theater performance, 
``God said, 'Ha!''' The show played in 1996 to sold-out houses in 
San Francisco and Los Angeles before a six-week run on Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	Funny, poignant and profound, the show was put on film, exactly  
as it was performed on the stage, in the film ``God Said, 'Ha!''' 
now in limited release. It is that rarest of movie forms -- a 
monologue -- just Sweeney and the camera. 
</P>
<P>
	Now working on a screenplay and continuing her movie career with  
the upcoming ``Stuart Little,'' Sweeney, 39, discussed Broadway, 
death and her good friend, Quentin Tarantino. (She appeared in his 
``Pulp Fiction.'') 
</P>
<P>
	1. How were you able to maintain the emotional intensity of the  
show night after night? 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney: In L.A., it was a dream. I don't know if I'll ever have  
as positive an experience as I did in L.A. But when I took it to 
Broadway, it was eight shows (a week) instead of six. Plus, I was 
tired of it. Plus, I was older. I was really just performing on 
Broadway. But in L.A., man, I couldn't wait to get to the theater. 
There wasn't one performance I couldn't wait to get to. I just felt 
like I had the story in me I had to tell. 
</P>
<P>
	2. Did you ever make mistakes in the Broadway show?  
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney: I knew the show so well it was getting in my way. I  
could make shopping lists while I was on stage. I would, like, take 
a deep breath and suddenly not know where I was in the show. I had 
to figure it out from where I was standing on the set. It was like 
standing on the edge of the Grand Canyon. It was just this feeling 
of: 'Oh, my God.' But I don't think the audience realized it, thank 
God. 
</P>
<P>
	3. You poke fun at your parents throughout the show. How did  
they deal with it? 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney: They were actually really positive. I almost had a  
coronary before they saw it. They came to San Francisco, and I took 
them to a restaurant and said, 'I'm doing a show. You have to know 
what's going to happen. You just tell me if you're upset to my 
face.' I could handle it to my face. About a quarter of the way 
through (my talk), they're looking at the floor and the ceiling and 
my mom just said, 'Oh, just show it all. We can handle a lot.' I 
thought it was really sweet. They do get redeemed in the end of the 
show. They have a great sense of humor. 
</P>
<P>
	4. After all this happened, your friend Phil Hartman was killed.  
How did you deal with that? 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney: It's still hitting me. It's so weird. When Mike died,  
you had a whole long time to get used to the idea. With Phil, 
you're talking to him one day and the next day he's dead. It takes 
a really long time to accept it. It just doesn't seem logical that 
someone could be alive and suddenly dead, even if you're me, when 
you've spent a lot of time with people who are dying. 
</P>
<P>
	5. The movie credits list Quentin Tarantino as executive  
producer. What was his role in the project? 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney: We have been good friends for years. We were in Ireland  
a couple of years before all this happened, and he said, 'Someday 
let's shoot a one-person show of yours.' It wasn't until the show 
was in L.A., and different studios were approaching me to film it, 
that I went to Quentin and said, 'What's the deal?' And he said, 
'Let's do it ourselves. I'll finance it and we'll work through it. 
And you'll direct it.' It turned out to be a treat. He's just an 
angel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
