<DOCNO> APW19990310.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 00:53:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Ruling Raises Major Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A sign that the apocalypse is upon us turned up this week in  
Overland Park, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice in as many days. The NCAA has been found lacking the same  
thing for which it has smacked many a school. It appears to have 
lost institutional control. 
</P>
<P>
	This is not the same thing as misplacing your dentures or  
running over a neighbor's mailbox after a heated argument. Still, 
the two losses combined to make the watchdog of college sports look 
less fearsome, yet just as vindictive as always, not exactly the 
image somebody in the enforcement business wants to be projecting 
these days. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, a federal judge in Philadelphia ruled the NCAA cannot  
force member schools to use a minimum score of 820 on the 
Scholastic Aptitude Test as the bottom-line measurement of whether 
incoming freshmen are eligible to play sports. 
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of the men's basketball tournament, its biggest  
moneymaker, the NCAA has a say which teams get in, but not which 
players those teams put on the floor. Can anarchy be far behind? 
</P>
<P>
	``What you have clearly, right now, is no rule,'' spokesman  
Wally Renfro said just before the NCAA asked U.S. District Judge 
Ronald Buckwalter to stay his order. 
</P>
<P>
	``That means you have no consistent, uniform across-the-board  
rule,'' Renfro added. ``That means you have over 500 rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To shake things up further, on Tuesday the NCAA conceded defeat  
in a second lawsuit, agreeing to pay $54.5 million to about 2,000 
Division I assistant coaches whose salaries were capped at $16,000 
for a calendar year. 
</P>
<P>
	That litigation dragged on for nearly four years, during which  
the organization stubbornly refused chances to settle for 
considerably less. And yet, in typical NCAA-speak, executive 
committee chairman Charles Wethington described it as a kind of 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``This association-wide nightmare is over,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	In the same sense, you might say the NCAA is on a roll -- only  
it's all been downhill. 
</P>
<P>
	Just recently, the organization lost a lawsuit brought by  
students with learning disabilities. Last April, it settled a 
decades-long dispute with lifelong rebel and current Fresno State 
coach Jerry Tarkanian for $2.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Over that time, Tark's lineups included more unsavory characters  
than a year's worth of ``America's Most Wanted.'' But shoddy 
investigative work and suggestions of a vendetta ultimately blew 
the NCAA's case apart. When Tarkanian finally maneuvered the NCAA 
into a Las Vegas court, there was nothing the organization could do 
but throw up its hands and reach for the wallet. 
</P>
<P>
	That could happen again with increasing frequency. Adidas, the  
very powerful athletic shoe and clothing manufacturer, is going 
one-on-one against the NCAA in yet another court for restricting 
the size of logos on some of its apparel. After that, next up on 
the organization's legal dance card is a lawsuit from a 
manufacturer of baseball bats. 
</P>
<P>
	After years of prevailing in courts at all levels, it looks like  
all the bullying and bad karma the NCAA has been handing out for 
years is suddenly coming home to roost. There is a temptation to 
chalk up the organization's increasing woes to an increasingly 
litigious society, but it would be more accurate to think of the 
NCAA as a corrupt cop, arrogant and sloppy after collecting bag 
money for years from the schools it is supposed to be protecting. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, there is something unjust about an organization that  
makes it possible for millions to flow into university coffers, but 
impossible for the ``student-athletes'' who generate most of it to 
get their hands on walking-around money. And there is something 
unseemly about colleges banding together to come up with enough 
``product'' to keep the networks, advertisers and endorsement 
people happy, then turning around and policing one another to make 
sure everybody's labor costs stay low. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent events suggest contradictions like these will be harder  
and harder to defend, let alone control. 
</P>
<P>
	The eligibility standards struck down by a Philadelphia judge as  
unfair to blacks had their origin more than a dozen years ago. They 
came in response to a series of embarrassing news stories about 
star athletes who were unable to read, and others whose eligibility 
was used up without being anywhere close to graduating. 
</P>
<P>
	But almost no one disputes that the state of affairs at the  
moment -- no eligibility standards at all -- will serve the kids they 
were supposed to protect any better. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those things where we knew something was wrong,''  
said Rudy Washington, who once headed the Black Coaches Association 
and now serves as commissioner of the Southwestern Athletic 
Conference. ``And we tried to get people to listen to us, but they 
wouldn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a familiar complaint against the NCAA. The difference  
is that now people are telling it to the judge. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@apamil.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:39:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RJR Nabisco To Shed Tobacco Biz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Food and tobacco conglomerate RJR Nabisco  
Holdings Corp. is sending its cigarette business out on its own. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR said Tuesday it will sell its international tobacco business  
to Japan's largest tobacco company and will break off its domestic 
tobacco operations into a separate company owned by RJR 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves come amid rising legal challenges to the tobacco  
industry and falling U.S. cigarette sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tobacco industry is in deep trouble,'' said Ahron  
Leichtman, executive director of Citizens for a Tobacco-Free 
Society. 
</P>
<P>
	But RJR said the cigarette and food companies will probably fare  
better as separate entities. 
</P>
<P>
	Its tobacco brands include Camel, Winston and Salem cigarettes,  
and the deals will leave it in control of a food business which 
makes Ritz crackers, Oreo cookies, Life Savers candy and Planters 
nuts. 
</P>
<P>
	The $17 billion conglomerate has been under pressure for several  
years from major stockholders to separate its food and tobacco 
businesses because the tobacco is considered a drag on RJR's stock. 
Some investors won't put their money in any company that has 
tobacco holdings, out of either opposition to smoking or fear that 
lawsuits will hurt profits. 
</P>
<P>
	John Maxwell, analyst at Davenport &AMP; Co., said RJR got a  
fantastic price for the international business -- $7.8 billion. He 
said RJR will use the proceeds to help reduce its $9.1 billion 
debt, leaving the domestic tobacco company in a better position to 
compete in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Icahn, a onetime corporate raider who holds about 7.7  
percent of RJR stock, had threatened to launch a fight for control 
of the board of directors to force a quick separation. Icahn failed 
to return repeated calls for comment Tuesday. The deadline for 
filing a rival slate is Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR is selling its international tobacco business to Japan  
Tobacco Co. which is also assuming $200 million in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deal will allow us to secure a base for future growth  
overseas and establish us as a global player,'' Japan Tobacco said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The RJR international tobacco business is a distant third to  
Philip Morris Cos. and British-American Tobacco PLC, and its 
earnings have fallen amid financial turmoil in its key Russian and 
Asian markets. 
</P>
<P>
	After the sale, the RJR board plans to spin off its domestic  
tobacco operations, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., to RJR shareholders. 
The tobacco company will keep its name and will retain its 
headquarters in Winston-Salem, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the food and tobacco businesses will be best  
able to achieve their full potential under separate ownership 
structures,'' said RJR chairman and chief executive Steven F. 
Goldstone. 
</P>
<P>
	Importantly, the new corporate structure allows people filing  
tobacco suits to continue to make claims against either R.J. 
Reynolds Tobacco Co. or the renamed RJR Nabisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The spinoff would leave RJR Nabisco with an 80.6 percent stake  
in Nabisco Holdings Corp., the food division that also makes Oreos, 
Chips Ahoy! and Snackwell's cookies, Premium saltines and A1 steak 
sauce. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathryn Mulvey, executive director of corporate accountability  
watchdog Infact, said RJR's moves meant ``the corporation 
responsible for Joe Camel would no longer being operating with the 
same influence on the national or international scenes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her Boston-based group has been encouraging consumers to avoid  
buying Nabisco products since 1994 because of the food company's 
ties to cigarette making. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with lower debt after the spinoff, Reynolds Tobacco faces  
challenges. Analysts expect the steady decline in cigarette 
consumption will accelerate due to hefty price hikes that are being 
used to pay for a lawsuit settlement that is costing the industry 
$246 billion over 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government is considering a similar suit to recover  
the costs of treating sick smokers. A California jury recently 
ordered Philip Morris to pay $51 million judgment to a smoker. A 
class-action smokers' suit is pending in Florida and several union 
health funds are also suing the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had long warned that simply spinning off the food  
division into a separate independent company would face a prolonged 
court challenge because plaintiffs would charge the company with 
putting valuable assets out of their reach. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Daynard, a tobacco critic who heads the Tobacco Products  
Liability Project, said that plaintiffs may still protest if the 
company uses the proceeds from the sale of the international 
company for a stock buyback or higher dividends. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
