<DOCNO> APW19990310.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 23:32:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Breaks Through in Skiing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- While Norway's Lasse Kjus took a  
small step toward his second overall World Cup title, North 
Americans Chad Fleischer and Melanie Turgeon made the biggest leaps 
of their ski racing careers. 
</P>
<P>
	While Kjus, teammate Kjetil Andre Aamodt and defending champion  
Hermann Maier raced for World Cup overall supremacy, Fleischer and 
Turgeon made their first appearances on the medals podium. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleischer's second place in the men's downhill helped Kjus  
distance himself from Aamodt and Maier in the chase for the overall 
crystal globe. 
</P>
<P>
	With most of the contenders having already run and Aamodt in  
second place behind Kjus, Norwegian rookie Audun Groenvold squeezed 
into third place and Fleischer into second -- with Aamodt dropping 
to fourth. Defending World Cup champion Maier finished ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of picking up 80 points in the overall standings, Aamodt  
got only 50. With three races remaining, Kjus leads the overall 
standings with 1,359 points to 1,317 for Aamodt and 1,271 for 
Maier. 
</P>
<P>
	Happy for the American but also grateful, Kjus gave Fleischer a  
giant bear hug following the race. 
</P>
<P>
	For Fleischer, the second place did little to affect his spot in  
the season standings, but it's a major breakthrough after seven 
seasons without a podium finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been doing this a long time, so it feels really great,''  
said Fleischer, who placed a surprising sixth in super-G at the 
worlds at home in Vail, Colo., last month, but had never finished 
better than ninth in a World Cup. ``It's taken a long time, but I 
think people become successful because they know what they want. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was kind of lost in the world of ski racing for a long time,  
so it was hard to achieve anything. But now I just want to win. I 
believe that's my destiny to dominate ski racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aware he comes across as cocky and overconfident, the  
27-year-old Fleischer adds to that image with a flamboyant, 
snow-leopard hairdo that he adopted last May. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a mindset,'' explained Fleischer, rubbing his hand over  
his short bleach-blond hair dotted with brown and black spots. ``My 
hair is meant to make me go fast, to remind me every day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now my dad will have to dye his hair the same way. He promised  
that if I got a podium he'd do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While a place on the podium was a long time coming for  
Fleischer, it seemed even longer for Turgeon, who showed unusual 
promise back in 1994 when she won two golds, a silver and a pair of 
bronze medals at the junior world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian then finished fifth in her first World Cup race.  
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Turgeon had been unable to match that result,  
battling pressure, painful shin splints and back problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Finally a podium,'' shouted Turgeon, who finished third in the  
women's downhill behind winner Alexandra Meissnitzer of Austria and 
runner-up Ingeborg Helen Marken of Norway. ``I've waited for this 
day for so long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to drop everything midseason, I cried a lot and had  
many frustrations. But a day like today erases all the bad 
moments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turgeon, the only downhill skier on a weak Canadian women's  
team, attributes her success in the season's final downhill to 
newly found peace. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before, there was a lack of communication with the coaches,  
but now the group fits well together,'' explained Turgeon, 22. 
``We've fallen on the right combination of people. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a small group, but we blend well together. We're all  
very supportive of each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turgeon also planned to race in today's final super-G race.  
Meissnitzer, who already clinched the overall World Cup title, was 
hoping to add a second crown to her collection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
