<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Microsoft Seeks Travel Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is joining a group of Web-based  
travel agents who will ask the Justice Department to investigate 
possible antitrust violations by the nation's airlines, The New 
York Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint will be addressed to Justice Department antitrust  
division chief Joel Klein, who is handling the government's lawsuit 
against Microsoft over the software giant's alleged 
anti-competitive practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft says the two issues are unrelated. A spokeswoman for  
the Redmond, Wash.-based company told the Times the ongoing lawsuit 
``does not prevent us from moving forward with our business 
strategies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's MSN Expedia is one of a number of online travel  
agents upset over the airlines' aggressive online ticket sales and 
the small commissions paid to online agencies. The group contends 
the practices keep most travel agents off the Web, which could 
drive up fares by limiting choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're concerned things are happening in the marketplace that  
are disadvantageous to the online travel agent,'' said Simon 
Breakwell, the general manager of Microsoft's travel business unit. 
``There are implications for consumer choice, and that would have 
implications on price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass., estimates that nearly  
$30 billion in tickets and travel-related products will be sold 
online annually by 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Three online travel agent associations -- the Interactive Travel  
Services Association, the American Society of Travel Agents and the 
Coalition for Travel Industry Parity -- will file the complaint by 
the end of March, said ITSA executive director Reid Detchon. 
</P>
<P>
	The travel agents' group filed its own complaint last December  
alleging that airlines are trying to control Internet sales. 
Spokesmen for American Airlines, UAL Corp.'s United Airlines and 
U.S. Airways declined to comment. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
