<DOCNO> APW19990310.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 00:32:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SuperSonics Ticket Case Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Six former ticket-sellers for the Seattle  
SuperSonics will get a chance to reinstate their $5.2 million 
damage award against the NBA team, which was overturned by a 
federal appeals panel last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals withdrew the three-judge  
panel's ruling Tuesday and said a majority of its 21 judges voted 
to refer the case to an 11-judge panel for a new hearing, not yet 
scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief issue is whether the team violated federal labor law  
by firing the employees after they complained about the cutoff of 
their overtime pay, a cutoff that a federal judge later ruled 
illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 3-0 ruling last October, the appeals court panel said  
federal labor law forbids retaliatory firings only if an employee 
has first filed a formal complaint with a federal agency. The court 
acknowledged that several other federal circuits have found that 
the law also prohibits retaliation for complaining to one's 
employers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's decision to reconsider the issue ``is good news for  
employees generally,'' said John Widell, a lawyer for the 
ticket-sellers. ``It seems to me that employees who complain to 
employers about overtime shouldn't be fired for doing that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission joined  
employees in asking the court to reconsider. The EEOC has no 
authority over overtime laws, but enforces other federal labor 
laws, including equal pay for women, that could be affected by the 
ruling, Widell said. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's managing company, Full House Sports and  
Entertainment, said in a statement that the court's action was just 
another step in the legal process. ``The plaintiffs have won no 
victory,'' the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case dates from mid-1994, when the Sonics eliminated the  
$2,000 annual overtime allowances paid to ticket sales account 
executives, as the employees were called, and stopped paying them 
any overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Employee Laura Lambert said she complained to team controller  
Brian Dixon. She said he replied that William Ackerley, then an 
executive of Ackerley Communications, the team's umbrella 
organization, didn't care about the law and wouldn't pay overtime. 
She said Dixon threatened to fire her if she persisted. 
</P>
<P>
	Lambert complained in writing to team management, which  
eventually repaid her and the other ticket-sellers for back 
overtime. She telephoned the U.S. Labor Department for information, 
but did not file a complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine ticket-sellers, including Lambert and the other five  
plaintiffs, were fired in December 1994 by Full House Sports and 
Entertainment, which took over the team's business management and 
restructured the sales staff. 
</P>
<P>
	After U.S. District Judge Barbara Rothstein ruled that the  
team's overtime policy was illegal, a jury found that the six were 
fired in retaliation for complaining about the policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors awarded them $697,000 in back pay, $450,000 for emotional  
distress, and $12 million in punitive damages, an amount Rothstein 
reduced to $4.18 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 3-0 ruling Oct. 1, the appeals court panel said federal  
labor law prohibits retaliation for complaining about a violation 
of employees' rights -- but only if a formal complaint was filed 
with the proper federal agency. The law does not cover retaliation 
merely for ``informal complaints'' to one's supervisors, said the 
opinion by Judge Melvin Brunetti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
