<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lasse Kjus Wins Men's Downhill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- Lasse Kjus of Norway won the men's  
downhill at the World Cup finals today and took the lead in the 
tight race for the overall season title. 
</P>
<P>
	American Chad Fleischer finished second in the downhill, his  
first top-three finish ever. He was timed in 1:49.89. Norwegian 
Audun Groenvold was third in 1:50.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus has 1,359 points to 1,317 for fellow Norwegian Kjetil Andre  
Aamodt and 1,271 for defending overall champion Hermann Maier of 
Austria. Three events remain to be skiied. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus, who wrapped up the season downhill title last week, added  
100 points to his season total in clocking a winning time of 1 
minute 49.73 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt was fourth in the downhill in 1:50.02. The result was  
worth 50 points and saw him slip into second place in the overall 
standings with 1,317 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Maier, the overall World Cup winner last season and two-time  
Olympic gold medal winner, continued his poor downhill showing and 
finished tied for ninth in 1:50.51. Maier, who slipped to 16th and 
11th place in downhills last week, fell 88 points off the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus and Aamodt both ski all events and will battle for the  
overall title through the season's final super-G, giant slalom and 
slalom races. Maier, who seldom skis slalom, will race it this 
weekend to boost his fading chances. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt won the World Cup overall title in 1994 and Kjus was the  
1996 overall champion 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus last month became the first man in history to win five  
medals in the world championships including gold in super-G (which 
he shared with Maier) and giant slalom. He has also won an Olympic 
gold and two silver medals. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt won gold and bronze medals in the recent worlds and is is  
also an Olympic gold medalist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
