<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Expecting Bigger Budget Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eager to offer Americans the biggest possible  
election-year tax cuts, Republicans probably will delay writing a 
tax bill until new budget estimates expected to show more money 
available from growing federal surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP budget writers preparing spending blueprints for the budget  
year beginning Oct. 1 are hemmed in by their promise not to touch 
Social Security surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Honoring that pledge has left Republicans scrambling for other  
ways to pay for next year's tax cut because all of the expected 
$133 billion surplus in fiscal 2000 would come from Social 
Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers think they have found about $15 billion worth of  
savings for 2000, a modest start for a tax-cutting package they say 
will total $800 billion over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans believe the tax cut could grow by at least $10  
billion if they wait until the summer -- and the prospect of an even 
bigger surplus forecast -- for the Congressional Budget Office's 
annual revision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'll wait until CBO updates this summer,'' said House  
Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, asked when he would 
write a tax bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., has not  
decided on his timetable. His committee usually waits until Ways 
and Means has approved its tax plan. 
</P>
<P>
	House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, said the  
2000 budget his committee plans to vote on next week will state 
that if CBO surplus projections grow this summer, the extra money 
would pay for lower taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., is  
considering similar language. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is a bigger surplus, the number is bigger for the tax  
cut,'' Kasich said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how Kasich and Domenici would protect the extra  
money for tax cuts. One possibility would be to require 60 votes in 
the 100-member Senate to use the funds for anything else. 
</P>
<P>
	That would achieve another GOP goal: making it harder for  
President Clinton and Democrats to use the extra surpluses for 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	As before, White House aides accused Republicans of unwisely  
planning to use surpluses for tax cuts instead of helping Medicare, 
which faces financial problems in the coming decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our concern right now is the fact that they are planning a  
large tax cut, rather than shoring up Medicare,'' White House 
spokesman Barry Toiv said. 
</P>
<P>
	By awaiting the new projections, Republicans seem to be risking  
little. In recent years, CBO repeatedly has made its forecasts more 
optimistic, only to underestimate the health of the federal budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Many private analysts say the economy's continued strong  
performance -- growing 6.1 percent in 1999's final quarter -- means 
the surplus trend is only upward, although the magnitude is 
unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers should inch up,'' said Ethan Harris, a senior  
economist with Lehman Brothers in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	When CBO last week updated its January projections, the agency's  
forecast for the 2000 surplus had grown from $131 billion to $133 
billion in that short two-month period. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Republican leaders revealed details of their plan to  
ensure that Social Security surpluses totaling $1.8 trillion over 
the next decade be used only to strengthen that program or to 
reduce the accumulated national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is part of their fight with Clinton over which side  
would do more to protect Social Security, the government's most 
popular and politically sensitive program. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the GOP proposal, the public debt would have to decline  
every two years by an amount equal to the Social Security surpluses 
for that same period. Using the money for a purpose other than 
Social Security would require 60 Senate votes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to locking away every penny of the Social  
Security trust fund surpluses for our nation's elderly,'' said 
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	With Social Security facing fiscal pressures from the impending  
retirement of baby boomers, the White House's Toiv said the GOP 
plan does not extend Social Security's solvency ``by even one 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have said Clinton's plan for helping Social Security  
doesn't extend its life either. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
