<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carreras Sings Premiere of Opera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jose Carreras of Three Tenors fame is coming  
out of 12 years' absence from the American opera scene to take the 
title role tonight in ``Sly,'' a 72-year-old opera based on 
Shakespeare. 
</P>
<P>
	The opera, by Ernanno Wolf-Ferrari, has never been produced  
commercially in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spanish tenor, who has struggled with leukemia, continues to  
sing concerts that are less strenuous than major operatic roles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sly'' is directed by Marta Domingo, wife of another of the  
Three Tenors -- Placido Domingo, the artistic director and singing 
star of the Washington Opera. 
</P>
<P>
	The title character -- Christopher Sly -- is a beggar in the  
first, framework scene of a Shakespeare play, sleeping off a binge 
outside a tavern. A passing nobleman hauls him off to his castle on 
a cruel whim, dresses him in fine clothes and tries to convince him 
that he is a nobleman, suffering from amnesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone then sees a performance by a visiting troupe of  
Shakespeare's ``The Taming of the Shrew.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Sly nor the nobleman has anything to do with  
Shakespeare's main plot, and directors often leave this episode out 
of ``Shrew'' performances. But the Italian Giovacchino Forzano 
turned it into a tragic story, making Sly a poor poet who romances 
the nobleman's mistress and kills himself in the end. 
</P>
<P>
	The German-Italian composer Wolf-Ferrari made it into an opera,  
first performed in 1927 in Milan and later elsewhere in Europe, but 
never in North America. The composer is best known for lighter 
work, the operas ``Secrets of Suzanne'' and ``Jewels of the 
Madonna.'' Some critics consider ``Sly'' his best serious opera. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Opera has scheduled eight performances at the  
Kennedy Center this month, sung in Italian with English surtitles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 09:44:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel OKs ATM Fee Disclosure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Banking Committee overwhelmingly  
approved today a measure that would require ATM surcharges to be 
clearly disclosed at the teller machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel voted, 48-1, to attach the measure to sweeping  
legislation it was drafting that would lift the Depression-era 
barriers between banks, securities firms and insurance companies by 
allowing them to merge. 
</P>
<P>
	The sole dissenting vote came from Rep. Judy Biggert, R-Ill.,  
who said she believed the banks could sufficiently police 
themselves in operating automated teller machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The ATM surcharge measure, sponsored by the committee's  
chairman, Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, and its senior Democrat, Rep. 
John LaFalce of New York, was a compromise. It would require clear 
disclosure of the surcharges, which come on top of charges by 
customers' own banks for using a machine operated by another bank. 
In addition, consumers would have to be given the right to 
terminate their transaction before paying the double charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Many banks currently do those things voluntarily at the ATMs  
they operate. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier attempt to ban the surcharges outright, pushed by  
Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont, the House's lone independent, gave 
way to the compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bank fees are soaring and bank profits are at a record high,''  
Sanders said before the vote. ``Maybe it's time we stood up for the 
consumers rather than large banks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A surcharge ban was proposed last year by former Sen. Alfonse  
D'Amato, R-N.Y., then chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, but 
was rebuffed by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The most common ATM surcharge was $1.50 as of last fall, and 64  
percent of the nation's banks imposed them, according to a study by 
congressional investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Thursday, the Senate Banking Committee voted along party  
lines to approve and send to the full Senate a bill to overhaul the 
financial services laws proposed by Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, 
and opposed by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In its current form, it would face a White House veto because  
Clinton believes the bill fails to protect consumers and would hurt 
community lending laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial overhaul legislation being drafted by the House  
banking panel, by contrast, is a bipartisan compromise bill for 
which the Clinton administration has indicated its strong support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 22:12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Urge More Hockey Padding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Young hockey players might want to check out  
better padding before they face off -- their very lives may be at 
stake. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors on Wednesday recommended that young players should wear  
better neck and chest padding to protect against rare but 
catastrophic blows that can trigger cardiac arrest or strokes. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Barry Maron of the Minneapolis Heart Institute said he knows  
of 12 cases over the last 15 years in which young male players died 
suddenly on the ice after being struck by hockey pucks or fists. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not trying to scare the populace,'' Maron said.  
``Sports is safe. But we also need to inform the public about 
risks, even when they are small.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts have calculated that overall, about one in 200,000  
school-age athletes dies annually from accidents on the playing 
field. Maron said that he believes many hockey fatalities haven't 
been reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Maron, who released his figures at a meeting in New Orleans of  
the American College of Cardiology, said padding typically worn by 
young hockey players does not completely cover the neck, and the 
area over the chest is usually totally exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Routine blows to the neck can rupture the arteries that feed the  
brain, triggering bleeding strokes. Even seemingly innocent blows 
to the chest can cause cardiac arrest if they happen at precisely 
the right moment in the heartbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The heart is most vulnerable during the repolarizing phase, when  
it is preparing to contract again. On an electrocardiogram, this 
point is called the T-wave, and it comprises about one-hundredth of 
the entire heartbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitting the chest at this point can put the heart into  
fibrillation, which is deadly unorganized quivering. When this 
happens, athletes instantly collapse and usually cannot be revived 
with CPR. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Adolph Hutter of Massachusetts General Hospital said he  
agrees that young hockey players -- especially those 8 to 13 -- 
should have better chest and neck protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we are calling for is very simple,'' Hutter said.  
``Preventing even five or six deaths is worth it. We're not talking 
about changing the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hutter said extra chest protection may not be needed for older  
players, since their chests are less pliable. Hutter is team 
cardiologist to the Boston Bruins and a former president of the 
college of cardiology. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 12 hockey fatalities compiled by Maron, six resulted from  
blows to the chest, five to the neck and one to the face. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 23:42:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fight Is Big But Not Ali-Frazier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lennox Lewis believes his fight against Evander Holyfield  
matches the two best heavyweights on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	They are -- and their scheduled 12-round bout Saturday night in  
Madison Square Garden is a major match. More than 20,000 fans will 
fill the arena, and some people are comparing it to The Fight 
between Joe Frazier and Muhammad Ali on March 8, 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Such comparisons are unfair to Holyfield and Lewis. They have  
fought their way to this showdown and should be judged on their 
merits. 
</P>
<P>
	Their fight has many intriguing aspects.  
</P>
<P>
	How will Holyfield be affected by his age (36), numerous hard  
fights and the 6-foot-5 Lewis' size and strength? How will Lewis 
handle the tension of his first super fight? Does he have the chin 
and stamina needed to win? Does the laid-back Lewis have the desire 
to beat one of boxing's great warriors? 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's not The Fight, a match that took the Big Apple by  
the throat and shook it like it hasn't been shaken since. 
</P>
<P>
	It had everything. It was a battle between two unbeaten  
heavyweights. Frazier was the champion, but many people thought the 
only way he could truly claim the title was to beat Ali, from whom 
the championship was stripped for his refusal to accept the 
military draft. 
</P>
<P>
	So it had a real sense of drama, spiced by the fact that two  
fighters were each getting the unheard of sum of $2.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	It also had the greatest publicist in the history of boxing --  
Ali. himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali turned news conferences into shows.  
</P>
<P>
	Unlike most such news conferences today, the fighters did most  
of the talking. When one of the fighters was Ali, a press 
conference could turn into a monologue. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali's points victory over Joe Bugner in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia,  
was forgettable. Not so the prefight news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	It turned out that the commission member in charge of the gloves  
was a prison official and so the gloves were going to kept at the 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're putting my gloves in jail; My gloves are going to  
jail,'' bellowed Ali. ``They ain't done nothing . . . yet!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even weigh-ins became circuses when Ali was involved. In fact,  
when Ali retired, heavyweight weigh-ins should have been stopped. 
The fighters should be weighed privately, and their weights given 
to the media on mimeographed sheets. That's how interesting they 
have become. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali turned the weigh-in for his challenge to the menacing Sonny  
Liston at Miami Beach in 1964 into an event of its own. 
</P>
<P>
	He ranted and raved and convinced many reporters that he was so  
scared of the man he called the Bear that some of them thought the 
fight should be called off. Liston did not answer the bell for the 
seventh round, and boxing's most flamboyant career was launched. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, The Fight stands alone -- and that certainly is no putdown  
of the Holyfield-Lewis match. 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield has helped hype the bout by matter of factly  
predicting he will knock out Lewis in the third round. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali would have said, ``Lennox Lewis came from over to sea, and  
it's a long way to come just to get knocked out in three.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
