<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Citigroup Exec To Join MasterCard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Citigroup, which is loosening its ties with Visa  
USA, is getting a seat on the downsized board of directors of 
MasterCard International. 
</P>
<P>
	While MasterCard announced Wednesday it was slashing the size of  
its board nearly in half, the credit card association also 
nominated two new directors, including a Citigroup executive. 
</P>
<P>
	In the shake-up, the MasterCard board will be cut to 17 members  
from 31. The new members will be Robert B. Willumstad, head of 
global consumer lending for Citigroup, and Hiroshi Arai, president 
and chairman of Orient Corp. of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last month, Citigroup's two representatives on the Visa  
board resigned in a dispute over Citigroup's plans to build up its 
own credit card brand image at the expense of Visa's. 
</P>
<P>
	Citigroup wanted to issue credit cards with the ``Citi'' name on  
the front and the Visa logo on the back. While Visa balked, 
MasterCard, which has been losing market share, swept in and made a 
deal with Citigroup. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe the way MasterCard is restructuring its board is  
going to be more aligned with our strategic thinking,'' said Susan 
Weeks, a spokeswoman for New York-based Citigroup. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect, over time, to issue a larger proportion of  
MasterCards in the United States than we have in the past, but we 
will continue to issue Visa cards,'' she added. 
</P>
<P>
	While MasterCard is expected to let Citigroup move the logo to  
the back of the card, Weeks said, ``Any decision (about the logo) 
would have to go before the MasterCard board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MasterCard said its decision to cut 14 board seats was part of a  
wider effort within the association to increase its flexibility and 
allow it to respond quickly to the fast-changing economic 
environment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The change in the structure of our board, together with the  
recent realignment of our internal resources, is a strong 
demonstration of MasterCard's leadership, flexibility and intense 
focus on serving our most important customers,'' Robert W. 
Selander, president and chief executive of MasterCard, said in a 
statement. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 14:36:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prostate Cancer Kills 40,000 a Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Prostate cancer is second only to lung cancer among cancer  
killers of American men, taking about 40,000 lives annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Most prostate cancer happens sporadically; patients have no  
particular family history of the disease. However, about 1 in 10 
cases seems to be clearly inherited because many men in the same 
family have it. 
</P>
<P>
	There were an estimated 179,300 new cases of prostate cancer in  
the United States last year. More than 75 percent of all cases are 
diagnosed in men older than 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the symptoms of prostate cancer include interrupted  
urine flow or the inability to urinate, the need to urinate 
frequently, blood in the urine, continuing pain in the lower back, 
pelvis or upper thighs. 
</P>
<P>
	The method of treatment depends on age, stage of the cancer and  
other medical conditions. Hormone treatment may control prostate 
cancer for long periods by shrinking the size of the tumor and 
relieving pain. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past 20 years, the survival rate for all prostate cases,  
regardless of stage, has increased from 67 percent to 93 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the most recent data, 68 percent of men diagnosed  
survive 10 years and 52 percent survive 15 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:52:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Announcement Focuses GOP Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole, taking a first, formal  
step toward a possible run for president, says it's high time that 
the nation's leaders restore voters' faith in their government -- to 
``call America to her better nature.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was among the themes the former U.S. labor and  
transportation secretary touted in a TV ad that was to accompany 
her announcement that she was forming an exploratory committee for 
the 2000 GOP presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's announcement at a rally here moves Mrs. Dole to the  
first tier of potential Republican contenders. Most polls have 
shown her and Texas Gov. George W. Bush far ahead of lesser-known 
potential Republican rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	In making her announcement, Mrs. Dole pointed to her experiences  
serving under five presidents but maintained a distance between 
herself and any rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a politician and, frankly, today that may be a plus,''  
Mrs. Dole said in her television ad, which was to air in Iowa and 
New Hampshire. Aides said the ad would flesh out the themes of a 
Dole campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politics and the politics of governing have become so  
negative, so paralyzed by special interests, that as a people we're 
beginning to lose faith in our own institutions,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her opening pitch took a not-too-subtle poke at President  
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I run, this will be why: I believe our people are looking  
for leaders who will call America to her better nature,'' Mrs. Dole 
said. ``Yes, we've been let down, and by people we should have been 
able to look up to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the resume Mrs. Dole brings to a field of GOP contenders  
that could reach double digits: A very prominent and widely 
recognized name, extensive government experience and decades of 
campaigning as a surrogate for her husband, 1996 GOP presidential 
nominee Bob Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen many presidential campaigns up close,'' Mrs. Dole  
said in her 15-minute ad. ``I know what they entail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She's going to bring a grace and a dignity to the race,'' said  
Ralph Reed, a consultant and former head of the Christian Coalition 
who is offering advice to Bush. ``I'm glad she's running. This 
nominating campaign is shaping into an embarrassment of riches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After today's announcement, Mrs. Dole's opening campaign swing  
takes her to Arizona, then to New Hampshire, before she heads back 
to her home in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's precinct caucuses mark the initial test of the  
presidential nominating season next February, while New Hampshire 
holds the first primary shortly after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole has headed the Federal Trade Commission, served as  
secretaries of labor and transportation and been president of the 
American Red Cross. Some strategists argue that her Red Cross 
background insulates her from charges often hurled at Republicans 
that the party lacks compassion. 
</P>
<P>
	She hammered that experience in her TV pitch to voters.  
</P>
<P>
	``In my eight years at the American Red Cross, I saw things that  
will haunt me the rest of my life,'' she said. ``But I also saw the 
power of the human heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole said her early travels left her ``buoyed by the  
goodness of our citizens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Which is why I am ready to take the next step,'' Mrs. Dole  
said. ``This week, I have filed papers to form an exploratory 
committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among benefits Mrs. Dole brings to the campaign is her gender,  
some analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gender plays into it to the extent that having a very visible  
and viable female candidate causes women voters to pay closer 
attention to the Republican primaries,'' said Ed Gillespie, a 
consultant allied with Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, a likely 
presidential candidate in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole has certainly gotten the attention of potential rivals  
like Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've long since passed the time when Americans are  
uncomfortable with women in any position of leadership,'' Gore 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Reed argued that Bush has laid claim to the pillars of the  
Republican establishment, pointing to a broad range of prominent 
Republicans who joined the Texas governor last Sunday as he 
announced his exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Bush exploratory committee, you had the full range of  
the diversity of the Republican Party,'' said Reed. ``Bush has 
probably raised the bar for all subsequent contenders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others suggested that front-runners like Mrs. Dole and Bush will  
stumble when they begin to face contentious issues that divide 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of soft underbelly when it comes to an issues  
campaign for this establishment candidate,'' said Greg Mueller, a 
consultant allied with publisher Steve Forbes and former 
communications director for conservative 1996 candidate Pat 
Buchanan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Signs $1B Aluminum Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will buy more than $1  
billion in recycled aluminum over the next 13 years to use in 
making engines and components. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker has agreed to buy all of the recycled aluminum  
that Imco Recycling Inc. will produce at a new plant it plans to 
build in Zilwaukee. The plant will be situated near a GM Saginaw 
Metal Casting Operations, a powertrain facility. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this is a tremendous win for our foundry in Saginaw  
because it provides a solid future for our employees and provides 
numerous environmental benefits,'' John Stiles, executive director 
of GM purchasing of metals, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement with Imco, which is based in Irving, Texas, calls  
for almost 2 billion pounds of recycled aluminum over the next 13 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Recycled aluminum has become the largest single component of the  
national auto supply, said Imco chairman Don Ingram. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingram said about 65 percent of the aluminum used in automobiles  
is recycled metal. He said the percentage could rise as more usable 
scrap become available. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with Imco is the third major aluminum agreement GM has  
made in the last four months. In November, GM announced a 10-year 
agreement with Alcan Aluminium Ltd. to buy aluminum. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Imco rose almost 25 percent, or $2.93 3/4 to $14.75 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
