<DOCNO> APW19990310.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 22:25:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Campaigns in Home State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Former Sen. Bill Bradley, who set high  
school basketball records in his native Missouri, says there is one 
key statistic in his favor in his run for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	He's the only announced challenger to Vice President Al Gore for  
the Democratic presidential nomination next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``What pack?'' Bradley said Wednesday when asked how he will  
distinguish himself from other Democrats. ``And my guess is, it 
will remain a two-person race, which will be an interesting 
dynamic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, 55, spoke at a news conference sandwiched between a  
breakfast meeting with Kansas City friends and a major fund-raiser 
in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	An advocate of campaign finance reform during his 18 years in  
the U.S. Senate, he is refusing donations from political action 
committees and trying to raise $20 million through $1,000 
contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I have to reach out to the widest range of friends,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	As he has throughout the young campaign, Bradley declined to  
criticize Gore. Instead, he focused on the differences in their 
``life experiences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The vice president has spent most of his life in Washington,''  
Bradley said of Gore, whose late father was a longtime U.S. senator 
from Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, Bradley said, he grew up in a small community --  
Crystal City, on the Mississippi River -- and traveled widely for 30 
years, first during 10 years with the New York Knicks of the 
National Basketball Association and later as a New Jersey 
politician, author and businessman. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley was widely mentioned as a possible presidential  
candidate in 1988 and again in 1992, but has said the timing never 
felt right until now. 
</P>
<P>
	He was asked about recent polls showing that Americans would  
favor probable Republican presidential candidates George W. Bush of 
Texas and Elizabeth Dole over the Democrat Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to have a nominee who can win,'' Bradley said. ``I  
think I can win.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
