<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 14:36:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Stays With Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- A senior DaimlerChrysler official said  
Wednesday that the giant carmaker had never threatened to end its 
support of the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to an article in the Sydney Morning Herald, senior  
vice president Matthias Kleinert said the company had no plans to 
cut its ties to the International Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Kleinert said his comments to the Australian newspaper were  
misleading because they had been taken ``fully out of context.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are convinced that the problems of the IOC will be solved  
next week in Lausanne,'' Kleinert said. ``An end of our involvement 
is therefore not a topic of discussion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney Morning Herald quoted Kleinert as saying that the car  
maker's continued support was conditional upon IOC making its 
finances and business open. 
</P>
<P>
	Kleinert said he was only trying to describe procedures in the  
world of business and that DaimlerChrysler ``would not get involved 
in the discussions on IOC structures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We see no reason to doubt the IOC's determination to draw  
consequences from the affair,'' Kleinert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although not an official sponsor, the company has been  
supporting the IOC since 1964. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us, it's a give and take,'' Kleinert said.  
</P>
<P>
	The partnership allowed the car company to enter new markets, he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cooperation has been going on without problems, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have been in constant contact with the IOC leadership since  
the beginning of the affair and we saw no reason to draw any 
consequences,'' Kleinert said. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract with the IOC runs through 2004.  
</P>
<P>
	The IOC is holding an emergency session next week at its seat in  
Lausanne, Switzerland to discuss the case of IOC members accused of 
accepting lavish gifts from Salt Lake City before the U.S. city won 
the vote in 1995 to stage the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
