<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Austerity Measure Passed in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's government has won an  
important vote in its bid to pass a major austerity measure 
expected to yield $8 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chamber of Deputies voted 357-135 late Tuesday to increase a  
tax on financial transactions. The lower house must vote one more 
time for the measure to make it law. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's upper house, the Senate, passed the bill in January.  
</P>
<P>
	The measure is the last in a $14.9 billion austerity plan that  
helped ensure Brazil a $41.5 billion loan from the International 
Monetary Fund and other lenders in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has already started work on a new set of  
belt-tightening measures since its currency plunged 40 percent 
after the central bank let it float freely starting Jan. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Finance Ministry and the IMF made public Brazil's  
revised 1999 economic targets. These include a budget surplus of 
3.1 percent and 16.8 percent inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	To achieve the targets, the government plans to freeze salaries  
of 500,000 civil servants, speed up privatization and raise 
electric energy charges, among other measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
