<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Probes Fight Over Generic Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Generic drugs were once seen as the solution to  
rising cost of brand-name prescription drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	But large pharmaceutical companies have become increasingly  
sophisticated at starving off generic competitors by finding ways 
to extend the patent life of their blockbuster drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the federal government is taking a hard look at whether all  
the methods pass legal muster. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts, though, expect little to come of the  
investigation because they believe the companies, such as Eli Lilly 
and Dupont, are acting within their rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``The companies are all doing the normal practices that they  
have to do to protect their franchises,'' said Hemant Shah, a drug 
analyst with HKS &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission is looking at deals drug companies  
have with potential rivals and other activities undertaken to 
protect their patents. The agency's widened inquiry was first 
reported in the Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, for example, Eli Lilly formed an agreement to buy a  
modified form of Prozac from Sepracor, a company that specializes 
in removing dangerous side effects from established drugs and 
licensing the rights back to the manufacturer. The FTC is 
requesting more information on that deal, Eli Lilli officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is valuable to Lilly because Prozac, which had nearly  
$3 billion in worldwide sales in 1998, is expected to lose patent 
protection in the next two years. While Sepracor isn't a generic 
drug maker, it illustrates Lilly's desire to hold onto the rights 
to desirable second-generation drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Lilly-Sepracor deal is an exclusive arrangement it  
eliminates a potential rival in a class of drugs dominated by 
Prozac. 
</P>
<P>
	A second generation Prozac drug made by Lilly would likely  
hamper potential sales of a generic competitor to the existing 
Prozac drug because the newer form would have fewer side effects, 
analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulatory concerns have been fueled as drug prices continue to  
increase at more than twice the overall inflation rate. The higher 
prices combined with the rising demand for new drugs has placed a 
difficult burden on private and public health insurance programs. 
``We think this is positive that the FTC is looking into this, and 
at least calling into question the parameters of these deals,'' 
said Carole Cox, a spokeswoman for generic drugmaker Barr 
Laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	An FTC spokeswoman said the agency does not comment on  
investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Barr is suing Lilly for blocking its ability to make a generic  
form of Prozac. Barr is also suing Dupont, which has cracked down 
on Barr's efforts to sell its generic form of the blood thinner 
Coumadin. Dupont asserts that Barr's generic copy is not equivalent 
to Coumadin. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox said the FTC contacted the company last month about Prozac  
and Coumadin issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Some companies, such as Abbott Laboratories, have paid potential  
generic rivals not to produce a generic drug until they resolve 
their litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst David Saks of Gruntal &AMP; Co. said that may appear  
anti-consumer, but such deals help both firms, and ensure a generic 
version eventually does come to market. Without such an agreement, 
major pharmaceutical companies could keep small generic firms in 
court for years before resolving patent disputes, he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
