<DOCNO> APW19990310.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 07:17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coaches Say Ruling Could Open Doors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- NCAA coaches say a federal court ruling  
tossing out the NCAA's minimum test score requirement might help 
many student athletes get educations they couldn't otherwise 
afford. 
</P>
<P>
	But the four high school athletes who sued the NCAA in 1997 on  
grounds of discrimination for eligibility rules barring them from 
athletic scholarships have already found other ways to attend 
college. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge barred enforcement of an NCAA rule saying  
students must score at least 820 on the Scholastic Assessment Test 
to compete as college freshmen, in addition to achieving a 2.5 
grade-point average in 13 ``core'' courses. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling would have helped one of the Philadelphia plaintiffs  
in the 1997 lawsuit, Leatrice Shaw, now competing for the 
University of Miami as a junior, according to her foster father, 
Robert Massie. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the rule, when Shaw was a freshman she could only  
practice with the Miami track team, said Massie, head track coach 
at Simon Gratz High School, where Shaw and fellow plaintiff Tai 
Kwan Cureton were high school stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they went to compete, she had to wave `bye-bye,''' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cureton was able to compete as a freshman by going to Wheaton  
College in Massachusetts, a Division III school where the SAT 
minimum did not apply. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tai Kwan was president of the Student Government Association  
(at Gratz) and president of the senior class, but he didn't have 
the SAT scores,'' Massie said. ``Leatrice was a member of the 
National Honor Society. She took the test three times. She came up 
10 points short.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Temple basketball coach John Chaney said the SAT requirement was  
``a denial of opportunity and access for youngsters and targeted 80 
to 90 percent black, Hispanic, poor and disadvantaged youngsters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If upheld, the ruling could restore a lost year of eligibility  
to athletes like Temple senior guard Rasheed Brokenborough, who sat 
out his freshman year due to the SAT cutoff and ran up $15,000 in 
debt because he could not qualify for a scholarship that year, 
Chaney said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who wouldn't like to get another year back?'' said  
Brokenborough, who said that although he is graduating, he would 
use the additional year of eligibility to pursue graduate studies. 
``I only got to play three years of basketball and I'd like to come 
back a fourth year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw did not immediately return messages left on her answering  
machine seeking comment Tuesday. Massie said he told her about the 
ruling Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's happy about it,'' but since Shaw is entering her junior  
year ``she's not really affected by it,'' Massie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other plaintiffs were Alexander Wesby, a basketball player now  
in his freshman year at Temple, and Andrea Gardner, a junior on the 
track team at Howard University. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner could not immediately be reached at Howard, where  
university offices and the athletic department were closed due to a 
snowstorm. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State Coach Joe Paterno, an early strong advocate of  
tougher academic standards, declined to comment on the new ruling, 
saying he wanted to find out more about the details of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	When the NCAA launched eligibility reforms in the early 1980s,  
Paterno said that a lack of standards hurt a generation of black 
students by allowing them into college unprepared for the academic 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke Coach Mike Krzyzewski, president of the National  
Association of Basketball Coaches, said the group has long been 
concerned about how the minimum test score would affect youths from 
lower socioeconomic backgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``This court ruling will certainly open a new discussion for  
creating better legislation for all youngsters,'' Krzyzewski said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes the SAT is viewed as a measure of kids' innate  
abilities. It's not. It's a measure of learned skills,'' said Andy 
Rosen, chief executive officer of Kaplan Educational Centers in New 
York, which offer education and career services including test 
preparation training. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaplan runs a ``Good Sports Athletic Scholars Program'' designed  
to help about 200 students a year in poor neighborhoods meet the 
NCAA eligibility requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a fun class, too,'' said Lawrence Wade, a junior at  
Eastern High School in Washington, D.C., who hopes to play football 
at a college such as Maryland, North Carolina State or Florida 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the training, the SAT requirement could make that a  
distant dream, Wade said. ``I took a practice SAT. It was kind of 
hard. I think they should consider other things as well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
