<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Wednesday as  
Tokyo stocks soared and Japanese companies brought yen back home 
before the close of the fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also fell against the euro as investors became less  
concerned that Europe would lower interest rates or that the United 
States would raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think (the dollar's) pausing to take a breath,'' said Robert  
Katz, a foreign exchange dealer at MTB Bank Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 119.88  
Japanese yen, down from 121.00 yen on Tuesday. The euro was quoted 
at $1.0940, up from $1.0890. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, the yen got a boost as one of the key indices  
gauging the Nikkei stock average rose 2.54 percent to 15,480.00, 
its highest close since August 10. On Tuesday, the index climbed 
2.15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the rally boosted demand for yen.  
</P>
<P>
	``The market doesn't have much appetite for further (dollar)  
buying now,'' said Koichi Kubo, assistant general manager for the 
foreign group at Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank in Tokyo. ``Market sentiment 
is that it is still top-heavy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Corporations and banks were still selling dollars and  
dollar-denominated assets and bringing yen home to boost balance 
sheets before the end of the Japanese fiscal year on March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4603 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4667, and 1.5222 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5178. The British 
pound rose to $1.6271, up from $1.6186. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7876 German 
marks, down from 1.7960; 5.9952 French francs, down from 6.0241; 
and 1,769.91 Italian lire, down from 1,779.36. 
</P>
</TEXT>
