<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SLOC Finance Director Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The finance director for the Salt Lake  
Organizing Committee has quit. 
</P>
<P>
	Rod Hamson was already out on administrative leave while SLOC  
determined his role in the Olympics bid scandal. He was one of two 
employees put on leave Jan. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The other, senior vice president of marketing and legal affairs  
Kelly Flint, returned to work last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamson submitted his resignation last Friday but gave no reason  
for quitting, SLOC spokesman Frank Zang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamson joined the bid effort in 1989 as a volunteer and was  
later hired as finance and licensing director. 
</P>
<P>
	An independent ethics panel last month blamed Tom Welch, former  
head of the bid committee, and David Johnson, senior vice 
president, for lavishing more than $1 million in gifts, cash and 
other favors on International Olympic Committee members and their 
families during the bidding for the 2002 Winter Games. Hamson 
prepared vouchers for checks co-signed by Flint that paid for 
relatives of IOC members to live in the United States and attend 
American universities, the ethics panel reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Flint told the ethics panel he thought the checks were  
authorized under a scholarship program. He said he had no way of 
knowing that the names on the checks belonged to relatives of IOC 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	The report described Hamson as a fresh college graduate who was  
given the title of finance director, but who had no leadership 
role. Hamson socialized with IOC members and simply did what he was 
told by Welch and Johnson, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this regard, he was not unlike other bid committee  
employees who were aware of educational grants to IOC relatives and 
had suspicions about direct payments,'' the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
