<HEADLINE> Year in Jail for Fake Kidnap Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) -- A man was sentenced to one year in  
jail for a fund-raiser in which he asked people to donate the 
ransom money he needed to free his kidnapped daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Norbert Michalski, of Sterling Heights, was sentenced Tuesday to  
one year in jail for the October 1997 fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
	Michalski claimed his daughter had been kidnapped by his former  
wife, but the girl had actually been taken into protective custody 
because her mother had a drug problem, and Michalski knew that, 
Eastpointe police Detective Leon Berdy said today. 
