<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spacecraft Begins Mapping of Mars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Mars Global Surveyor has finally begun  
mapping the red planet, turning an array of instruments on Earth's 
dusty neighbor a year later than originally planned. 
</P>
<P>
	``All our instruments are on now,'' flight operations manager  
Joseph Beerer said Tuesday at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 
Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
	The spacecraft, which started its primary mission Monday  
afternoon, has a camera to make wide- and narrow-angle images of 
Mars, and a laser altimeter to measure surface features by bouncing 
pulses of light off the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	It also carries a spectrometer to scan for heat transferred from  
the planet to the atmosphere and to map mineral composition, and a 
magnetometer to gather data that can be used to understand the 
interior of Mars. 
</P>
<P>
	The spacecraft has already delivered a preview of the science  
portion of its mission. It has sent back detailed images of such 
features as 16-mile-high Olympus Mons and the planet's ancient 
water and lava flows. 
</P>
<P>
	The surveyor was launched in November 1996 and went into orbit  
around Mars in September 1997. It was supposed to begin its primary 
mapping mission a year ago after using a process called aerobraking 
to tighten its orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	Mapping had to be put off for a year because a damping mechanism  
on one of its two solar panels did not operate properly when it was 
deployed and controllers decided to avoid stressing the part by a 
gradual aerobraking. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellite is in a two-hour orbit. Instruments will gather  
data during nine of each day's orbits and then the spacecraft will 
be turned to point its antenna at Earth to transmit that data 
during three orbits, Beerer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 09:58:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oscar Looks to Past for Best Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hollywood may be obsessed with the here and  
now, but the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences voters 
dipped into the recent and distant past to select the nominees for 
best movie of 1998. Three concern World War II, two are set in 
Elizabethan times. 
</P>
<P>
	Costume pictures are out of fashion in American studios, partly  
because of the cost of creating bygone attire and settings. Another 
factor: young ticket buyers, the core audience, like contemporary 
themes, often laced with sex and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Academy members in the past two decades have often favored  
period films of an epic nature, filmed abroad. Among the best 
picture winners: ``Chariots of Fire,'' ``Gandhi,'' ``Amadeus,'' 
``Out of Africa,'' ``Platoon,'' ``The Last Emperor,'' ``Schindler's 
List,'' ``Braveheart,'' ``The English Patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As well as similarity of themes, the five nominees for the 71st  
best-picture Oscar are filmmaking of uncommonly high quality. 
That's what makes predictions so hard. Here is a rundown: 

</P>
<P>
                  	 *``ELIZABETH'' (7 nominations)    	
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, there wasn't any tortured story with  
'Elizabeth,''' says Russell Schwartz, president of Gramercy 
Pictures. ``It wasn't nine years in the making, it wasn't in 18 
different versions... . Based on Michael Hirst's first draft, we 
all agreed that this was something we had to put on as fast a track 
as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The producers were not worried about ``Elizabeth,'' starring  
Cate Blanchette as England's Queen Elizabeth, being a costume 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``The secret is how you make it relevant to a contemporary  
audience,'' Schwartz observed. ``What was happening in Elizabeth's 
16th-century court could certainly be happening in a 20th-century 
court -- or suite. We always saw the movie as the 'Godmother' or the 
'Godfather' of the 16th century. We tried to sell it as a 
historical thriller.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gramercy took chances on a virtually unknown leading lady,  
Australia's Blanchette, and a director, India's Shekhar Kapur, who 
had never made an English-language film. Amazingly for a movie of 
such scope, ``Elizabeth'' cost only about $19 million. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
               	 *``LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL'' (7 nominations)    	
</P>
<P>
	Having established himself as Italy's most popular film and  
television comedian, Roberto Benigni decided to try something very 
different with ``Life Is Beautiful'' (``La Vita E Bella''). 
</P>
<P>
	A Holocaust comedy may seem like the worst of oxymorons. Yet  
director-writer-actor Benigni managed to get laughs as well as 
pathos out of his tale of an Italian Jew who saves his son from the 
horror of a concentration camp by making a game of their 
imprisonment. 
</P>
<P>
	Some accused Benigni of trivializing the subject. At a forum  
after the premiere in Jerusalem, he was warned, ``It's dangerous to 
laugh at the Holocaust.'' Almost in tears, the comedian declared 
the film was ``invented from truth,'' adding, ``It's my best cry 
and scream about the Holocaust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acclaimed at the Cannes Film Festival, ``Life Is Beautiful'' has  
become the biggest foreign-language moneymaker in the United 
States, surpassing 1996's ``Il Postino.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Life Is Beautiful'' is only the second film to be nominated  
for both picture and foreign-language picture in the same year. The 
other was ``Z'' in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *``SAVING PRIVATE RYAN'' (11 nominations)    	
</P>
<P>
	``I made this picture for my father and the rest of his  
generation who fought the war,'' says Steven Spielberg of ``Saving 
Private Ryan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The director, who had dealt with the Holocaust in ``Schindler's  
List,'' turned to World War II with ``Saving Private Ryan,'' 
covering the heroics and tragedies of American GIs from Omaha Beach 
to the French interior. He was determined to make the battle scenes 
as realistic as possible. The gore of the opening D-day sequence 
drew gasps from audiences and earned an R rating because of the 
violence -- unusual for a Spielberg film. That did not seem to 
hinder ``Saving Private Ryan'' at the box office, however. This 
year's re-release brought the domestic total over $200 million, 
displacing ``Armageddon'' as the top moneymaker released in the 
United States and Canada in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Spielberg's urge to depict World War II began when, as a  
movie-mad teen-ager, he was impressed by the raw realism of the 
1949 William Wellman film, ``Battleground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to make the kind of war film about which a veteran of  
Omaha Beach might remark, 'This is pretty close to what it was 
like,' '' Spielberg has said. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
             	 *``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE'' (13 nominations)    	
</P>
<P>
	Unlike ``Elizabeth,'' ``Shakespeare in Love'' followed a rocky  
road to completion. In 1991, writer Marc Norman sold Universal 
Pictures on the idea of a young Will Shakespeare who found his love 
and inspiration while barely surviving as an actor and playwright 
in London. A script was written, and in 1994 Edward Zwick 
(``Glory'') was primed to direct, with Julia Roberts as Will's 
love. 
</P>
<P>
	``But they were unable to find the right actor for  
Shakespeare,'' says Donna Gigliotti, who became a producer of the 
final project. ``Sometimes at big studios when things fall apart 
they're pretty hard to resurrect. So it went on the shelf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gigliotti, who was in charge of European production for  
Miramax Films and is now an independent producer, recommended the 
script to her then-boss, Harvey Weinstein. After lengthy 
negotiations, Miramax acquired the project, with Universal 
remaining as co-financer and overseas distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Stoppard contributed to the script, John Madden (``Mrs.  
Brown'') came on as director, and Gwyneth Paltrow and Joseph 
Fiennes became the stars. For a film that cost in the low $20 
millions and has already grossed more than $60 million 
domestically, it has proven a wise investment for Miramax and its 
parent, the Walt Disney Co. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
               	 *``THE THIN RED LINE'' (7 nominations)    	
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five years ago, writer-director Terrence Malick made the  
critically acclaimed ``Badlands.'' Five years later he made the 
stunningly beautiful ``Days of Heaven.'' Then for the next two 
decades he made -- nothing, and became an enigma. 
</P>
<P>
	Malick's return to filmmaking with James Jones' war novel, ``The  
Thin Red Line,'' seemed destined to be a film event. While reviews 
were mixed, most critics agreed that Malick's talent for capturing 
a poetic beauty amid human brutality remained unimpaired. 
</P>
<P>
	The screen rights to Jones' novel of GIs during the Guadalcanal  
campaign were acquired in 1988. With customary thoroughness, Malick 
worked years on the script. He intended only to write, but was 
persuaded to direct as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Malick's name was enough to attract actors such as Sean Penn,  
Nick Nolte, John Cusack, Woody Harrelson, George Clooney and Ted 
Danson, some of them for roles of only a few minutes. The company 
shot two weeks of locations in Guadalcanal. The rest was filmed in 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	To no one's surprise, Malick has shunned all publicity for ``The  
Thin Red Line.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 11:36:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Condemns Russian Vandalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department on Wednesday deplored  
vandalism of a synagogue in Siberia and urged Russian leaders to 
speak out against anti-Semitism. 
</P>
<P>
	``The perpetrators of this crime in Novosibirsk must be brought  
to justice,'' said spokesman James P. Rubin, citing a rise in 
anti-Semitism in Russia, including recent anti-Semitic statements 
by leading members of the Communist Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Vandals threw Torahs on the floor and scrawled swastikas and  
anti-Semitic writings on the walls and ceiling of the Novosibirsk 
synagogue in southern Siberia late Sunday or early Monday, 
according to Jewish leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Police confirmed the incident but played down the seriousness of  
the attack. An investigator described it as ``kids having high 
jinks.'' Nobody claimed responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin noted that President Clinton has raised concern over  
attitudes toward Jews and other religious and ethnic minorities in 
Russia and said the United States rejects the activities of 
neo-fascist groups such as the Russian National Unity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anti-Semitism, racism and extremism have no place in any  
civilized society and must be strongly combated,'' said Rubin. 
``The issue remains a key element of our dialogue with the Russian 
leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin commended Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his  
government, however, for condemning anti-Semitism and other 
expressions of ethnic and religious hatred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
