<DOCNO> APW19990310.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 16:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Addresses Past in Guatemala  
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY, Guatemala (AP) -- Trying to heal old wounds,  
President Clinton today acknowledged the U.S. role in Central 
America's civil wars and repression but he urged that the United 
States now be viewed as ``a partner, a friend.'' Clinton said the 
United States was committed ``to shed light on the dark events of 
the past so that they are never repeated.'' His pledge to seek 
revisions in U.S. laws that discriminate by country in the 
treatment of illegal immigrants won loud applause from lawmakers 
from across Central America who had gathered for Clinton's address. 
Clinton also said he was seeking trade benefits for nations trying 
to rebuild after last fall's storms. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Hits New High on Gain of 79.08  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks shot to record highs today as oil prices  
soared, but concerns about technology-company earnings crimped 
gains in the Nadsaq Composite index. The Dow industrials climbed 
79.08 to 9,772.84, surpassing its previous high of 9,736.08, set 
last Friday. The Dow is now up 6.4 percent for the year. On the 
NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,676-1,344. The Nasdaq rose 13.07 to 
2,406.01. 

</P>
<P>
	Dole Moves Toward 2000 Run  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole moved a step closer to a  
full-fledged campaign for president, announcing the formation of an 
exploratory committee today. Mrs. Dole pointed to her experience as 
secretary of labor and secretary of transportation as well as her 
eight years heading the American Red Cross. Early polls have shown 
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Mrs. Dole far ahead of other 
potential GOP rivals. And a poll released today showed Mrs. Dole 
with 50 percent support compared to 45 percent for Vice President 
Al Gore in a one-on-one matchup. 

</P>
<P>
	Latest Susan McDougal Trial Opens  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- One of Kenneth Starr's prosecutors  
opened the latest trial of Susan McDougal today by charging that 
her refusal to testify has kept investigators from determining 
whether President Clinton lied under oath about his business 
dealings. Associate Independent Counsel Mark Barrett mentioned the 
president and Hillary Rodham Clinton 10 times during his opening 
statement, signaling the Clintons' conduct will be a key focus of 
the trial. But the lawyer for McDougal said that Starr's tactics 
will also be on trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Airline Passengers Gripe to Congress  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airline passengers packed a hearing today to  
tell their tales of alleged mistreatment by airline companies as 
lawmakers moved to improve protections of air travelers' rights. 
One women told the House Transportation Committee of being confined 
for nine hours on a Virgin Atlantic plane that never took off. When 
she declined to take another plane the next day, the airline 
refused to return her luggage. Panel Chairmain Bud Shuster, R-Pa., 
has introduced a bill that would require airlines to pay 
compensation to passengers kept waiting on a runway more than two 
hours. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic Again Rejects NATO Troops  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Defying pressure from senior U.S.  
envoy Richard Holbrooke and the threat of NATO airstrikes, Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic today rejected NATO forces to police a 
Kosovo peace agreement. Milosevic said the U.S.-sponsored peace 
plan is ``a good basis'' for a political settlement of the Kosovo 
crisis. But he continued to reject the key provision of NATO troop 
deployment. Meanwhile, in Kosovo, Yugoslav forces backed by tanks 
torched the homes of ethnic Albanians and sent hundreds fleeing. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombia Rebels Admit to Killings  
</P>
<P>
	SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's largest rebel  
group admitted that one of its officers kidnapped and killed three 
American activists found dead last week. The guerrilla commander 
acted without the approval of his superiors, said Raul Reyes, a 
senior commander of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia. 
Reyes said the guilty rebel officer may face the death penalty. The 
three Americans were setting up a school system for a local Indian 
group. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA To Fix Hubble Telescope  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA will launch an emergency repair  
mission this fall to the Hubble Space Telescope, which is in danger 
of shutting down. NASA decided today to move up the Hubble visit to 
October from June 2000. Although the $2 billion telescope would be 
safe in orbit, NASA does not want to risk losing any valuable 
science time. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees' Torre Has Prostate Cancer  
</P>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- New York Yankees manager Joe Torre left  
the World Series champions today for treatment of prostate cancer. 
It was not immediately clear how long he will be away from the team 
or what his course of treatment will be. Torre discovered he had 
the cancer from a test the Yankees required in response to Darryl 
Strawberry's colon-cancer diagnosis in October. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
