<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Plans Flight Safety Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A soon-to-retire Navy admiral will lead a  
joint U.S.-Italian review of safety rules for U.S. military 
training flights originating from bases in Italy, the Pentagon 
announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-day review is designed to prevent the kind of mistakes  
that led to the Feb. 3, 1998, accident in which a Marine Corps jet 
severed cables holding a ski gondola near Cavalese, Italy, killing 
20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot of the EA-6B jet, Marine Capt. Richard Ashby, was  
acquitted last week in a military court-martial on 20 counts of 
involuntary manslaughter and negligent homicide. The Marines are 
likely to make a decision by the end of this week on whether to go 
ahead with the court-martial of Ashby's navigator on that flight, 
Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, who also faces a charge of obstruction of 
justice. 
</P>
<P>
	In the aftermath of the gondola accident, the Marines ordered a  
tightening of safety procedures, including a review of all maps to 
ensure that obstructions such as ski lifts are accurately plotted. 
Ashby's attorneys argued that his crew was given a flight map that 
did not show the cable his plane struck. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ashby flight originated at Aviano air base in northern  
Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint U.S.-Italian review of safety procedures will be  
headed by Adm. Joseph Prueher, who last month finished his tenure 
as commander in chief of the U.S. Pacific Command and is due to 
retire in May. Prueher previously served as commander of the U.S. 
6th Fleet, based at Naples, Italy, and is a naval aviator with more 
than 5,500 hours of experience in 52 types of aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Prueher is to ``assess the adequacy'' of operational and safety  
measures taken in the aftermath of the gondola incident and to 
recommend whether any additional measures are called for. He is to 
conduct the review jointly with Italian defense officials and 
report to the U.S. and Italian defense chiefs in 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine Corps, meanwhile, is weighing whether to proceed with  
the Schweitzer court-martial next week. The Ashby acquittal 
triggered speculation that the case against Schweitzer, 31, of 
Westbury, N.Y., would be dropped. Jury selection is scheduled to 
begin March 18 at Camp Lejeune, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision is up to Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of Marine  
Forces Atlantic. Marine officials said a possibility remains that 
Pace will decide to proceed with the case against Schweitzer. One 
alternative would be to drop the criminal case and go directly to 
administrative action that could include removing Schweitzer and 
Ashby from the Marines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
