<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stranded Pakistanis Reach Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas (AP) -- After months at sea with  
nowhere to go, the 740-foot Delta Pride is now a ghost ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Its 23-man Pakistani crew is alive and well, and most  
importantly, all of them are now ashore. The 12 remaining crew 
members finally made it to land Tuesday after a nearly year-long 
ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very thankful to God,'' Capt. Maqsood Ahmed said. ``We  
were prisoners at sea without committing a crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Delta Pride, which transported coal and other natural  
materials, became stranded in Tampico, Mexico, in May when its 
owner, Tri-star Shipping Lines of Karachi, went bankrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	A financial dispute with Mexican officials followed, leading to  
the seizure of the ship's documents and the crew's passports. 
</P>
<P>
	SOS calls were ignored as life aboard the ship became more  
desperate by the day. With fuel almost gone, there was no way to 
run the air conditioner or lights. The seamen lived off rain water 
and whatever fish they could catch. 
</P>
<P>
	With no clean water for bathing and washing clothes, rashes and  
early signs of scurvy were setting in. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people were dying in front of me,'' said Ahmed, who was on  
his first voyage as captain. 
</P>
<P>
	Although no one died, the men were threatening to commit mass  
suicide by November. That's when Ahmed found a $10 bill in a drawer 
and was inspired by the words ``In God We Trust.'' He gathered his 
crew and told them they were making a 300-mile journey to the 
United States for help. 
</P>
<P>
	They didn't have much fuel or even enough water to keep the  
engines cool. Also, two of three generators weren't working and the 
other kept catching fire. Any breakdown could have set them adrift. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delta Pride made it to U.S. waters on Nov. 24, but was  
denied the ship permission to pull into port because of mechanical 
problems and because it lacked documents guaranteeing payment if 
the ship caused any damage. Crew members couldn't come ashore 
because they had no passports. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven crew members with health problems were finally allowed to  
go home earlier this year, leaving Ahmed and 11 others. Chief 
officer Ahmed Shamshad, who had spent 2 1/2 years on the Delta Pride, 
didn't know if he'd ever see his wife and six children in Pakistan 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't have the hope that we would be alive and go home to  
our families,'' said Shamshad, a 28-year seaman who kissed the 
ground when he came ashore Tuesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The Immigration and Naturalization Service said the crewmen  
could remain in the country for 30 days while they worked out 
travel plans and other details. They will stay in a Catholic-run 
refugee center. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the abandoned ship was auctioned for scrap for  
$300,000 to ESCO, a North Carolina company. 
</P>
<P>
	Shamshad doubts he'll ever sail again.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is very difficult for my family,'' he said, noting that  
he's spoken to them for about three minutes in the past year. ``It 
was a very bad experience.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
