<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lamar Alexander Jumps In GOP Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- He's left the plaid shirt in the closet  
this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander launched his second bid  
for the Republican presidential nomination with a speech Tuesday 
before a few hundred supporters at the state Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	``I invite you to join me in a campaign to expand American  
freedom, renew its pioneer spirit and bring out the best in 
America,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander was to visit Washington today to pick up endorsements  
from Tennessee's two senators, Bill Frist and Fred Thompson. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it's on to New Hampshire and Iowa, the states most crucial  
to his candidacy because of their early primary and caucus. He'll 
also visit New York and Los Angeles before returning to his 
hometown of Maryville on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander sought the GOP nomination in 1996, but dropped out  
after the early primaries. He's been gunning for the 2000 election 
ever since, maintaining his campaign organization and fund-raising 
machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he hasn't done well in public opinion polls and is likely  
to have plenty of competition, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush, 
son of former President Bush. Elizabeth Dole, former American Red 
Cross president and Bob Dole's wife, planned to form an exploratory 
committee today. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan and New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith have already  
announced their candidacies. The 58-year-old Alexander said he's 
the most qualified, experienced candidate and has the best-defined 
proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, who announced his candidacy last time wearing a  
bright plaid shirt, wore a business suit this year. He has said 
that talk about his shirt interfered with his message in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The former U.S. education secretary and University of Tennessee  
president said he wants to let states decide how to spend federal 
education money, give more autonomy to teachers and principals and 
let parents decide where their children should attend classes. 
</P>
<P>
	He'd like to create a $1,500 scholarship for kindergarten  
through high school students similar to the HOPE program in 
Georgia, which provides poor and middle-class college students with 
financial help. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander also said he wants a missile defense system to target  
terrorists and a new branch of the armed services to stem the flow 
of drugs from other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	He said inheritance and capital gains taxes should be cut,  
married couples should get more of a tax break, the deduction for a 
child should be tripled and the tax code shouldn't discriminate 
against parents who stay home with their children. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander also took several digs at President Clinton, whom he  
called ``the Wizard'' and Vice President Al Gore, a fellow 
Tennessean likely to be the Democratic presidential nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look behind the screen of their magic show and see what has  
really happened in the last six years,'' Alexander said. ``Twelve 
more countries have jumped over us in high school graduation rates, 
our taxes are higher, our military defense is weaker, it is harder 
than ever for parents to raise children, ... and our standards of 
right and wrong have sunk to a new low.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
