<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Cautioned To Keep Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Financial institutions should make sure they  
set aside enough reserves for possible losses due to global 
financial turmoil, federal bank and security regulators warned 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement -- issued jointly by the Securities and Exchange  
Commission, Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., Federal Reserve Board, 
Office of the Comptroller of the Currency and Office of Thrift 
Supervision -- was issued as a followup to a warning in November 
against inflating loss reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	That earlier statement came after the SEC criticized the  
Atlanta-based SunTrust Banks Inc. for setting aside larger reserves 
than needed in order to use the money later during a possible 
downturn in earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest statement acknowledged ``continued uncertainty among  
financial institutions as to the expectations of the banking and 
securities regulators'' regarding loan loss reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	The agencies said they ``continue to emphasize the importance of  
depository institutions having prudent, conservative, but not 
excessive, loan loss allowances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But they added, ``We recognize that today instability in certain  
global markets, for example, is likely to increase loss inherent in 
affected institutions' portfolios and consequently require higher 
allowances for credit losses than were appropriate in more stable 
times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agencies said they were establishing a joint working group  
and would, within a year, issue more complete guidance on several 
issues regarding loan loss reserves. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 11:16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Sex Chain To Offer Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- Germany's best-known erotic shop is  
going public -- not with tawdry tales, but with a stock offering. 
</P>
<P>
	The business may be risque, but there was nothing unconventional  
about the announcement Wednesday by Beata Rotermund, owner of the 
Beata Uhse sex shops. 
</P>
<P>
	Rotermund said she plans to sell shares in her enormously  
successful erotic business beginning in May or June to finance 
expansion with the goal of making it the biggest in the world. The 
deal will be handled by Commerzbank, Germany's third-largest. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time is ripe for the Beata Uhse stocks,'' the 79-year-old  
Rotermund told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Beata Uhse's sales rose 34.2 percent last year to $96 million.  
The business includes over 50 erotic shops, a mail-order business 
and a chain of X-rated theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Rotermund plans an initial public offering of 25 percent of the  
company, with about 5 percent reserved for her 750 employees. The 
majority stake in the company will remain in the family. 
</P>
<P>
	A Luftwaffe captain during World War II, Rotermund escaped  
Berlin with her 2-year-old son just before the Russians moved in 
during the closing days of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Settling in a small town near the Danish border, she started her  
own business in 1946 selling information about birth control to the 
wives of returning soldiers. She soon added contraceptives and 
other items to her stock and branched into a mail-order business. 
She opened her first sex shop in 1962. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
