<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns To Review Couch's Arm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Browns might decide to use their  
No. 1 pick in the NFL draft on someone other than Tim Couch. If 
they do, Mike Leach thinks they're making a mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'd be crazy not to take Tim,'' said Leach, Couch's  
offensive coordinator for two years at Kentucky. ``I don't think 
there is a better quarterback out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's what the Browns planned to find out today at Couch's  
private workout in Lexington, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch, Kentucky's All-American quarterback, will get a chance to  
convince the Browns that he should be their choice with the No. 1 
overall pick in the April 17 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Browns coach Chris Palmer, who earlier this week observed  
quarterback Akili Smith's workout in Oregon, visited with Couch on 
Wednesday. Couch's workout session also was to be attended by 
Cleveland director of football operations Dwight Clark; 
quarterbacks coach John Hufnagel; player personnel director Joe 
Collins; and director of college scouting Phil Neri. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching hours of game film, the Browns' braintrust will  
finally see first hand what Couch can do with a football. 
</P>
<P>
	With snow in the forecast, the workout will take place inside  
Nutter Field House adjacent to UK's football stadium. The Browns 
had hoped to see Couch throw outdoors, so they could see if he 
possesses the arm strength to handle the blowing winds off Lake 
Erie that are sure to make passing difficult in Cleveland's new 
lakefront stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	How far and how hard he can throw a football have been the  
biggest questions about Couch, who rarely needed to air it out 
while playing at Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's ridiculous,'' Leach said. ``He can throw it as  
far down field as he needs to. If he was throwing it 60 yards for 
us, we weren't happy. That meant it was a broken play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under head coach Hal Mumme and Leach, who is now at Oklahoma,  
Couch ran a Kentucky offense that stressed throwing the ball 
underneath coverage. Patterns of 5 to 10 yards were the norm, not 
50- and 60-yard bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ran timing patterns with the deepest route about 28  
yards,'' Leach said. ``Tim has all the arm strength the Browns will 
ever need. Hey, if they're looking for a guy who can throw it 60 
yards, there are defensive ends at Kentucky and Oklahoma who can 
throw it farther than that. 
</P>
<P>
	``That doesn't mean they are quarterbacks. They can't play  
quarterback on the same planet as Tim Couch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couch was to be assisted in his workout by four of his top five  
receivers at Kentucky, including All-SEC wideout Craig Yeast. Couch 
has spent the last two months working out a game plan for the 
Browns and the other NFL teams who'll attend. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to run all the different routes from each side  
of the field,'' said Greg Couch, Tim's brother and one of his 
advisors. ``He'll do three-, five- and seven-step drops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leach is confident that once the Browns see Couch in person, all  
this talk about arm strength will fade away for good. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Tim has a stronger arm than Joe Montana, it's stronger  
than Steve Young's and Fran Tarkenton's. The Hall of Fame is full 
of guys who couldn't throw it that far. But when they had a target, 
they usually hit it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
