<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Wins Gold in World Moguls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEIRINGEN, Switzerland (AP) -- World Cup champion Ann Battelle of  
Steamboat Springs, Colo., a three-time Olympic skier who considered 
retirement last summer, took advantage of changing snow conditions 
Wednesday to win the gold medal in moguls in the freestyle World 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's event, Finns swept all three medals in bright  
sunshine, led by Olympic silver medalist Janne Lahtela. He received 
26.59 points from the judges with Lauri Lassila (26.12) taking the 
silver medal and Sami Mustonen in third place with 26.07 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Battelle, 31, who didn't ki moguls until 1989 after graduating  
from Middlebury College, where she played soccer. She received 
24.38 points from the judges. A native of Williston, Vt., she 
clinched the World Cup title last month, winning the last event in 
Madarao, Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Kari Traa of Norway took the silver medal with 24.12 and local  
favorite Corinne Bodmer of Switzerland was third with 23.81. 
</P>
<P>
	The other American skier in finals was Justine Van Houte of  
Telluride, Colo., but one of her skis broke during training and she 
had to compete using a coach's pair, and finished 15th. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty cool, now I can say I was the world champion,''  
Battelle said. ``This is one of the steepest and toughest courses 
on the World Cup. It's the big gnarly one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She had pondered retirement last spring but a summer of working  
as an intern for a brokerage firm instead of spending time on skis 
in training camp left her refreshed. A shortened World Cup season 
after the Olympics also was appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourth in the last two world championships, she came to  
Meiringen with a relaxed attitude after almost a week of easy 
skiing and seeing friends at home. Training, though, was a little 
unnerving. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were frozen ice balls on the course during training and  
I couldn't make it down the course to save myself,'' Battelle said. 
``But it got softer when the sun came out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of those mornings where I figured, `If I live  
through today, it'll be a miracle.' It was definitely not a lot of 
fun ... but I didn't realize everybody else was having trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the snow softening, Battelle, skiing next to last in the  
flip-16 format after qualifying second on Monday, nailed her two 
jumps and skied off with the gold medal. Marja Elfman of Sweden, 
who, coincidentally, lost the World Cup title to Battelle in Japan, 
was the only one who could have caught her, but made several 
mistakes and finished fifth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
