<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 79.08, Hits New High / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks shot to record highs Wednesday as oil  
prices soared, but concerns about technology-company earnings 
crimped gains in the Nadsaq Composite index. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 79.08 to 9,772.84,  
surpassing its previous high of 9,736.08, set last Friday. The Dow 
is now up 6.4 percent for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators, which lagged the Dow for most of the  
day, narrowed the gap late in the session. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500 index set its second record of the week, adding 7.00 to finish 
at 1,286.84, beating the record 1,282.73 set Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite ended in positive territory but was  
hampered by ongoing nervousness about technology company earnings. 
The Nasdaq added 13.06 to finish at 2,406.00, still shy of its 
all-time closing high of 2,510.09, which was reached Feb 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were sharply higher, following reports that leading  
exporting nations are close to agreement on production cuts in a 
bid to shore up prices. Oil prices have been rising steadily for 
over a week, recovering from 12-year lows and pushing oil stocks 
higher. Crude oil for April delivery closed 84 cents higher to 
$14.69 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, its highest 
level since last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	That helped the Dow, which includes Chevron, which was up 3 5/16  
at 83 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont was another big winner among Dow shares, up 3 13/16 to  
57 3/8, after the company said it would issue a separate stock to 
track the performance of its life-sciences business and was seeking 
alliances with drug companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer-related stocks sank after retailer Computer Associates  
was downgraded by Morgan Stanley, which cited concerns about softer 
demand for computers, increasing competition, and potentially lower 
profit margins. Computer Associates' shares dropped 5 1/16 to 34 
15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq Computer, whose warning of possible lower earnings sent  
the market lower last week, declined 1 3/16 to 31 9/16 in leading 
New York Stock Exchange volume. Its competitor, Dell Computer, fell 
in leading Nasdaq volume. Dell dropped 3/4 to 43 5/16, even after the 
computer maker announced that it had agreed with Amazon.com to 
offer linked Web sites. Amazon's shares climbed 7 3/16 to 137 1/8, 
along with other Internet-related shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks got a turbo charge Wednesday afternoon as Ralph Acampora,  
director of technical research at Prudential Securities and a 
well-known market bull, told a group of Belgian traders that U.S. 
equities, especially blue-chip Dow components, are in the ``early 
stages of another bull market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acampora said low inflation, low interest rates, the technology  
revolution and a peacetime economy are all supporting stocks. The 
fact that blue-chip companies are leading the market means ``the 
market's telling me that it wants to go up, because it's led by 
quality,'' Acampora said, predicting that the Dow will climb as 
high as 11,500 sometime in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Pradilla, chief investment strategist at SG Cowen  
Securities, said he agreed that the market is in good shape, for 
now. But he repeated warnings that stocks are already pricey and 
analysts don't expect earnings this year to be knocked out of the 
park. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody can say stocks are undervalued, and earnings are going  
to be OK,'' Pradilla said. ``But you're going to get some 
unpleasant exposure (to earnings declines) as the year goes on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds fell, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury up to 5.55  
percent from 5.53 percent late Tuesday. The higher rates didn't 
disturb bank stocks, however. Citigroup shares advanced 1 1/2 to 64. 
</P>
<P>
	On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues outnumbered  
decliners by a 5-to-4 margin. Consolidated volume came to 1.02 
billion shares, up from Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 3.55 to 606.48 , and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.69 to 715.14. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies added 1.92 to 401.12. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei index in Tokyo surged 2.54 percent as Japanese  
investors repatriated funds to their own markets. In Europe, 
Frankfurt's DAX index eased 0.78 percent, but the FT-SE 100 index 
in London and CAC in Paris each added 0.06 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
