<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MacLeod Says Resignation His Idea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- John MacLeod denied Wednesday that he  
was pressured into resigning as basketball coach at Notre Dame, 
saying it was the right time to step down. 
</P>
<P>
	He now hopes to return to the NBA, where he spent 18 seasons.  
</P>
<P>
	MacLeod, who didn't attend the Tuesday night news conference  
during which his resignation was announced, indicated as late as 
Tuesday morning he intended to coach another year at Notre Dame, 
where he has had just three winning seasons in eight years as 
coach. He wouldn't say what changed his mind but said he did not 
leave for personal reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the thing to do, just a situation where it was the best  
move for me to make at the time,'' MacLeod said in a phone 
interview. ``I leave knowing full well that the program is a great 
deal better, vastly improved from when I started. I know that I 
made major contributions to the university as a man and as 
basketball coach. I'm leaving the program in, I think, superb 
condition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came as a shock to many of his players, who are  
on spring break this week, despite the team's 14-16 record this 
season and 8-10 mark in the Big East. MacLeod called each one 
Tuesday to tell them the news, and point guard Martin Ingelsby said 
he first thought MacLeod was just calling to check up on him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what the situation is or if Notre Dame asked him  
to leave or what,'' Ingelsby said. ``But I really thought coach 
wanted to come back, and I was really looking forward to next year 
and I think he was, too. I don't think it was him that wanted to 
leave. I think Notre Dame wanted a change and it was just time to 
do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although sticking to his assertion that it was his choice to  
leave, MacLeod expressed frustration that Lon Kruger was praised 
for winning 14 games at Illinois with mostly underclassmen, which 
is exactly what Notre Dame did this season with two freshmen and a 
sophomore in the starting lineup. He also said the Irish exceeded 
expectations this season and had a strong nucleus for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were picked to finish 12th'' in the Big East, MacLeod said.  
``We finished eighth, one win from sixth and two wins from fourth, 
so how were we doing? We were doing pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MacLeod's Notre Dame teams have a 106-124 mark, and his only  
winning years were 1991-92, his first at the school, 1994-95 and 
1996-97. He is the only coach in school history to lead the team at 
least five seasons and still register an overall losing record. 
</P>
<P>
	But players said they thought MacLeod would get at least one  
more year, especially with freshmen Harold Swanagan, Dave Graves 
and Troy Murphy, the Big East rookie of the year, providing a solid 
foundation for next season. Plus, MacLeod had secured commitments 
from 6-foot-5 guard Mike Monserez of Cincinnati and Matt Carroll, a 
6-5 guard from suburban Philadelphia considered one of the top 30 
recruits in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the class he brought in and the way he had the freshman  
class perform this year and the recruits coming in next year, he's 
got all the pieces of the puzzle right there,'' senior Antoni Wyche 
said. ``It's hard to explain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It surprised me, really,'' Swanagan said. ``I figured that he  
would stay. I knew we had a bad season, but not anything like that 
severe where he would get fired. I don't know. I really don't know. 
I thought he was going to stay for at least another year if he was 
going to get replaced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MacLeod, 61, said he'll now turn his attention to landing a job  
in the NBA, either as a coach or a general manager. He said he 
won't coach in the college ranks again and would consider a spot in 
the broadcast booth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no harsh feelings (toward Notre Dame). I know what I've  
been able to do; I know how the program has turned around,'' 
MacLeod said. ``Did anybody think we were going to come out of 
independent status and be a dominant player in the Big East? It 
took Miami six years to win a Big East Tournament game. We 
accomplished a great deal in four years.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
