<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Education Savings Accounts Pushed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers from both parties renewed a push  
Wednesday for education tax legislation that President Clinton 
vetoed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure offers tax breaks for parents who send their  
children to private schools and allows tax-free withdrawals from 
education savings accounts for pre-college expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton vetoed the legislation last summer, saying it would have  
provided $3 billion to fund tax benefits for richer families while 
doing ``virtually nothing for average families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional backers believe they have a ``strong, bipartisan  
coalition building here,'' said one sponsor, Rep. Kenny Hulshof, 
R-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters are ``struggling against a very large component,  
particularly in this city, who are committed to the status quo; 
they don't want to change,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic co-sponsors are Sen. Robert Torricelli of New  
Jersey and Rep. William Lipinski of Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would expand the tax-free savings accounts that  
Congress created in 1997, with Clinton's blessing, to provide for 
college expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot easier for parents to sock money away each month  
during a child's early years,'' Hulshof said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the legislation lawmakers are introducing this year,  
covered expenses would include private tutors, home computers, 
supplies and transportation. It also contains other tax breaks for 
prepaid tuition plans and employer-paid tuition, along with breaks 
to make it easier for communities to build new public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Families, employers, friends, relatives and other sponsors could  
contribute up to $2,000 a year to the accounts on a child's behalf. 
Accrued interest and withdrawals would be tax-free; the money could 
pay for expenses beginning with kindergarten. 
</P>
<P>
	While the average family's tax break would be small, Coverdell  
said, the savings accounts would leverage up to $6 billion over 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The accounts would cost the Treasury an estimated $1.5 billion  
over 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
