<DOCNO> APW19990310.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 23:12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stephen F. Austin Haunted by Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stephen F. Austin's basketball season was turning into an  
embarrassment for Anitra Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Here she was a senior, the leader of a team from a school with a  
rich tradition in women's hoops, a perennial NCAA tournament 
qualifier, and the Ladyjacks were losing. It wasn't fun. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're not expected to lose here,'' Davis said. ``We probably  
lost more games this year than any other team. That's very 
disappointing, almost embarrassing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Halfway though the season, Stephen F. Austin stood 7-7. Then,  
just when it looked as if it couldn't get any worse, it did. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 18, two days after a second straight narrow loss, Davis  
and her teammates learned the horrifying news that Katrina Price, 
the star of last year's team and a revered figure in the SFA 
community, had died, apparently from a self-inflicted shotgun 
blast. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone was stunned -- players, coaches, family and friends.  
Many wondered if the Ladyjacks would get over it. 
</P>
<P>
	But they did, and Saturday night, Stephen F. Austin will play  
Texas Tech in the first round of the NCAA Midwest Regional. The 
Ladyjacks finished with 10 victories in their last 12 games and won 
the Southland Conference tournament to earn their NCAA berth. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were questioning do they have the character and the  
heart to come back and get it done,'' SFA coach Royce Chadwick 
said. ``Well, they played great. For them to turn it around the way 
they have, I've never coached a team I'm more proud of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chadwick said Price's death was such a burden on his players  
because they had no one to turn to for solace. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have a player that loses a family member, usually  
they're gone for a while and when they come back, the others pull 
together and help them get through the tough times,'' he said. ``In 
our case, we all lost a family member and there was nobody on the 
team to help pull everybody through. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like forever,'' Chadwick said. ``We had counselors, we  
rescheduled a couple of games, we reorganized the majority of our 
schedule for two weeks to give ourselves an opportunity to recover. 
It was the toughest thing I've ever been through as a coach of a 
basketball team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chadwick wonders if those who knew Price will ever recover  
completely. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if we'll ever be 100 percent over it,'' he said.  
``But it doesn't possess us like it did at one time. You lay down 
at night and you can't sleep and when you finally do get over it, 
you wake up and before you get out from the covers, you're thinking 
about it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis said the players still feel the pain of their teammate's  
loss. But now when she thinks about Price, Davis tries to picture 
how she played and how she used to respond when things got tough. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was a fierce competitor in everything and didn't accept  
losing when we played here together,'' said Davis, the team's 
leading scorer (19.8) and rebounder (9.1). ``It inspired me to go 
out and make it important. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the game and I wanted to go out and play like I love  
the game,'' she said. ``I think it helped. It turned the season 
around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The turnaround enabled Stephen F. Austin to extend its run of  
consecutive NCAA tournament appearances to 12. It's the 14th time 
overall the Ladyjacks have made the field and maybe, Davis muses, 
all is becoming right again in the program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think now,'' she said, ``we're a little more deserving to  
wear the Ladyjack uniform.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
