<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 09:26:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quiet Irish Play Is Making Noise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Four men and a woman gather to swap stories, some  
of them ghostly, in a remote Irish pub, and from their yarns is 
woven a tapestry of love, loss and perhaps even healing. 
</P>
<P>
	That is the essence of ``The Weir,'' a play slight in plot but  
rich in character and feeling that, for all its quiet intimacies, 
has been making quite a noise. 
</P>
<P>
	Conor McPherson's drama initially opened for a mere monthlong  
run two summers ago in a 60-seat London theater. Since then, it has 
generated three companies of actors, the first of which will lead 
the play to Broadway this month. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 12, the Royal Court production of ``The Weir'' produced  
further clamor, winning the Olivier Award for the best play of 1998 
in a hotly contested race with Michael Frayn's ``Copenhagen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It all seems very weird,'' says McPherson, a shy, stocky  
Dubliner with carrot-colored hair. ``I just stay home and wait for 
the checks,'' the 27-year-old playwright deadpans. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadway previews begin March 23, before an April 1 opening. The  
replacement London cast opened March 8, while yet a third cast has 
embarked on an 11-week British tour. 
</P>
<P>
	McPherson could scarcely have imagined this when he wrote ``The  
Weir,'' set in a country pub in County Leitrim, northwest Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of plays are earmarked all along for the West End and  
Broadway. That is their reason to exist,'' he says. ``But this has 
been so organic -- if the play had just been around for those first 
three weeks, I would have been happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the universal is grounded in the particular, ``The Weir''  
proves it, as did another award-winning 1990s play set in an Irish 
backwater, Brian Friel's ``Dancing at Lughnasa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Weir,'' says director Ian Rickson, ``draws upon all sorts  
of needs we have at this moment to do with community and contact 
and intimacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``You spend an evening in real time and in a real place with  
real characters on a human journey that is so necessary, needed, 
desired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the start, the play seems to be little more than an exercise  
in banter, as bartender Brendan greets some pub regulars on a windy 
day during which his all-important Guinness tap is broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the booze must be poured out of a bottle, and with it  
come various eerie stories of increasing intensity designed to 
impress Valerie, the new girl in a very male town. 
</P>
<P>
	What the men competing for her attention can't predict is that  
Valerie has on reserve her own story, which is that much more 
genuinely disturbing and heart-stirring for being true. 
</P>
<P>
	No sooner has she spoken her narrative than Jack, the pub's  
senior denizen, offers up his second tale of the play, this time 
drawing from a well of emotion that Valerie's presence has gently 
yet piercingly evoked. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jack is sort of feminized by Valerie,'' Rickson says. ``He's  
able to tell a story about himself that he would never have been 
able to tell at the beginning of the play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And although the town itself possesses its own weir, or dam, the  
play suggests that unlike the flow of water, feelings cannot be 
easily controlled. 
</P>
<P>
	``I read it, and I cried for about an hour,'' Jim Norton, the  
play's very first Jack, says of the play. ``I just thought, `This 
is a major new voice' -- the ability and maturity and ease with 
which Conor writes about very complex subjects. `If I don't play 
this part, I'll die.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Norton, Kieran Ahern as the sweet-natured mama's boy Jim, and  
Brendan Coyle as the ever-watchful bartender together make up the 
play's so-called ``home team.'' All three have been with ``The 
Weir'' since its July 4, 1997, debut at the Royal Court's tiny 
Theater Upstairs. 
</P>
<P>
	That means Coyle has spent more than 300 performances listening  
attentively to the others, since Brendan is the only character who 
doesn't get to tell his own story. 
</P>
<P>
	Does his mind ever wander?	   ``It's very, very difficult, and that's the key. If I don't  
listen, I have a bad night,'' says Coyle, who won his own Olivier 
for best supporting performer in a play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure, you find yourself thinking, `Oh, I forgot to set the  
video,' but you have to fight that. It's like meditation: You have 
to get rid of any outside rubbish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's talk of a Tony Award in June. But as the members of the  
original company get ready for New York, they just hope such an 
unshowy and deeply felt play can hold its own on Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just want it to work,'' says Michelle Fairley, the  
northern Irish actress who plays Valerie. ``Through working on it, 
you love it so much that it becomes like your baby, so you just 
want everybody to like your baby.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
