<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate To Vote on Education Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill that would grant the states greater  
freedom in spending federal education money gained momentum in 
Congress Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate broke through six days of procedural jousting and  
agreed to vote Thursday on both the bill and amendments demanded by 
Democrats to implement President Clinton's education proposals, 
including federal subsidies for hiring thousands of new teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the House, however, Republicans continued to block Democrats'  
efforts to attach Clinton's proposals to their so-called ed-flex 
bill reducing number of strings the federal government puts on 
education aid to states and local school districts. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans promised a final vote on their bill Thursday,  
telling Democrats they could bring up Clinton's new-teacher plan 
later as part of a larger education bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, visiting Guatemala and El Salvador, issued a statement  
saying he was pleased the Senate agreed to an up-or-down vote on 
hiring 100,000 new teachers ``to reduce class size in early 
grades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president said he would ``vigorously oppose'' amendments by  
Senate Republicans to instead devote to special education the money 
he wants for reducing class sizes. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Jake Siewert said Clinton isn't thinking  
veto -- at least not yet. ``We'll wait and see how it comes out in 
the Senate,'' Siewert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota predicted  
that the final package will pass overwhelmingly. ``We've reached a 
point where we are going to be able to finish this bill,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans didn't seem eager to make accommodations as  
they rejected a Democratic proposal to add more state requirements 
to the ed-flex bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't improve education unless you admit you have a  
problem,'' said Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., who called the 
``ed-flex'' bill a first step in addressing what he called 
education's core problem: too many rules and not enough local 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic proposal for new money for teachers to reduce  
class sizes would only add money without fixing those problems, 
said Goodling, chairman of the House Education Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the ed-flex measure, states and school districts could  
apply federal money to programs that serve them best, Republicans 
say. For example, states could allow schools to use money targeted 
for low-income students or for training math and science teachers 
on other programs that benefit the entire school. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Democrats also support that idea, but insist that schools  
need more federal money to hire more teachers to reduce class 
sizes. Rep. Bill Clay, D-Mo., was offering one such amendment in 
the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, in a spending bill compromise, Congress approved $1  
billion for the states to use to hire new teachers. Clinton has 
said his plan to hire a total of 100,000 new teachers for the 
nation's schools would require $11 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a vital first step,'' said Rep. David Wu, D-Ore.  
``Unfortunately, some in Congress don't want to continue past the 
first year, leaving school districts in budgetary limbo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since education's emergence as a popular issue of concern to  
voters, both parties have rushed to be the first to pass an 
education bill this session, leading to frustration on both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	The scramble is particularly keen in the Senate, where  
retirement announcements leave some big seats up for grabs in the 
2000 elections in New York, New Jersey, Florida and Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are trying to raise all of these presidential programs  
often, to get the GOP voting against popular programs,'' said Sen. 
Bill Frist, R-Tenn., who brought ed-flex to the Senate with 
Democratic Sen. Ron Wyden of Oregon. ``We've started off with a 
program aimed at the 2000 elections and I find that extremely 
distasteful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the ed-flex bill passes, it would not affect many of the  
rules governing the $15 billion in education spending for 
kindergarten through high school. By law, states cannot waive rules 
regarding a school's safety, maintenance or assurance of student 
civil rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The states also could not waive regulations under the federal  
special education law, which many states view as the most expensive 
and time-consuming to follow. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill is HR 800; the Senate bill is S 280.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
