<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Chides Reno Over Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of a Senate spending panel  
accused the Justice Department on Tuesday of playing politics with 
proposals to cut more than $1.4 billion from community law 
enforcement programs in the next fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., told Attorney General Janet Reno the  
cuts were sought to put his subcommittee in the ``untenable 
position'' of having to find money elsewhere to pay for the 
programs, while another lawmaker asked why the $21 billion budget 
request included no money for new Border Patrol agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno was also questioned about the independent counsel law,  
which is under fire from both political parties and scheduled to 
expire in June unless Congress renews it. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregg, who runs the Appropriations panel that funds the  
department, noted the administration had changed its position 
``basically 180 degrees'' to oppose renewal of the act, which 
provides for independent investigation of allegations concerning 
certain senior administration officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno, who has sought seven independent counsels over the past  
six years but has opposed an outside investigation of alleged 
fund-raising abuses during President's Clinton 1996 re-election 
campaign, said there were problems with the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as the attorney general has that authority and  
responsibility under the act, you're not going to get away from the 
issue of is the independent counsel independent,'' she said. 
``There are going to be questions raised, as there are constantly 
over the decisions that I make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding Justice's budget plan, Gregg criticized proposals to  
eliminate a $250 million juvenile accountability block grant and a 
$523 million local law enforcement block grant, and to reduce 
grants for state prisons by nearly $650 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The department, meanwhile, wants $600 million to expand an  
existing community policing program to help states hire between 
30,000 and 50,000 police officers over five years. The program 
known as COPS, enacted in 1994, is nearing its original goal of 
putting 100,000 police officers on the nation's streets. The new 
money would be for even more officers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've made politically attractive choices at the expense of  
this committee,'' said Gregg, noting that the programs Justice 
wants to cut have ``been strongly supported, up until now, jointly 
by this committee and the administration.'' Justice's proposal 
``was done in order to put us ... in the untenable position of 
having to go out and find the money to put back in those 
programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said crime is down significantly nationwide, and state and  
local law officers shouldn't become too dependent on the federal 
government. She also said the proposed budget still contains 
funding for juvenile justice and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregg said the subcommittee may accede to the administration's  
plan to cut the three programs, but would not back expanding COPS, 
saying the money would be spent elsewhere, such as on beefing up 
border patrols. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, criticized Justice's  
decision not to hire 1,000 Border Patrol agents authorized by a 
1996 immigration law. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno called it an ``extraordinarily high priority,'' but said  
recruiting difficulties forced cancellation of some classes for new 
agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
