<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Bank Takeover Faces Hurdles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Banque Nationale de Paris' surprise $37.2 billion  
bid for two rival French banks faces serious hurdles including the 
politically sensitive issue of layoffs in a country with high 
unemployment and possible clashes in management styles. 
</P>
<P>
	The move by BNP to create a $1 trillion world-leading banking  
group in an unprecedented three-way merger with Paribas and Societe 
Generale comes as European banks are joining forces to better 
compete in a market transformed by a new common currency, the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	The unsolicited offer is evidence that French banks, often  
criticized for their slowness to consolidate, are moving 
frantically to catch up with their neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The euro has the effect of increasing competitive pressures in  
Europe,'' BNP Chairman Michel Pebereau said at a news conference 
Wednesday. ``France needed to create a banking champion. Our offer 
sets this up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If successful, the combined bank would be a formidable  
competitor, setting the stage for international acquisitions and 
possible inroads in the U.S. market, experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once they are more profitable in France, they will be better  
equipped to attack the U.S. and other world markets,'' said Yves 
Burger, a banking analyst at Standard and Poor's in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	But another cautioned that initially, ``top management will be  
too busy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They won't have the time or the resources to look to the U.S.  
market for the next few years,'' said Evagelos Kavouriadis, 
European banking analyst at Bernstein Research in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	While French banks have been slow to expand into the United  
States, several European banks are making moves, including Deutsche 
Bank, HSBC, Dresdner and ABN Amro. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1 trillion in combined assets under the merger proposal  
would easily exceed the size of what was going to be the world's 
biggest bank -- the $800 billion institution that would be created 
by the pending acquisition of Bankers Trust Corp. by Deutsche Bank 
AG. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP's takeover bid, announced late Tuesday by regulators from  
the Paris stock exchange, comes just weeks after Societe Generale 
moved to buy Paribas for $17.07 billion to create Europe's 
second-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	While regulators suspended trading Wednesday on shares of all  
three banks on the Paris stock exchange, other European banks 
rallied on merger expectations. Dresdner Bank, seen as a merger 
candidate, rose 5.5 percent in trading in Frankfurt, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Some observers saw BNP's move as defensive, especially after the  
bank was rejected as a partner in the privatization of the 
state-owned bank Credit Lyonnais. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said BNP's bid, though feasible, faces difficulties  
because its hostile nature means management will have a hard time 
working out the complicated structure of a new entity. 
</P>
<P>
	Paribas and Societe Generale on Wednesday described BNP's offer  
as ``risky,'' adding that they didn't see it as ``friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both banks said they would study the proposal. BNP's takeover  
offer would scuttle Societe Generale's plans to buy Paribas, an 
investment bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, possible staff reductions would be extremely  
politically sensitive in this strike-prone country. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP has said there will be no massive layoffs in France and that  
they will maintain the group's two major retail banking networks. 
Staff reductions will come largely from an expected wave of 
retirements, BNP said. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts said the deal's success depends on whether a joint  
management team can wring out major cost savings from BNP and 
Societe Generale's overlapping domestic networks. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't lay off workers, the deal doesn't make sense,''  
Kavouriadis said. 
</P>
<P>
	The French Finance Ministry and the Bank of France, in a joint  
statement Wednesday, said BNP's takeover offer will have to respect 
the need to preserve jobs -- an expression of government anxiety 
over France's 11.4 percent jobless rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
