<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 06:01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chechnya Hunts Kidnap Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Chechnya's president called top police and  
security officials together today to plan action against foes whom 
he accused of abducting a top Russian general in order to draw 
Russia into war. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to throw the Chechen people into the abyss of war,''  
President Aslan Maskhadov said on Chechen television late Tuesday, 
referring to a number of warlords whose armed gangs roam Chechnya 
with virtual impunity. 
</P>
<P>
	He specifically accused two key opponents, Shamil Basayev and  
Salman Raduyev, of masterminding the abduction. The pair has 
intensified efforts to oust him from power in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you must, even put Basayev in jail,'' Maskhadov said.  
``Those people don't care for the people's needs. We had war for 
two years, and we don't want to have it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia and Chechnya fought a 1994-1996 war in which the Chechens  
won de-facto independence. Moscow still claims the republic as part 
of Russia, but leaves it to manage own affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions were ratcheted up a notch by the latest confrontation,  
in which kidnappers dragged police Maj. Gen. Gennady Shpigun off an 
airplane just before it was to take off Friday from the Chechen 
capital Grozny. So far, no one has claimed responsibility or named 
any conditions for his release. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in Moscow threatened military attacks on the republic  
if Shpigun is not found. Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin also 
ordered more troops to the border areas around Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	Shpigun's disappearance was a blow to Maskhadov, who has  
Moscow's backing but has seen his authority undermined by violence 
and a wave of kidnappings of Russians and foreigners alike. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is still smarting from the high-profile abduction of  
Valentin Vlasov, Russia's envoy to Chechnya, who was held for six 
months and released late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Maskhadov, however, warned the Russian government against using  
force if Shpigun isn't found soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Threats and blackmail are unacceptable,'' Maskhadov said  
through his spokesman, Mairbek Vachagayev. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin discussed the situation late Tuesday with President  
Boris Yeltsin, who is hospitalized with an ulcer, but no decisions 
were announced. The Russian government scheduled a meeting today to 
discuss a response. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking on Russian television late Tuesday, Yeltsin's deputy  
chief of staff, Oleg Sysuyev, said the government would try to 
prevent hostilities, but may launch strikes against ``bandits'' in 
Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bandits will be punished. There will be a full-scale war  
against them,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Professor Wins $1.2M Religion Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ian Barbour, a nuclear physicist and theologian  
who has devoted his career to reconciling science and faith, won 
the $1.24 million Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Templeton is the world's richest annual prize for  
achievement in any field. 
</P>
<P>
	The 75-year-old Barbour, who holds both a theology degree and a  
Ph.D. in nuclear physics, teaches at Carleton College in 
Northfield, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	He has spent the past 15 years examining moral issues raised by  
technological advances such as cloning and nuclear power. He did 
doctoral work with Enrico Fermi, one of the fathers of the atomic 
bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's easy to think science has all the answers, because it's a  
very powerful tool,'' Barbour said Wednesday. But he insisted that 
science cannot answer humanity's spiritual and ethical questions. 
</P>
<P>
	The prize was established in 1972 by mutual fund entrepreneur  
John M. Templeton to spotlight advances in a field omitted by the 
Nobel prizes. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbour will accept the award at a May 17 ceremony at the  
Kremlin. The site symbolizes Russia's move from enforced scientific 
atheism toward toleration of faith. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbour is the ninth winner engaged in science and religion.  
Other recipients have included Mother Teresa, the Rev. Billy 
Graham, Alexander Solzhenitsyn and prison evangelist and Watergate 
figure Charles Colson. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbour plans to give some of the prize money to Carleton  
College and his local United Church of Christ congregation. But $1 
million will go to the Center for Theology and the Natural 
Sciences, affiliated with the Graduate Theological Union in 
Berkeley, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Beijing, Barbour was chairman of the physics department  
at Kalamazoo College in Michigan before he moved to Carleton in 
1955 to teach both physics and religion. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965, he published ``Issues in Science and Religion,''  
considered a pioneering work in relating the two fields. His recent 
works include ``Ethics in an Age of Technology'' (1993) and 
``Religion and Science: Historical and Contemporary Issues'' 
(1997). 
</P>
<P>
	Barbour said that when he started in the field, there were two  
main ways of looking at science and religion: They were either in 
conflict or two strictly separate domains. At the time he favored 
the latter. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very attractive solution, in a way,'' he said. ``But  
ultimately we're whole people. We can't live in two worlds.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 03:59:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Money for Clinton Museum Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Just days before President Clinton is  
due in his native Hope, Arkansas lawmakers rejected a $500,000 plan 
to make improvements at his boyhood-home-turned-museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Sandra Rodgers, D-Hope, rushed from the House chamber after  
the House defeated her bill Tuesday and cried in the Capitol hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want President Clinton to know that they don't support  
him, that's fine with me, I'll try to convey that message for 
him,'' said Ms. Rodgers, her voice breaking. ``I'm just really 
mad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many representatives who opposed the bill said it had nothing to  
do with Clinton, but with the source of the money. The project 
would have been funded immediately, instead of having to compete 
later with other projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which needed 75 votes in the 99-member House, was  
defeated 41-8. Most members, not wanting to appear opposed to 
Clinton, either didn't vote or cast a ``present'' vote. 
</P>
<P>
	One representative said he opposed the funding because he  
opposes Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have voted for impeachment, and I think he has  
disgraced our state in a lot of ways,'' said Rep. Jim Bob Duggar, 
R-Springdale. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rodgers had hoped to have the funding approved before  
Friday, so she could present Clinton with a copy of the legislation 
when he makes his first visit to his birthplace home. Clinton is 
attending the dedication of the Virginia Clinton Kelly Memorial 
Garden in memory of his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum, which opened in June 1997, has received about $1  
million in donations from individuals and corporations. Executive 
Director Becky Moore said the state money would have sped up work 
so that the museum could be part of the national park system. 
</P>
<P>
	The $500,000 would have funded a 40-seat theater, computer room,  
board room, gift shop expansion and relocation of the director's 
office at the tourist center next to Clinton's home. Some of the 
money also could be used to spruce up the grounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
