<DOCNO> APW19990310.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 07:17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How Much Did Citigroup Pay Execs? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Citigroup Inc., the nation's largest financial  
company, paid their top two executives handsomely last year. How 
handsomely? 
</P>
<P>
	Six major newspapers reported different totals for the salary,  
bonus and stock options paid to John S. Reed and Sanford I. Weill, 
co-chairmen and co-chief executive of the New York financial giant. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest discrepancies were over the Weill's compensation,  
which ranged from $166.9 million, according to The Wall Street 
Journal and $27.2 million according to The New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Schlein, a spokesman for Citigroup, ``I wouldn't say any  
of them were wrong. They just added up the numbers differently.'' 
(Eventhough the company went so far as to give the media a 
four-page crib sheet along with its proxy statement to help 
reporters decipher the accounting.) 
</P>
<P>
	So, just what did Weill earn?  
</P>
<P>
	The board of directors of Citigroup, which was formed last  
October through the merger of Citibank and Travelers Group, agreed 
both Weill and Reed would be paid the same base compensation: $9.5 
million, plus 1.75 million stock options with a market value of 
about $16.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not that simple.  
</P>
<P>
	Weill was paid a salary of $1.03 million and a bonus of $6.17  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the easy part. But there's more. His restricted stock  
awards of $3.1 million, and other compensation, such as a personal 
trip taken on a corporate jet, of $237,253. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the stock options. In addition to the 1.75 million options  
awarded by the board, Weill actually cashed out some 7.1 million 
previously awarded stock options, and realized a $156.6 million 
gain. Some people didn't include this money because it wasn't 
technically part of his 1998 compensation package. 
</P>
<P>
	For Reed, it was easy: $1.67 million salary, $7.86 million  
bonus, and the 1.75 million options (which can't be exercised until 
2004, but have a market value of $16.9 million.) 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 07:17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Asian Markets Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asia's top three stock markets -- Tokyo, Hong  
Kong and Singapore -- all posted strong gains Wednesday, though 
smaller exchanges were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average jumped  
383.30 points, or 2.54 percent, to 15,480.00, its highest close 
since Aug. 10. On Tuesday, the Nikkei had climbed 317.65 points, or 
2.15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices have been rising ever since electronics giant Sony  
announced Tuesday that it would undertake aggressive restructuring, 
including cutting 17,000 jobs over four years. Sony's stock 
skyrocketed 8.3 percent, after a 8.9 percent rally Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony is seen as a leader among Japanese firms and its move  
fueled optimism that other Japanese companies would also become 
more aggressive about restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overall market's sentiment has improved substantially,''  
said Masaru Arai, general manager at Ryoko Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market rally helped boosted demand for the Japanese  
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In late trading, the dollar fell to 120.54 yen, down 1.22 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo, and less than its late New York level 
of 121.00 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares also surged for a second consecutive day,  
as sharp gains in banking giant HSBC Holdings PLC and buying in the 
futures market pushed the key stock index to close at a 15-week 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index jumped 216.07 points, or 2.1 percent, to  
10,749.72. The Hang Seng had gained 2.6 percent on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	HSBC's shares gained 2.6 percent to their highest close in  
nearly a year. Analysts said international investors have been 
bullish on HSBC's prospects ever since the banking group unveiled 
two weeks ago its plan to launch a secondary listing on the New 
York Stock Exchange later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, positive sentiment on the property sector pushed  
the key stock index sharply higher. The Straits Times Index rallied 
2 percent, or 29.01 points, to 1,469.53. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stocks rose on the renewed belief the government  
will be able to pass key economic legislation through parliament 
soon. The SET index gained 3.69 points, or 1.1 percent, to 333.28. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares tumbled on a weakening local currency, the  
rupiah, and uncertainty over an expected government announcement of 
more bank closures. The JSX Composite Index fell 5.619 points, or 
1.5 percent, to 373.802. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares fell on speculation that banks  
might gain the right to assume some of the function of stock 
brokers. The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange Composite Index fell 2.41 
points, or 0.45 percent, at 528.12. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Negative corporate news weakened Philippine shares. The  
PSE index dropped 16.93 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,981.48. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean stocks fell on futures market concerns. The  
Kospi index fell 3.58 points, or 0.62 percent, to 567.27. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares closed higher, driven by a resurgence  
in the banking sector and selected corporate announcements. The All 
Ordinaries index rose 10.6 points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,931.4 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI : Taiwanese stocks fell as investors sold financial  
shares after recent gains and on concern over growing bad debts in 
the banking sector. The Weighted Price Index fell 6.82 points, or 
0.1 percent, to 6,486.61. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares slumped, dragged down by  
bellwether Telecom Corp. of New Zealand. The NZSE-40 Capital Index 
fell 11.72 points, or 0.54 percent, to 2,144.08. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
