<DOCNO> APW19990310.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 05:44:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NIT Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) -- Being left out of the NCAA tournament  
was tough to swallow for Mississippi State. Being forced to play 
its first game of the National Invitation Tournament on the road 
felt like an added insult. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs (20-12) travel to Colorado State (17-10) for an NIT  
game tonight, when all 16 first-round games will be played. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team earned the right to be in the NCAA,'' Bulldogs coach  
Rick Stansbury insisted. ``It won 20 games. It won seven of its 
last 11. Of the 12 losses we had, seven were against Top 25 teams. 
But we can't control any of that. We feel fortunate to have another 
opportunity to play basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the road assignment, Stansbury said, ``Why? I don't  
know. But again, I'm not in control of that. All we're going to be 
concerned with are the things we are in control of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs launched a surprising run in the SEC tournament  
that ended with a semifinal loss Saturday to Arkansas, then were 
one of the teams snubbed by the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played hard and won 20 games,'' guard Detrick White said.  
``We were looking forward to getting into the NCAA tournament. We 
were disappointed when we watched the selection show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi State, which has enjoyed increased success since  
going to a smaller lineup in January, faces a Colorado State team 
that was surprised to get an NIT nod. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams, making their third appearance in the NIT in four  
years, made an early exit from the Western Athletic Conference 
tournament last week. The home game was equally unexpected. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a huge advantage for us,'' coach Ritchie McKay said.  
``We're 12-2 at home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But McKay is concerned primarily about MSU's athleticism.  
</P>
<P>
	``Mississippi State is more athletic than any team we have  
played,'' he said, ``and we have played some pretty good teams in 
Tulsa and Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to play strong on defense and limit Tyrone  
Washington's catches. Washington is an NBA prospect, a big 6-10 
kid. We have to make him work for everything he gets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other NIT games tonight have Xavier (21-10) at Toledo (19-7),  
Hofstra (22-9) at Rutgers (18-12), Georgia (15-14) at Clemson 
(16-14), Seton Hall (15-14) at Old Dominion (24-8), Butler (20-9) 
at Bradley (17-11), Alabama (17-14) at Wake Forest (16-13) and 
Providence (16-13) at North Carolina State (18-13). 
</P>
<P>
	Also, it's Nevada-Las Vegas (16-12) at Nebraska (19-12),  
Pepperdine (19-12) at Colorado (17-14), Georgetown (15-15) at 
Princeton (20-7), Texas Christian (19-10) at Kansas State (20-12), 
Southern California (15-12) at Wyoming (17-9), Northwestern (15-13) 
at DePaul (17-12), Fresno State (21-11) at California (17-11) and 
Georgia Tech (15-15) at Oregon (16-11). 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years ago, 16th-seeded Princeton nearly pulled off the  
biggest upset in NCAA tournament history against No. 1 seed 
Georgetown. The Tigers get another crack at Georgetown, only this 
time in the NIT. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers in 1989 NCAA gave the Hoyas a memorable first-round  
scare in which Georgetown held on to win 50-49. A No. 16 seed has 
never defeated a No. 1 in the history of the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a different story now,'' Tigers senior guard Brian Earl  
said. ``It's not on the same stage, it's the NIT as opposed to the 
NCAA's. And they're not so much the powerhouse, we're not so much 
the underdog. I'm sure it sparks memories, but not many.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Tigers win this time around, it wouldn't be much of a  
surprise. Princeton's chance to make the NCAA tournament slipped 
away in a loss to Pennsylvania in its final regular season game, 
while the Hoyas barely made the NIT, extending their streak of 
postseason appearances to 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the near upset, Princeton has become a national fixture,  
going to six more NCAA tournaments and winning two first-round 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hoyas have gone in the opposite direction, compiling a 31-30  
record the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown finished 0-9 against NCAA teams this year as opposed  
to Princeton's 4-3 mark. But Georgetown's young starting lineup, 
which includes two freshmen and two sophomores, has recently come 
together, and the Hoyas won six of their last 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only is Hofstra making its first postseason appearance in 22  
years, the Flying Dutchmen only have to travel about 60 miles for 
the game, so their fans are going to be able to make the trip 
rather easily. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our players are familiar with Rutgers and because we watch  
them all the time,'' Hofstra coach Jay Wright said. ``Eleven of our 
13 guys are from the metropolitan area and Rutgers has a lot, and 
our guys love that challenge, they really do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright's biggest concern is the health of junior point guard  
Craig ``Speedy'' Claxton. He missed the final regular-season game 
and was not at hardly played in the conference tournament with a 
strained left thigh. His status probably won't be determined until 
just before tipoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Claxton averaged 13.3 points, while handing out 159 assists. The  
junior was the player of the year in the American East conference 
as a sophomore. 
</P>
<P>
	With Claxton, Hofstra might present problems for Rutgers, which  
struggled late in the season, losing five of its last six games and 
a potential NCAA berth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
