<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Settles Coaches Earnings Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- When Southern California cut Andy  
Greer's salary by one-third, the assistant basketball coach took 
out a loan to cover living expenses. He also took the NCAA to court 
for allowing the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Greer is in line to receive at least $9,000 in lost wages.  
And the NCAA has the painful job of assessing Division I schools 
their shares of a $54.5 million settlement with Greer and about 
2,000 others affected by its short-lived restricted earnings rule. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule, adopted by Division I schools to save money, created a  
class of assistant coaches -- except in football -- whose pay was 
fixed at $12,000 per academic year and $4,000 for summer work. It 
was in effect from August 1992 until May 1995, when a judge ruled 
the NCAA had violated antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	With Tuesday's settlement, the NCAA abandoned further appeals of  
a nearly $67 million judgment won by the coaches last year. NCAA 
officials estimated that continuing the fight could have pushed the 
cost above $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't want a lawsuit. We begged, we pleaded with the NCAA,  
`Don't do this, don't put this into effect''' said Greer, who made 
$25,000 at USC before his pay was slashed, speaking Tuesday from 
his office at Northern Illinois, where he's an assistant basketball 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Wethington, NCAA executive committee chairman,  
acknowledged that the organization's handling of the case ``pitted 
employee against school and sometimes friend against friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We know there will be those will say the NCAA should have  
settled long ago,'' while others argue that appeals should have 
been pursued to the end, Wethington said. But for now, he said, 
``the association-wide nightmare is over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The nightmare could return in September, when the NCAA expects  
to notify all of the 302 Division I schools of their shares of the 
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Executive director Cedric Dempsey said the schools' financial  
pain could be cushioned by about $22 million in projected NCAA 
cost-cutting measures the next three years, but the schools would 
be responsible for the balance of the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Dempsey would not speculate on individual schools' possible  
allocations. An NCAA subcommittee is studying the question, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement was reached through mediation that began after  
the judge granted the coaches' motion in January to increase the 
$67 million judgment to $75 million to account for inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the judge must approve the settlement, clearing the way for  
the coaches to submit claims and their lawyers to take their share 
in fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount the coaches receive will probably be based on what  
they made under the cap and what their schools would otherwise have 
paid them, said Dennis Cross, a Kansas City-based lawyer for the 
coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Greer, 36, said he had ``no idea'' how much he will receive when  
checks start going out, ``and I don't think anybody does at this 
point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also unknown is how many Division I careers were derailed by the  
restricted earnings rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``A number of people got out of the coaching profession,'' Greer  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greer's own career was detoured into Division III because of the  
rule. He had nine years of college coaching, including a stint at 
Boston University, when he left USC after his third season there 
because of his paltry pay and took the head coaching job at 
Merchant Marine, which paid better. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that really bothered me was that the NCAA tried to  
portray this as covering entry-level coaches,'' he said. ``That's 
ridiculous. We worked as many hours as anybody else.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
