<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Underdog Winthrop Ready for Auburn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- To call Winthrop a longshot is an  
understatement. The Big South Conference champion Eagles are in the 
NCAA tournament for the first time, awaiting a debut Thursday 
against Auburn, the top seed in the South Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	First-year coach Gregg Marshall, who turned a 7-20 team into  
21-7 after a preseason challenge to the players, has fulfilled his 
initial goal to get a spot in the 64-team tourney field. Now, who 
knows what will happen? 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think this team will be surprised by anything that  
happens to them,'' Marshall said Wednesday. ``The fact that no No. 
16 seed has every gotten a No. 1 ... I'm not worried about that. We 
were picked dead last (in the conference). Now we're first. We're 
here. This is a reality. We're going to go out and play the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 5,600-student school in Rock Hill, S.C., has offered a men's  
basketball program for 21 years and earned its first NCAA bid by 
winning the Big South tourney two weeks ago. It's also the first 
time Winthrop has won 20 games in a season, and the turnaround 
began when Marshall arrived and told the players that anyone who 
didn't think the team could still be playing in March might as well 
pack his bags and leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first three years, every loss hurt,'' said forward Heson  
Groves, the team's scoring and rebounding leader. ``When coach 
Marshall came, I knew he was a winner. We've worked extremely hard, 
and we're not going to stop now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn (27-3), making its first NCAA appearance since 1988,  
earned a top seed despite a loss to Kentucky in the Southeastern 
Conference tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	In Thursday's other first-round games in the RCA Dome,  
fourth-seeded Ohio State plays No. 13 Murray State, No. 5 UCLA 
faces 12th-seeded Detroit, and No. 8-seed Syracuse plays No. 9 
Oklahoma State. The second round will be on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a magic carpet ride for this team this season,''  
the Winthrop coach said. ``We've given life to a program that was a 
little stagnant, a little dormant. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it was a two-part goal, to play in March, with a chance to  
advance,'' he said. ``I didn't come here to roll over. If they 
didn't think this game was necessary, the No. 1 teams would get a 
bye. But they don't. Stranger things have happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn knows that, too.  
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers beat Winthrop by 25 points in their only other  
meeting, two years ago in the regular season, but they're not 
counting on a victory by that margin, if at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't go out and match their intensity, you're liable  
to get beat,'' forward Bryant Smith said. ``Anything can happen. We 
watched Valparaiso last year. Who's to say Winthrop can't be one of 
those teams?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valparaiso, seeded 13th, reached the tourney Sweet 16 a year  
ago, a sobering lesson to all the so-called favorites. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what's going to happen,'' Auburn coach Cliff  
Ellis said. ``I know Winthrop's going to come out and play, and our 
team, I think, will play with a lot of energy. I don't know what 
the results will be, but I would be very disappointed if that 
energy wasn't there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn scoring leader, Chris Porter, a second-team All-American,  
said the Tigers' status as favorite is no cause for relaxation. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the NCAA, you don't get a second chance. You play every  
game like it's your last game,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma State (22-10) is in the tournament for the 16th time.  
The Cowboys lost to Kansas in the finals of the Big 12 Conference 
tourney. Syracuse (21-11), making its 25th NCAA appearance, lost to 
Connecticut in the Big East semifinals. Both teams received 
at-large bids. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two teams are pretty evenly matched,'' Cowboys coach Eddie  
Sutton said. ``Maybe the biggest keys will be how well we can 
defend their transition game and how well we get on the defensive 
boards. Then the biggest key in any game is how well you shoot it. 
That camouflages so many shortcomings in other areas of the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Syracuse, the NCAA runner-up in 1987 and 1996, lost in the  
regional semifinal to Duke last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both teams might be a little better than they played this  
year,'' Sycacuse coach Jim Boeheim said of his Orangemen and 
Oklahoma State. ``We'll find out.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
