<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Charged in Baby's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A woman was charged Wednesday with covering up  
the death of her infant son by cremating the boy after he drowned 
in a bathtub. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman's boyfriend and his sister also were charged in the  
death of 14-month-old Christopher Hutton last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Mjelde, 22, was charged with first-degree criminal  
assistance and filing a false police report. Police say she 
initially told them the boy was staying with his father. 
</P>
<P>
	Her boyfriend, Stanley Red, 24, was charged with first-degree  
manslaughter for allegedly allowing Christopher to drown in a 
bathtub in October. His sister, Cynthia Red, also was charged with 
first-degree criminal assistance in the cover-up. 
</P>
<P>
	All were in custody Wednesday pending arraignment, scheduled for  
March 18. Bail was set at $200,000 for Red, $50,000 for Ms. Mjelde 
and $25,000 for Ms. Red, authorities said. It was not known if the 
three had attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities lacked evidence to file murder charges in the case,  
Prosecutor Norm Maleng said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say Ms. Mjelde left the boy with Red while she went to  
California for three days beginning Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	At some point, police said, Red left the boy alone in a bathtub  
in about 8 inches of water while he went to the store to buy beer 
and the baby drowned. 
</P>
<P>
	Upon her return, Ms. Mjelde suggested they burn the body rather  
than bury it so she could keep the ashes, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three used gasoline to burn the baby's body in a garbage can  
in a nearby park before eventually heading to Ms. Red's home to use 
her fireplace, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police began investigating in January, when the boy's aunt told  
authorities the boy had not been seen for about three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
