<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading  
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, 
and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *DuPont, up 3 1/8 at 56 11/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company will issue separate stock for its blossoming  
life-sciences business that will trade separately from DuPont's 
current stock. Analysts have complained that DuPont's larger and 
more mature chemical business overshadowed the life-sciences arm, 
which is much smaller but is perceived as having more growth 
potential. 

</P>
<P>
 *Genentech Inc., down 1/4 at 17 1/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	Two new clot-busting drugs appear to be as effective as TPA,  
Genentech Corp.'s flagship medicine and the standard treatment for 
heart attacks, but much easier to administer. 

</P>
<P>
 *AT&AMP;T, down 2 1/4 at 83 5/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The telecommunications giant is selling $5 to $6 billion worth  
of global long-term debt. 

</P>
<P>
 *Computer Associates, down 6 1/4 at 33 3/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley downgraded the computer retailer's stock to  
neutral from outperform, citing concerns about softer near-term 
demand, increasing competition, and a potential peaking of margins. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Cisco Systems, down 2 1/16 at 103 1/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	The stock fell on Tuesday reports that the company had warned in  
a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission that its gross 
margins will decrease in the future and that its research and 
development expenes will rise more quickly than its sales. Cisco 
makes remote access and computer switching products, as well as 
technology that routs information through computer. 

</P>
<P>
 *Lycos, up 12 3/8 at 108 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	Prospects grew that an alternative suitor to USA Networks Inc.  
would emerge, including an outright purchase by 20-percent 
stakeholder CMGI. On Tuesday, David Wetherell, CMGI's chief 
executive, resigned from Lycos's board because of his opposition to 
Lycos' planned merger with USA. Wetherell said he is exploring 
other options for Lycos. 

</P>
<P>
 *PSS World Medical, down 2 31/32 at 9 1/32.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company expects fourth-quarter earnings of 19 cents to  
21cents per share, below analysts' expected 24 cents. 



</P>
</TEXT>
