<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marty Cordova's MRI Shows No Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Minnesota Twins left fielder Marty  
Cordova doesn't have structural damage in his right shoulder, 
general manager Terry Ryan said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordova, a disappointment the last two seasons in part because  
of injuries, had the magnetic resonance imaging exam Wednesday 
because of persistent soreness. Ryan said Cordova should be able to 
resume throwing soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordova, who has 25 home runs and 120 RBIs the last two years  
after a combined 40 and 195 in his first major league seasons, 
thinks the pain in his shoulder resulted from an alteration in his 
swing. 
</P>
<P>
	He was bothered by it last week and has had trouble throwing  
since. He hasn't picked up a baseball in three days and he didn't 
travel to Dunedin for the Twins' 6-4 loss to Toronto on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 12:18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glitches in Army Parachute System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) -- Some Army paratroop units have stopped  
using a new kind of backup parachute after it failed to open when 
tested on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Fort Bragg officials said there are no known cases of it failing  
during a jump. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of the 28,000 members of the 18th Airborne Corps who  
are stationed at Fort Bragg are using an older backup parachute 
while Army safety officials examine the new one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we continue to see this as a fairly short-range  
situation,'' Lt. Col. Rick Spearman said Wednesday. ``Our only 
concern right now is for us to do the prudent thing, the right 
thing -- not place soldiers at unnecessary risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paratroop units at other Army bases, including Fort Benning,  
Ga., continue to use the new model. 
</P>
<P>
	Airborne units began using the Modified Improved Reserve  
Parachute System in November. It has a spring-loaded mechanism to 
help it open. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Fort Bragg scaled back use of the parachutes March  
3 after a soldier pulled his reserve rip cord while on the ground 
and nothing happened. Safety investigators then examined 10 
parachutes and found six did not deploy when the rip cord was 
pulled. 
</P>
<P>
	Col. John Latimer, chief of staff at Fort Benning, said that  
even if the chute sometimes doesn't open on the ground, it will 
work in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's reliable. It works great. There is not a problem with  
it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin Aerospace, the manufacturer, said the new parachute has  
saved six lives since Fort Bragg began using it last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Guidelines issued last week direct soldiers to punch the  
parachute with a fist to loosen it if the rip cord fails during a 
jump. Army officials said that was standard procedure with the 
older model. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 09:55:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Takeover Shakes Up French Banking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A $37.2 billion takeover bid by Banque Nationale de  
Paris for Paribas and Societe Generale that would create the 
world's largest banking group sent shock waves today through the 
normally staid French bank sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid coincides with widespread consolidation among European  
banks scrambling to compete in a market transformed by a new common 
currency and fewer barriers to financial trade. 
</P>
<P>
	It also shows that French banks, often criticized for their slow  
reaction to consolidation, are moving frantically to catch up with 
their neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The euro has the effect of increasing competitive pressures in  
Europe,'' Banque Nationale chairman Michel Pebereau said today at a 
news conference detailing the takeover bid. ``France needed to 
create a banking champion. Our offer sets this up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Banque Nationale's takeover bid, announced late Tuesday, comes  
just weeks after Societe Generale moved to buy Paribas for $17.07 
billion to create Europe's second-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined bank would hold nearly $1 trillion in assets,  
surpassing the $800 billion in assets from the bank that would be 
created by the pending merger of Deutsche Bank and Bankers Trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said today that the takeover bid throws into question  
France's role in future consolidation of the European banking 
sector, and is likely to undergo scrutiny from anti-trust 
authorities in Brussels and in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	It is also seen as an attempt to pre-empt a foreign takeover bid  
for French banks. 
</P>
<P>
	``What worries me is that this is a Franco-French solution,''  
said Bruno Eudes, a trader with the brokerage house 
Meeschaert-Rousselle. ``It doesn't add much to the banks' 
international competitiveness and excludes any foreign bank from 
getting a big share of the French industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement today, Paribas chairman Andre Levy-Lang and  
Daniel Bouton, his Societe Generale counterpart, described Banque 
Nationale's intentions as ``risky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The chairmen said they had been unaware of Banque Nationale's  
interest until Tuesday night. ``This operation therefore cannot be 
portrayed as being friendly,'' they concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Pebereau insisted that the bid was not hostile. ``It isn't a  
question of a forced marriage,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This really positions BNP as a major player in the European  
scene and leaves them well-positioned to move into North America in 
a bigger way,'' said Keith Stock, a New York-based global 
management consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	Banque Nationale's bid would be the second-highest price ever  
paid in a bank deal, just shy of the $41.5 billion merger between 
NationsBank Corp. and BankAmerica last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Banque Nationale is offering 15 of its shares for seven Societe  
Generale shares and 11 of its shares for eight Paribas shares. 
Trading in shares of all three banks have been suspended on the 
Paris stock exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	While French banks have been slow to expand into the United  
States, several European banks are making moves, including Deutsche 
Bank, HSBC, Dresdner and ABN Amro. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance companies are also getting in the game. On Monday,  
Fortis, one of the biggest insurance and banking companies in 
Europe, said it would buy American Bankers Insurance Group, a Miami 
insurer. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Aegon NV said it was buying TransAmerica of San  
Francisco for almost $10 billion. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
