<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dr. Tom Preparing for Iowa Finale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Tom Davis removed his glasses and took a soothing  
sip of water as he listened to his players pay him tribute. 
Emotions are hard to hide as Dr. Tom prepares to write his final 
basketball prescription at Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, whose Hawkeyes play Alabama-Birmingham in the first round  
of the NCAA tournament Thursday, learned last spring that his 13th 
season in Iowa City would be his last. His contract would not be 
renewed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I debated a long time whether to come back another year and do  
this thing,'' Davis said Wednesday. ``I did it because of the 
seniors and my staff. Sometimes I say, `I'm not sure I should have 
done this,' but the guys have been terrific. They've really been a 
lot of fun and appreciative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To some degree, Iowa also has overachieved, winning games at  
Ohio State, at Michigan and at Kansas. Though they slumped late in 
the season and finished 9-7 in the Big Ten, the Hawkeyes enter the 
tournament ranked No. 21 and the fifth seed in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Iowa hasn't advanced past the second round of the NCAAs  
since 1988, the players have plenty of inspiration to extend the 
Davis era another three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing for coach has been the greatest basketball experience  
of my life,'' senior guard Kent McCausland said. ``It was more than 
just wanting to be a Hawkeye. I wanted to soak in everything he had 
to give me. It's been perfect. I hope we can take it as far as we 
can for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like McCausland, senior Jess Settles has treasured his time with  
Davis. Settles missed nearly all of the 1997-98 season with health 
problems, but won another year of eligibility -- a year he is not 
taking for granted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came out of high school and I considered myself an average  
player,'' said Settles, who ranks sixth on Iowa's career scoring 
list. ``He gave me the opportunity to have the chance to be great. 
I owe my entire career to him. I would have made a huge mistake if 
I'd have gone anywhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, a 60-year-old with a Ph.D and a career record of 541-289,  
doesn't know where he will be this time next year. He has not ruled 
out coaching and said Thursday he plans ``to look at everything'' 
available to him. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, he is hoping to get past Alabama-Birmingham and keep  
his emotions in check. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way I'll deal with it is day-to-day, minute-to-minute,  
whatever,'' Davis said. ``When other thoughts jump into your head -- 
which they do -- just push them aside, and then when the season's 
over, look back and reflect.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
