<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Declares Strike Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Protesters blocked provincial highways  
with rocks and trees and police repelled demonstrators with tear 
gas in Ecuador's capital today, the first day of a nationwide 
strike over economic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Indians barricaded highways in 15 of the country's  
22 provinces, causing long traffic jams. Demonstrators hurled 
stones at police and burned tires on the streets of Guayaquil, 
Ecuador's main port city 170 miles southwest of the capital, Quito. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks, markets and factories were closed, and the streets of  
Quito were largely deserted as bus drivers heeded the strike call. 
Police used tear gas to disperse about 100 marchers 10 blocks from 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second national strike called by the leftist-led  
Unified Workers Federation, Ecuador's largest labor federation, 
since President Jamil Mahuad took office seven months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with increased powers under a newly declared state of  
emergency, machine gun-toting troops guarded power plants, oil 
installations and gasoline stations against union members who have 
threatened to disrupt vital industries. 
</P>
<P>
	With the 48-hour strike likely to aggravate Ecuador's economic  
crisis, the president on Tuesday declared a 60-day state of 
emergency that limits freedom of movement and assembly and gives 
him the authority to order strikers back to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Unions have threatened to paralyze Ecuador if Mahuad does not  
back down on reforms that have caused prices to soar and a bill now 
in Congress that calls for deep public spending cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Some influential members of the armed forces tried to calm the  
nation of 12 million people by denying there was discontent within 
the military over the economic crisis and offering to protect oil 
installations from strikers. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior Minister Vladimiro Alvarez said today that soldiers  
have orders not to violently disperse highways barricades where 
protesters ``are using women and children as cannon fodder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mahuad has extended through Thursday an emergency bank holiday  
that has shut banks since Monday to keep people from withdrawing 
their savings in anticipation of drastic economic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday was declared a surprise bank holiday after a run on  
deposits last week threatened Ecuador's tottering financial system. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuador's currency, the sucre, lost a quarter of its value last  
week amid rumors the government planned to forcibly convert dollar 
bank accounts into sucres and doubts about Mahuad's ability to 
reform Ecuador's statist economy. 
</P>
<P>
	With banks and automatic teller machines closed for three days  
now, many people have no money to buy basic goods, leading to 
rising popular discontent. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Ana Lucia Armijos has said that the government  
will announce emergency economic measures Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuador's economy is in tatters after floods last year did $2.6  
billion in damage and the price of its main export, oil, plummeted. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic growth has stagnated, inflation is running near 50  
percent, the budget deficit reached $1.2 billion and state coffers 
are bare. In September, Mahuad ended fuel subsidies, causing prices 
to soar. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have stopped working not because we support the strike or  
not, but simply because we cannot work. We're broke,'' said truck 
driver Guido Molina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
