<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Pull Back / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds pulled back Wednesday, halting a  
three-session advance, as traders locked in some gains before 
Thursday's report on retail activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 3/8 point  
Monday, or by $3.75 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, rose to 5.55 percent from 5.53 
percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have been rebounding from inflation jitters since Friday,  
bolstered by an encouraging economic report and some soothing 
remarks by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders will scour Thursday's report on February retail sales  
for more clues on whether inflationary pressures remain under 
control. Rapid inflation makes fixed-income investments like bonds 
less attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	Also pressuring the bond market Wednesday were more than $4  
billion worth in new debt securities from Lucent Technologies Inc. 
and mortgage company Freddie Mac. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market Wednesday, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities fell 1/16 point to 1/8 point, while intermediate 
maturities fell 3/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.80 
points to 1,284.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were unchanged from late  
Tuesday's 4.59 percent while the discount held steady at 4.47 
percent. Six-month yields were unchanged at 4.66 percent, and the 
discount remained 4.49 percent. One-year yields rose to 4.74 
percent, while the discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.51 
percent compared with late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks was unchanged from late Tuesday's 4.56 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/16 point to 124. The average yield to 
maturity rose to 5.23 percent, up from 5.22 percent late Monday. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
