<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jerry Reed: Still Picking, Grinning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRENTWOOD, Tenn. (AP) -- Jerry Reed sits by the TV in his condo,  
a stone's throw from the 18th hole of a golf course, cracking up as 
he watches the soap opera ``Days of Our Lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now this guy -- the one with that fake Russian accent -- he's  
got the mind-control thing going with that girl,'' the 
singer-guitarist-actor-comedian gleefully explains. ``I love this 
stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A reporter tries to engage him in conversation. A photographer  
glances at his watch. A publicist fidgets as his schedule slips 
away. Reed winks and turns back to the soap. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, 61, is supposed to be spending the day promoting  
``Pickin,'' his first album of new music in nearly a decade. But 
he'll do it his way, squeezing every ounce of fun out of the 
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're laughing your guts out, how can you be depressed?''  
he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Jerry Reed Hubbard in Atlanta, he gained notoriety in the  
1970s by making people laugh with songs like ``When You're Hot, 
You're Hot'' and playing rakish good ol' boys in films, most 
notably the truck-driving sidekick in the ``Smokey and the Bandit'' 
series starring his friend, Burt Reynolds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I was never going to be a Perry Como or Tom Jones or  
Glen Campbell,'' Reed said. ``I wanted to be a Phil Harris, a Spike 
Jones. My favorite people on Earth are the Jack Bennys and Jackie 
Gleasons and Red Skeltons and Sid Caesars -- those guys that could 
just tear your head off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed's humor often overshadowed his musical talents. He's a  
superb guitarist; his instrumental ``The Claw'' has become a 
classic that guitarists struggle to master. And he's an 
accomplished singer-songwriter whose range goes far beyond novelty 
hits like ``Amos Moses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote the touching ``A Thing Called Love,'' a hit for Johnny  
Cash in 1972. Elvis Presley recorded Reed's ``Guitar Man'' and 
``U.S. Male,'' and used Reed as his guitarist. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed has played at thousands of recording sessions, including  
those of Dean Martin and Frank Sinatra. Chet Atkins, his mentor, 
has recorded many of his guitar instrumentals and collaborated on 
albums with him. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed started playing guitar at 9, and was good enough to perform  
on the bill with country stars like Ernest Tubb when still in his 
teens. He got his first record deal at 17. 
</P>
<P>
	After a stint in the military, he moved to Nashville in 1962. He  
became an in-demand guitarist at recording sessions and wrote some 
hits, but attempts to mold him into a standard country star didn't 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I owe almost every bit of success that has come to me to Chet  
Atkins,'' Reed says. Atkins, a legendary guitarist and music 
industry executive, signed Reed to RCA and produced his records. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a nonconformist, and he suggested that I just play my  
guitar and sing my songs and he'd release singles,'' Reed says. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed hit the charts in 1967 with ``Tupelo Mississippi Flash.''  
He quickly established an inimitable style: funny, unabashedly 
Southern songs accompanied by his aggressive, complex guitar 
playing. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1971, he had a No. 1 country hit with ``When You're Hot,  
You're Hot.'' The song went to No. 9 on the pop charts. 
</P>
<P>
	From there, his comic talents won him frequent guest shots on  
the ``Glen Campbell Goodtime Hour.'' He was host of a short-lived 
network variety show in 1972, then became one of Reynolds' favorite 
movie partners, starting in 1974 with ``W.W. and the Dixie Dance 
Kings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He kept scoring country hits until 1983, including a No. 1 tune  
with ``She Got the Goldmine (I Got the Shaft)'' in 1982. Then he 
was pushed aside by a new generation of stars. 
</P>
<P>
	He continued playing concerts, but faded from national view  
until his film comeback playing an outlandishly mean Southern 
college football coach in the 1998 comedy ``The Waterboy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed now has teamed with fellow country stars Waylon Jennings,  
Mel Tillis and Bobby Bare to form the Old Dogs, a less glamorous 
version of The Highwaymen, of which Jennings is a member. They sing 
comic, ribald songs about the perils of growing older. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not one of those flat-belly singers anymore,'' Reed says.  
``The record industry is one of those industries that will 
discourage you and turn you loose. They sell records to those 
screaming little girls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed says he understands the country music industry's obsession  
with youth, and it's not a big deal to him. 
</P>
<P>
	``But guitar playing is timeless,'' Reed says. The 10 songs on  
``Pickin''' are all excuses for him to show off his guitar playing. 
</P>
<P>
	The album has autobiographical songs in the ``Guitar Man'' mode  
(``Does Anybody Want to Boogie''), Atkins-style acoustic 
instrumentals (``My Priscilla'') and, of course, a novelty song 
(``Talk the Talk &AMP; Walk the Walk.'') 
</P>
<P>
	On the latter, Reed plays a braggart who can't back up his big  
talk. It's the kind of record that made him a star. 
</P>
<P>
	``The secret of my records is the attitude,'' Reed said. ``I  
want my records to be fun and individualistic. ... Today, I can 
hear records and I don't know who ... I'm listening to half the 
time. Do you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite all his musical accomplishments, Reed remains best known  
as Reynolds' partner in the ``Bandit'' movies. 
</P>
<P>
	That's fine with him, he says.  
</P>
<P>
	``To this day, kids follow me down the street talking about  
those movies,'' Reed says. ``They see the reruns on Saturday 
afternoons. The pictures gave me an (image) that kept me out there 
long after the music industry wasn't interested any more.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in country music ...  
</P>
<P>
	OSCAR BUZZ: Much-deserving country singer Allison Moorer will  
get a big career boost March 21 when she sings the Oscar-nominated 
song ``A Soft Place to Fall'' at the Academy Awards. The song is 
from ``The Horse Whisperer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	REISSUES: Sony Legacy is coming out with two dandy collections  
this month of Willie Nelson and Johnny Cash. ``The Very Best of 
Willie Nelson'' and ``The Man in Black'' each feature 30 songs on 
two CDs, many of them classics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
