<DOCNO> APW19990310.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 03:14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors To Testify Against McDougal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Grand jurors will testify against  
Whitewater figure Susan McDougal in her contempt trial, as will an 
FBI agent who investigated her use of a government-backed 
fraudulent loan for $300,000, a prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Associate Independent Counsel Mark Barrett would not say Tuesday  
who else might testify this week at the trial of Mrs. McDougal, who 
remains defiant after having served 18 months in prison on a civil 
contempt citation. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, 44, faces a three-count indictment alleging  
criminal contempt and obstruction of justice for refusing to talk 
to the Whitewater grand jury about President Clinton and first 
lady's business dealings in Arkansas. If convicted, Mrs. McDougal 
could be fined $750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening statements were expected to begin this afternoon.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors wanted Mrs. McDougal to testify in September 1996  
and again in April 1998. Among other things, they wanted to know if 
Clinton knew about Mrs. McDougal's use of the $300,000 loan for 
which she was convicted of fraud in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal said she didn't have any relevant information and  
that prosecutors wanted her to lie -- a claim they deny. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett said that among the government's witnesses will be FBI  
agent Michael Patkus, who investigated Mrs. McDougal's use of the 
loan. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Whitewater prosecutor W. Hickman Ewing Jr. has said the  
government could prove that Mrs. McDougal had relevant information 
to give the panel, which disbanded last May. 
</P>
<P>
	During jury selection, questions centered on whether potential  
jurors harbored animosity toward Whitewater Independent Counsel 
Kenneth Starr, the president or Mrs. McDougal. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, ex-husband James McDougal and the Clintons were  
business partners in the failed real estate development known as 
Whitewater. McDougal died in prison a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The McDougals and then-Gov. Jim Guy Tucker were convicted in  
1996. Mrs. McDougal also was recently acquitted of embezzlement in 
a separate, unrelated California case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 10:44:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phills Cleared To Re-Join Hornets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Bobby Phills has been cleared to rejoin  
the Charlotte Hornets on Wednesday after additional tests showed he 
did not have a stress fracture in his lower left leg, as had been 
originally feared. 
</P>
<P>
	Initial X-rays were inconclusive and Phills, the Hornets'  
starting guard, was held out of Tuesday night's victory against 
Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	A second set of X-rays showed no fracture, and Phills flew to  
Philadelphia, where the Hornets play the 76ers on Wednesday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
