<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Dollar Hurts Snowbird Biz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Fern Plamondon doesn't smile when she says a  
weak Canadian dollar may benefit her shuffleboard game. 
</P>
<P>
	Plamondon, 64, who migrates from Edmonton, Alberta, to Arizona  
each winter, says an unfavorable exchange rate has prompted her to 
cut costs by doing more free activities like shuffleboard at the 
recreational vehicle park where she stays. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our rent is $3,500 instead of $2,500. We're trying to stay at  
home (at the R.V.) and spend less money,'' Plamondon said as she 
arranged handmade lace at a weekly bazaar at the Good Life Resort. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses throughout Arizona used to a steady stream of  
spending by Canadian snowbirds say they are being hurt by a weak 
Canadian dollar, which is leading to fewer visitors who spend less 
and head home sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	And an alarming number of Canadians are saying goodbye to the  
Good Life altogether by selling their units, according to park 
manager Marianne Weins. 
</P>
<P>
	``This year is very unusual. Maybe we have 20 to 30 units for  
sale, all by Canadians. Usually we have about six,'' says Weins, 
who is in her 17th winter at the Good Life. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian dollar hit a 30-year low in October and has hovered  
around that level since then, according to Peter Dalton, spokesman 
at Custom House Currency Exchange in Victoria, British Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian dollar's decline means that between March and  
October 1998, American goods and services became about 9 percent 
more expensive for Canadians. Dating back to October 1997, the 
American price hike for Canadians is 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	For many Canadians, that has meant cutting back on winter  
escapes. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're calling to find something cheaper and for a shorter  
period of time,'' says Fred Farshler, a rental agent at McCulloch 
Realty in Lake Havasu City. 
</P>
<P>
	The sluggishness of this year's rentals prompted McCulloch to  
shorten the minimum rental period from three months to one month, 
unprecedented in his 15 years in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally, by the end of November we're completely rented  
through April, but this year's been an ongoing process,'' Farshler 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Another property manager in Lake Havasu City, Londonderry  
Realty, also reports a downturn in Canadian business. 
</P>
<P>
	``We usually have about 20 Canadians, but this year we have only  
five,'' says Marie Neadle, who has managed the company's 200 
properties for the past nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	The decrease in numbers doesn't tell the whole story.  
</P>
<P>
	``A couple of (the Canadians) stayed for one month instead of  
three months and they have tended to look at cheaper units,'' 
Neadle says. 
</P>
<P>
	They also spend less.  
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't bought much clothes this year and we have to shop  
much more carefully for our groceries,'' says Edie Lawton, 63, a 
Good Life resident from Fruitvale, British Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sew and I haven't been buying much material, either,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonnie Barsness, president of the Lake Havasu Tourism Bureau,  
said the decrease in Canadian visitors got the winter season off to 
a slow start for rental agencies in Lake Havasu City, but March 
bookings look promising. 
</P>
<P>
	Chamber of Commerce officials and the Arizona Office of Tourism  
recently made a trip to western Canada to try to drum up snowbird 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the exchange rate is hard to counteract. We have no  
control over it,'' Barsness says. 
</P>
<P>
	Milt Fort, acting director of sales and marketing at the Mesa  
Convention and Visitors Bureau, says Mesa is also reporting a 
decline in Canadian business because of currency woes. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far this winter we are probably 3 or 4 percent down and  
people who come say they are planning to spend less,'' Fort says. 
</P>
<P>
	But not all destinations in Arizona say they are seeing fewer  
Canadians. 
</P>
<P>
	``We appear to be a busy as ever,'' says Roger Beadle, executive  
director for the Yuma Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``Our walk-in 
traffic at the visitors center is up 67 percent over last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Yuma Convention and Visitors Bureau does not  
specifically track Canadian visitors, property managers in Yuma 
reflected a similarly rosy picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been saying we'll be seeing fewer and fewer Canadians  
because of the currency situation, but we haven't seen that 
happening,'' says Jami Frandsen of Realty Executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Yuma property manager, who also reported a strong rental  
market among Canadians, says Yuma enjoys certain advantages over 
other areas that might give it more staying power. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Lake Havasu) is a lot smaller and they're probably more  
congested,'' says Barbara Horn, also of Realty Executives. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dalton of the Custom House Currency Exchange says from what  
he hears from about 3,500 Canadian customers who travel to Arizona, 
everyone is feeling the effect of the currency decline. 
</P>
<P>
	``It affects everything, including the day-to-day costs,''  
Dalton says. ``In terms of long-term planning, the exchange rate is 
the most significant factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Finn, 74, from Alberta, Calgary, says the exchange rate  
prompted him shorten his stay this year from five months to four. 
</P>
<P>
	But he says he's holding out on cutting down on golf.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll probably continue golfing twice a week, but I might have  
to cut down next year if things don't improve,'' says Finn with a 
smile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 11:53:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gallup Presidential Poll Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some results from a Gallup Poll on the presidential race,  
Elizabeth Dole, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al 
Gore. When the total is less than 100 percent, the remainder didn't 
know or offered no opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	--As of today, do you lean more toward Al Gore, the Democrat, or  
Elizabeth Dole, the Republican? 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, 45 percent; Dole, 50 percent. About the same as in January  
of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	--As of today, do you lean more toward Al Gore, the Democrat, or  
George W. Bush, the Republican? 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, 41 percent; Bush, 56 percent. A Gallup poll in January had  
Bush and Gore in a dead heat. Many polls in recent months have 
given Bush a double-digit lead. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	--Everything else being equal, who do you think would make the  
better president. ... 
</P>
<P>
	A man, 42 percent; a woman, 31 percent; would not matter, 22  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who preferred a man as president, the reasons most  
often cited were ability to control emotions, the tradition of male 
presidents and ability to make decisions. Among those who said a 
woman would make a better president, the three reasons most often 
cited were their common sense or intelligence, a need for a change 
and their compassion. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	--If your party nominated a generally well-qualified woman for  
office would you vote for that person? 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, 92 percent; no, 7 percent. A decade ago, eight of 10 said  
yes to that question. And in 1975, less than three-quarters of the 
population said yes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The Gallup poll of 1,014 people was taken Friday through Sunday  
with an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
