<DOCNO> APW19990310.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 07:35:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves' Wohlers Shows Old Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Wohlers showed a glimpse of his old  
form Tuesday, retiring three of four batters as he pitched a 
scoreless inning for Atlanta against the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers entered in the third inning and gave up a single to  
right field by Mike Piazza, then retired John Olerud and Craig 
Paquette on grounders and Robin Ventura on a flyout. Wohlers threw 
11 fastballs and one slider. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing today was I didn't get ahead,'' Wohlers said.  
``I got behind a couple of hitters and I was able to come back and 
throw some fastballs. I think Piazza's ball would have been a home 
run if the wind wasn't blowing in so hard. That's all right. A 
little luck now and then doesn't hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Catcher Javy Lopez was impressed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to last year, this is a big, big, big improvement,''  
Lopez said. ``He's starting to get his confidence back and 
hopefully this is not just a two-game thing. Today was kind of 
windy, so it's hard to throw hard. But on a nice day, he would have 
thrown 95 easy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Bobby Cox also was pleased. In his first outing, Wohlers  
gave up four earned runs in an inning against Houston last Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great hope right now,'' Cox said. ``You really didn't  
know what to expect. He's not that far away from getting good. He 
was throwing plenty hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers said pitching is becoming natural again for him. He said  
thought earlier he could correct his problems physically, but that 
has changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``To get to where I'm at now, I needed to concentrate on my  
mechanics,'' Wohlers said. ``My brain would just think about bad 
stuff. What I try to do now, especially when I'm warming up, is 
remind myself about mechanical things, to get to the point where my 
mechanics are dumb proof. 
</P>
<P>
	``Half the pitches I threw today, I just saw the sign and I just  
went toward the target. That's where you need to be. You know what 
pitch you're going to throw, you know you can make yourself do it. 
Just go. My mind's basically blank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of 7,323 cheered wildly when Wohlers was announced as  
starter Kevin Millwood's replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully I'll get to the point where I get the last out of  
the ballgame and people stand up and cheer because we won,'' 
Wohlers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
