<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Lawmakers Push School Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans expect debate on their  
education bill to go more smoothly than it has in the Senate, which 
has wrangled over a similar measure for five days. 
</P>
<P>
	``There isn't a good reason why a bill like this hasn't just  
hasn't flown through,'' Rep. Mike Castle, R-Del., said of the bill, 
which would give states more flexibility in the way they can spend 
federal education dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	He predicted the House version of the bill would pass quickly,  
despite chances that the House Democrats will offer the same kind 
of amendments slowing down the Senate bill. The House was working 
late Tuesday on how to manage the potential amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	A success in the House could put pressure on the Senate, which  
remains deadlocked over Republicans' determination to block a 
new-teacher plan that Democrats want to attach to the bill. The 
amendment by Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., would reduce class sizes 
by hiring 100,000 teachers over the next seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	Since education's emergence as a popular polling issue, both  
parties have rushed to be the first to pass an education bill this 
session, leading to frustration on both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to ask whether the Democrats really want to give  
states autonomy,'' said Joe Karpinski, a spokesman for the Senate 
Labor Human and Resources Committee, which sent the bill to the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, charged that Democrats are using  
the bipartisan education flexibility plan to push through other 
initiatives they want and force Republicans into an early vote 
against those ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is all meant, personally, to get someone to make  
a vote against a program that could be used in a 30-second 
television spot,'' Voinovich said as his fellow Republicans failed 
on a second attempt Tuesday to limit the number of proposals that 
can be attached to the ``ed-flex'' bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats insisted Tuesday they are not trying to  
embarrass the Republicans on education. Senate Minority Leader Tom 
Daschle, D-S.D., said he unsuccessfully offered to limit the number 
of Democratic amendments and ensure the bill would be completed 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle said Democrats will keep offering their proposals, even  
if Republicans pull the bill from the floor out of frustration and 
Democrats have to attach their plans to other measures. A key focus 
is the class-size plan. 
</P>
<P>
	An initial $1 billion for the teacher plan was approved by  
Congress last year in a spending bill compromise. President Clinton 
has said the whole plan would cost $11 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the second day in a row, the Republican leadership has  
continued its efforts to stand in the way of voting on an amendment 
to finish the job of hiring 100,000 teachers to reduce class 
size,'' Clinton said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill, which started with broad bipartisan support,  
has become enmeshed in political scuffles. Two more votes to try to 
block the amendments were scheduled for today. A third try is 
slated for Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S 280.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
