<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer's Wynalda Has Knee Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- San Jose Clash forward Eric Wynalda  
had surgery Wednesday to repair torn knee ligaments and will miss 
most of the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynalda, 29, was on loan to Leon in Mexico's first division when  
he was hurt two weeks ago. He is expected to be sidelined for 
5-to-6 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury originally was thought to be only a sprain but it  
turned out to be a torn anterior cruciate ligament and medial 
meniscus in his left knee. Dr. Bert Mandelbaum, the U.S. national 
team's physician, repaired the injury during a 90-minute operation 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynalda has 32 goals in 101 career appearances for the United  
States and is the national team's leading scorer. He was scheduled 
to remain with Leon until May, and the Clash were thought to be 
discussing possible trades. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clash obtained Raul Diaz Arce during the offseason, making  
Wynalda expendable, but the Salvadorian forward has not reported to 
the Clash in a contract dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
