<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Digs Out From Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The capital city was slowly digging out and  
getting back to work today after the first significant snowfall in 
years snarled commutes and gave many people a day off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wish I had gotten a Jeep,'' said John Smithson as he  
dug his sports car out of a high drift caused by snowplows on a 
city street early today. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the region's approximately 270,000 federal workers took  
the day off, although the snow day counts against their annual 
leave time. And with many others staying home as well, traffic was 
light. The roads were mostly passable, with some slippery, slushy 
spots on side roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress for the most part was back to normal today, with the  
House going to work on an education bill and scheduling four votes 
on measures that were postponed Tuesday as the heavy snow piled up. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hearings were canceled, including two House Veterans  
Affairs Committee hearings and a Senate hearing on education 
research, but dozens of other committees were meeting as scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	Light flurries still hung in the air today as Washington awoke  
to 8.5 inches of snow -- the most in years and more than enough to 
close schools and offices across the city and its suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Some runways were closed at both Reagan National and Dulles  
International airports, and airlines told travelers to expect 
delays. The city's subways and buses were running, although buses 
skipped some hilly sidestreets. 
</P>
<P>
	Those heading to work were mostly good-natured, despite deep  
slush that made street corners tricky for those without tall snow 
boots. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a White Christmas three months late,'' said Ann  
Powers, who was commuting to work at a law firm in downtown 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm, which took the city somewhat by surprise, carried the  
first significant snowfall in three years, and the most from a 
March storm since 1993. Red-faced forecasters began the day Tuesday 
predicting only an inch or two of snow, and spent the day revising 
their estimates upward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
