<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``The Disco Box'' (Rhino) -- Various  

</P>
<P>
	Rhino Records has unleashed its most ambitious effort yet  
devoted to the ``Boogie Nights'' generation -- disco balls and 
platform shoes not included. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Disco Box'' ($59.98) is four discs that include most of  
the essentials of one of the most criticized music forms ever, from 
the instrumental ``Love's Theme'' (1973) to Kool &AMP; The Gang's 
``Fresh'' (1985). 
</P>
<P>
	To today's dour, techno dance crowd, disco may sound awfully  
dated. Still, most of the 80 tunes register instant nostalgic 
smiles (``Rock the Boat'' by The Hues Corporation, for one). Others 
should remain in a time capsule (``Get Dancin''' by Disco-Tex &AMP; the 
Sex-O-Lettes featuring Sir Monti Rock III). 
</P>
<P>
	The set is packaged in a silver holographic box with liner notes  
that try too hard to put a kind of academic spin on an era that 
just wanted to have a good time. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazingly, the box set ignores the most popular disco act ever --  
the Bee Gees. No ``Saturday Night Fever'' tracks? Rhino couldn't 
get the rights. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter. Despite its knocks over the years, maybe disco will  
be taken seriously for the mindless fun that it was. So get out 
there and shake your booty! 
</P>
<P>
	-- By David Kligman, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Confessin''' (Black Top Records) -- Rusty Zinn  

</P>
<P>
	Generation-X singer-guitarist Rusty Zinn proves once again the  
timelessness of the blues. Zinn artfully heads East with his 
California swing roots to meet Chicago blues about midway in the 
jump tradition of Kansas City. Zinn's voice brings to mind Gene 
Pitney, which just adds to the nostalgic good-times feeling of 
``Confessin','' Zinn's second compact disc. 
</P>
<P>
	But don't think of Zinn as some sort of novelty act. He studied  
with Chicago's Luther Tucker and cut his teeth touring with Kim 
Wilson. For ``Confessin','' Zinn enlisted fellow West Coast 
troupers Rick Estrin and Charlie Baty of Little Charlie and the 
Nightcats. At 28, Zinn should be ``confessin''' with authority for 
some time to come. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Garage Inc.'' (Elektra Records) -- Metallica  

</P>
<P>
	If you think that when you've heard one heavy metal record  
you've heard them all, then hear this. ``Garage Inc.,'' Metallica's 
collection of covers and tributes to its predecessors, incorporates 
almost the entire history of the genre into two CDs -- one filled 
with new tracks and another with previous covers. 
</P>
<P>
	And while the results are spotty, the highlights make the  
project worth a listen, especially since one of heavy metal's 
biggest acts digs deep into its past. 
</P>
<P>
	Metallica is usually at its best when it doesn't take itself too  
seriously, and the same applies here. The four-piece band's 
rapid-fire cover of Budgie's ``Crash Course in Brain Surgery'' 
stays just on the right side of camp. And on Diamondhead's ``It's 
Electric,'' Metallica shows its knack for finding the hook among 
all the power chords. 
</P>
<P>
	Those looking for the crossover appeal will cuddle up to the  
band's edgy take on the Bob Seger road-blues classic ``Turn the 
Page,'' but the musical highlight of the collection is the 
melancholy ``Loverman,'' originally produced by Nick Cave And The 
Bad Seeds. The track shows how Metallica can tone it down while 
staying true to their heavy metal roots. 
</P>
<P>
	``Garage Inc.'' shows Metallica has a sense of history, but more  
important, fun. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Valence Street'' (Columbia Records) -- The Neville Brothers  

</P>
<P>
	The Neville Brothers -- singers Art and Aaron, saxophonist  
Charles and percussionist Cyril -- still manage to keep their sound 
fresh, as evidenced on their 14th album ``Valence Street.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The record is named for the street where the brothers grew up in  
New Orleans, and like that city, the CD is a melting pot of styles. 
The album swings from the soaring soul of ``A Little Piece of 
Heaven'' through the funked-up version of Pete Seeger's folk 
classic ``If I Had a Hammer'' to the smooth jazz of the 
instrumental title track. 
</P>
<P>
	The highlight is a collaboration with rapper Wyclef Jean. But  
the Neville Brothers' classic sound only complements the toned-down 
hip hop on ``Mona Lisa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe the reason for the Brothers' longevity is that the music  
is timeless. Or as shown on ``Valence Street,'' maybe it's because 
they have made it timeless, and uniquely their own. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Wander This World'' (A&AMP;M) -- Jonny Lang  

</P>
<P>
	This teen-ager's exceptional first album, the 1996 ``Lie to  
Me,'' like any such startling debut, raised more questions than it 
answered. This, his second release, answers them. Jonny is for real 
and this disc is mandatory. 
</P>
<P>
	His ability, at age 17, is intimidating. As a singer, Jonny is  
settling down. As a guitarist, his play and sophisticated variety 
are astonishing. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonny Lang is already a darling of teen fanzines, and the  
sharpest track of this disc, ``Still Rainin,'' has been getting 
rock radio exposure. We dare say it now: Lang could rival Stevie 
Ray Vaughan in attracting an outside, pop-weary audience to 
reinvigorate the blues. 
</P>
<P>
	Blues veterans like B.B. King have seen his gift, pulling Lang  
into concerts and onto their releases as a guest player. But Lang 
is truest on his own, with some nicely written songs, refreshing 
variety, and soulful vocals on some tracks that remind us of Steve 
Marriot or perhaps of his own idol, Otis Redding. 
</P>
<P>
	Lang's covers of Luther Allison's ``Cherry Red Wine'' and  
Prince's ``I Am'' show a range that should be the envy of many pros 
who have been at it since before the kid was born. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Ralph Siegel, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Cecilia and Bryn: Duets'' (London/Decca) -- Cecilia Bartoli,  
Bryn Terfel, Orchestra dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia, 
conductor Myung-Whun Chung 

</P>
<P>
	In their first joint recording, Cecilia Bartoli and Bryn Terfel  
shine with as much luster as their performances of Mozart's ``The 
Marriage of Figaro'' at the Metropolitan Opera last fall, a 
compelling duo in a light and delightful recording that figures to 
be a big hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The mezzo-soprano and baritone start off with much of the first  
15 minutes of ``Figaro,'' through Figaro's ``Se vuol ballare.'' 
Miss Bartoli, who has no problem adjusting to higher soprano lines, 
then goes into ``Un moto di gioia,'' one of the pair of alternative 
arias that created a controversy when she sang them for three 
performances at the Met. (It substitutes for ``Venite 
inginocchiatevi'' in the second act). 
</P>
<P>
	Terfel is the perfect Figaro and Miss Bartoli is a compelling  
Susannah, hitting it off like Ricky and Lucy. It makes the listener 
hunger for a full ``Figaro'' recording from the pair. 
</P>
<P>
	Terfel switches characters for the Count's third-act duet with  
Susannah, ``Crude! perche finora farmi languir cosi?'' They follow 
with the Dorabella-Guglielmo duet from ``Cosi fan tutte'' (``Il 
core vi dono''), the Zerlina-Don Giovanni duet (``La ci darem la 
mano''), and a Papageno-Papagena excerpt from ``The Magic Flute.'' 
These two could go on singing Mozart for hours. 
</P>
<P>
	While Miss Bartoli takes a star turn in a pair of Rossini duets  
-- ``Dunque io son ... tu non m'inganni?'' from ``The Barber of 
Seville'' and ``Ai capricci della sorte'' from ``The Italian Girl 
in Algiers'' -- it is not the ideal role for Terfel, who struggles 
with the coloratura. He does much better in the Adina-Dr. Dulcamera 
``Quanto amore!'' from Donizetti's ``The Elixir of Love.'' Some 
opera house should immediately sign the pair for this opera. 
</P>
<P>
	While they often sing different repertoire, Miss Bartoli and  
Terfel appear to have a great future as a duets act. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Ronald Blum, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990310.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 23:23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vicar Favored for Florida Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A familiar cast of characters will be  
back for Saturday's Florida Derby, and that's OK with trainer Carl 
Nafzger -- as long as the results are the same. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone's talking about a surprise, and I hope to heck there  
aren't any,'' said Nafzger, who trains Fountain of Youth winner 
Vicar, the 3-1 morning line favorite for the $750,000 Florida Derby 
at Gulfstream Park. 
</P>
<P>
	A field of 11 3-year-olds, including the impressive filly Three  
Ring, were entered Wednesday for the 1 1/8-mile race. Vicar, a winner 
in three of five career starts, will also be facing five others who 
challenged him in the Fountain of Youth, including the second, 
third and fourth-place finishers in Cat Thief, Certain and Grits'N 
Hard Toast. 
</P>
<P>
	Also taking another shot at Vicar will be Casanova Star (eighth)  
and Aly's Alley, who was ninth in his first start this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Marquard, breeder and owner of Aly's Alley, expects his  
colt to run much better in the Florida Derby, one of several major 
Kentucky Derby prep races around the country this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was too anxious after being off 3 1/2 months,'' said Marquard,  
who was delighted his colt drew the No. 11 post. ``He seems to do 
better from the outside, so we hope to give you all a pleasant 
surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aly's Alley left from the No. 13 post when he finished second in  
the Breeders' Cup Juvenile last November. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Plesa, the trainer of Three Ring, was far from thrilled  
when his filly drew the No. 10 post. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outside post certain doesn't enhance her chances,'' Plesa  
said. `I'll talk it over with owner Barry Schwartz and we'll decide 
whether we want her in the Florida Derby or scratch her from the 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Three Ring is pulled out, she would run in the Bonnie Miss on  
March 16, the closing day at Gulfstream. 
</P>
<P>
	No filly has ever won the Florida Derby, first run in 1952.  
Three Ring, with four wins in seven career starts, is coming off a 
14 3/4-length romp in the Davona Dale on Feb. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar, who will be ridden by Shane Sellers, won the Fountain of  
Youth by a neck over the D. Wayne Lukas-trained Cat Thief. The 
victory came after a disappointing fifth-place finish in the Holy 
Bull on Jan. 16, and it gave Nafzger a touch of Derby fever again. 
</P>
<P>
	Nafzger won the 1990 Kentucky Derby with Unbridled, who also won  
the Florida Derby. The winner of the Florida Derby has gone on to 
win the Kentucky Derby nine times, with Thunder Gulch the last to 
do it in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``We couldn't be happier with him'' Nafzger said of his Wild  
Again colt, who is owned by James Tafel. ``He just keeps getting 
better. I saw what I wanted to see in his last work. We wanted him 
to relax and listen to his rider. He's a pretty happy horse right 
now. I think we have something special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Derby field, from the rail out, with jockeys and  
odds is: Valid Trefaire (Jose Santos, 15-1); Cat Thief (Pat Day, 
4-1); Certain (Kent Desormeaux, 6-1); Adonis (Jorge Chavez, 10-1); 
Vicar (Sellers, 3-1); Casanova Star (Mike Smith, 20-1); Wondertross 
(8-1, Jerry Bailey); Grits'N Hard Toast (Robbie Davis, 8-1); First 
American (Jose Velez, 20-1); Three Ring (John Velazquez, 5-1); and 
Aly's Alley (Edgar Prado, 15-1). 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Derby (ABC-TV, 5:43 p.m. EST post time) is one of  
several Derby preps at three tracks this weekend, with trainer Bob 
Baffert's brigade set to run in California and Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Baffert sends out current Derby favorite Exploit  
and Prime Timber in the San Felipe at Santa Anita and the filly 
Silverbulletday in the Fair Grounds Oaks; on Sunday, he's got 
Answer Lively -- the 2-year-old champion -- and General Challenge in 
the Louisiana Derby and the filly Excellent Meeting in the Santa 
Anita Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert nearly captured the Triple Crown the last two years,  
winning the Derby and Preakness with Silver Charm in 1997 and with 
Real Quiet in 1998. 
</P>
