<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Tibet Protesters Burn China Flags  
</P>
<P>
	DHARMSALA, India (AP) -- The Dalai Lama is marking the 40th  
anniversary of his people's exile today, and he is accusing China 
of lacking the ``political will and courage'' to seek a compromise 
on Tibet. Meanwhile, Tibetan protesters in New Delhi burned 40 
Chinese flags, lit firecrackers and burned an effigy representing 
Chinese President Jiang Zemin. The crowd also stood in silence for 
a minute to honor Tibetans who had died over the last four decades 
of Chinese rule. 

</P>
<P>
	US Envoy Meets With Yugoslav Leader  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Senior U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke  
began crisis talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic 
today, pushing for a Kosovo settlement. Yugoslav forces continued 
their military offensive in the province. Holbrooke huddled with 
fellow Western envoys and ambassadors at the president's palace 
before midday talks aimed at breaking down Milosevic's resistance 
to a U.S.-drafted peace plan. Yesterday, Holbrooke warned that 
Milosevic could be on a ``collision course'' with NATO. 

</P>
<P>
	Guatemalans To Meet With Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- President Clinton was meeting late today  
with a carefully chosen group of nearly 60 Guatemalans to discuss 
the war and the process that led to the peace agreement signed in 
Oslo in December 1996. Clinton is in Guatemala as part of a 
four-country tour of Central America. Two weeks ago, Guatemala's 
truth commission issued its report on the war, recommending that 
Guatemala's president, ``before the whole of Guatemalan society, 
ask for forgiveness'' for the murders and the violations of human 
rights. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Salad Bar Spawned E. Coli  
</P>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- An E. coli bacteria outbreak that sickened 10  
people has been traced to a restaurant salad bar, health officials 
said. At least eight additional cases may be linked to the Golden 
Corral restaurant in Kearney, 185 miles west of Omaha. Five people, 
including a 79-year-old woman and a 6-year-old boy, were 
hospitalized, although none was critically ill. 

</P>
<P>
	Mo., Va. Execute Convicted Killers  
</P>
<P>
	POTOSI, Mo. (AP) -- A prisoner whose case inspired a Vatican plea  
that his life be spared was put to death early today for killing a 
prison guard during a 1983 riot. Roy Roberts, 46, was executed by 
injection at Potosi Correctional Center. His fate was sealed after 
Gov. Mel Carnahan rejected a clemency request. Hours earlier, 
George Quesinberry Jr., 37, was executed by injection in Jarratt, 
Va., for killing company owner Thomas Haynes during a botched 
burglary at Tri-City Electrical Supply Co. in 1989. 

</P>
<P>
	Austrian Letter-Bomber Convicted  
</P>
<P>
	GRAZ, Austria (AP) -- A jury has convicted a reclusive former  
engineer of murder and sentenced him to life in prison for a series 
of letter and pipe bomb attacks that brought comparisons to the 
Unabomber case. Franz Fuchs was convicted on multiple counts of 
murder and attempted murder during a spree from 1993-96, the 
Austria Press Agency reported. He will serve the sentence in a 
mental institution. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler, Nissan End Talks  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler and Nissan have broken off talks  
over DaimlerChrysler's possible acquisition of a stake in Nissan 
Motor of Japan. Talks broke down regarding DaimlerChrysler's buying 
an equity stake in all of Nissan as well as an outright purchase of 
its commercial truck subsidiary, a DaimlerChrysler spokesman said 
at the Geneva International Motor Show. DaimlerChrysler had been in 
intense discussions with Nissan for the past three months. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei gained 383.30 points to close at  
15,480.00. In New York yesterday, the Dow industrials fell 33.85 to 
9,693.76. 

</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio's Son To Be Pallbearer  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Joe DiMaggio Jr. will be a pallbearer at his  
father's funeral tomorrow. The two had been estranged for many 
years, and they had not seen each other in two years. Only about 30 
relatives and close friends will attend the private service at Sts. 
Peter and Paul Church, where DiMaggio married his first wife, 
Dorothy Arnold, in 1939. The church's twin steeples tower over the 
North Beach section of San Francisco where DiMaggio spent most of 
his childhood. The New York Yankees great died Monday at age 84. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KATHLEEN SAMPEY  

</P>
</TEXT>
