<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NEA Cancels Children's Book Grant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The National Endowment for the Arts rescinded  
a grant to help a Texas printer publish and distribute a children's 
tale after finding the book was written by Mexican guerrilla leader 
Subcomandante Marcos. 
</P>
<P>
	William J. Ivey, the federal arts agency's head, canceled the  
$7,500 subsidy for the English edition of the children's book after 
a New York Times reporter brought the title's author to his 
attention, an NEA spokeswoman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I determined that this was not an appropriate use of  
government money,'' Ivey said in a statement relayed by the 
spokeswoman, Cherie Simon. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivey's concern was based on the possibility that some of the  
money could find its way to Marcos, Simon said, although the 
publisher said Marcos would not. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcos leads the Zapatista guerrillas in the southern state of  
Chiapas. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, called ``The Story of Colors,'' is a folk tale about  
Mexican gods, as told to Marcos by an Indian friend. It was 
originally published in Spanish in 1997 by a Mexican press with no 
financial help from the U.S. agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the front cover of the English edition, just printed by  
Cinco Puntos Press -- the small publisher in El Paso, Texas, that 
had been slated to get the grant -- is a photo of Marcos wearing a 
black ski mask over his face and with ammunition belts slung across 
his chest. That photo was not in the original Mexican edition, the 
NEA said. 
</P>
<P>
	The grant had been approved in the last few weeks by NEA panel  
that focused on the book's artistic merit, Simon said. None of the 
grant money had gone out, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The grant was approved by lower-level NEA officials, by an  
independent panel and by the National Council for the Arts, which 
includes two Republican House members, the spokeswoman said. They 
have a voice but no vote on the council. 
</P>
<P>
	The NEA staff knew of Marcos' authorship, and that appeared in  
the summaries the panel approved, Simon said. The final grant 
needed Ivey's approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Republican leadership tried again last year to abolish  
the agency, after members complained the NEA had helped some 
projects they considered obscene. The effort failed. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the Cinco Puntos Press, which has so far spent  
$15,000 to print 5,000 copies of Marcos' book, called the decision 
``spineless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This book is essentially about diversity and tolerance,  
everything the NEA is supposed to stand for,'' Bobby Byrd, a poet 
who runs the publishing company, told the Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas publisher still will get $7,500 from the NEA to  
publish an English version of another Spanish book, this one not 
written by Marcos, Simon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
