<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Breaks Through in Skiing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- After seven mostly fruitless years  
on skiing's top circuit, Chad Fleischer finished second Wednesday 
in the downhill at the World Cup finals -- trailing only the 
season's best downhiller, Norway's Lasse Kjus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will my dad ever have a surprise when he comes out of  
anesthesia,'' said Fleischer, whose father had knee surgery at home 
in Vail, Colo., after a skiing accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I called my personal trainer and told him to make sure my dad  
knows about it when he comes to. He's going to be psyched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Fleischer is also going to be sporting a new hairdo to  
match his son's -- a bleach-blond job with black and brown spots, a 
copy of a snow leopard's coat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now my dad will have to dye his hair the same way,'' Fleischer  
said. ``He promised if I got a podium, he'd do it. Maybe they'll 
give it to him when he gets out of surgery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, coming off what he called an ``absolute wreck'' of a  
season, Fleischer took a three-week break in Hawaii to contemplate 
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was three seconds out every race,'' he recalled. ``I had a  
million excuses -- it was boots, it was skis, the coach. But the 
real problem was me. I couldn't figure out how to put it together 
and get faster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus' victory stretched his overall World Cup points lead to 42  
over fellow Norwegian Kjetil Andre Aamodt and 88 in front of last 
year's overall champion Hermann Maier. Kjus also won an 
unprecedented five medals in the worlds. 
</P>
<P>
	Three races remain before the season ends Sunday. Aamodt was  
fourth in the downhill and Maier tied for ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	On the women's side, 22-year-old Canadian Melanie Turgeon -- like  
Fleischer -- got the first top-three finish of her career with a 
third in downhill behind winner Alexandra Meissnitzer of Austria 
(1:54.16), and Norway's Ingeborg Helen Marken 1:54.47. Turgeon 
clocked 1:54.70. 
</P>
<P>
	``Finally a podium. I'm so excited,'' said Turgeon, in her  
seventh season on the circuit. ``It's been a long time coming. I 
took it out of my back pocket. I gave it everything I had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meissnitzer wrapped up the overall World Cup title last week and  
is a prohibitive favorite to add season super-G and giant slalom 
titles. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleischer is 27 and old by racing standards. Entering the season  
he'd never finished better than 11th in any World Cup, a record he 
topped slightly this season with a best of ninth in a super-G and 
11th in downhill. 
</P>
<P>
	Even a month ago, he was mostly an also-ran with a wild haircut  
-- the best American racer on a modest team that misses the injured 
Olympic gold medalist Picabo Street, or retired Olympic gold 
medalist Tommy Moe. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came his sixth last month in super-G in the worlds in Vail.  
Last week he won a downhill training run in Norway and then came 
Wednesday's breakthrough -- a silver medal in 1 minute 49.89 
seconds, just .16 behind the downhill season champion Kjus, who is 
also a favorite to win the overall season title. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great feeling, I'm there with the big guys now,'' said  
Fleishcer, who knows what he says next sounds ridiculous. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that's my destiny to dominate ski racing, he said.  
``I've gotten some grief for saying it, but that's where I am,'' he 
added. ``That the mentality I've carried into the season, the 
mentality you have to have to be the best in the world. That might 
sound outrageous, but not to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rattle off names like Moe, AJ Kitt and 1984 Olympic downhill  
champion Bill Johnson, and Fleischer is respectful -- not 
deferential. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of respect for those guys,'' he said. ``But at  
the same time I want to gun 'em down, I want to be a little bigger 
and lot better than they ever were.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
