<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 00:53:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Hears of Foster Care Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When he was just a kid, Reggie Rollins had to  
look out for his younger brother and sister because his mother, a 
drug addict, couldn't care for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were many times when there was no food, or heat, or  
electricity, because our family income had gone to buy drugs,'' 
Rollins, 21, of Stamford, Conn., told the House Ways and Means 
subcommittee on human resources Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	After years in foster care, Rollins ended up at a group home,  
run by the Domus Foundation, that he credits for giving him the 
skills to live on his own. Now, he shares an apartment and goes to 
college. 
</P>
<P>
	``The group home had life skills classes where I learned about  
money management, transportation, cooking and other skills I would 
need,'' said Rollins, one of many witnesses who asked Congress to 
increase funding for programs that help foster children make the 
transition to independent living. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, about 20,000 teen-agers without permanent families  
leave foster care each year when they turn 18. Without support, 
many have a difficult time keeping a job or an apartment, and often 
end up in prison or living on the street, experts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of these youngsters experience depression, isolation and  
loneliness,'' said Carol Williams, a U.S. Department of Health and 
Human Services associated commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
	It's too early to say how Congress may address the problems  
facing the after-foster care population. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md., has proposed legislation that would,  
among other things, let states continue providing benefits, 
including Medicaid, to foster care youths up to age 21 if they are 
working or in school. Now, benefits end at 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., the subcommittee chairwoman, is  
also considering drafting her own bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has also proposed increasing funding  
for the Independent Living Program, which provides services to 
older children in foster care, by 50 percent, to about $105 million 
a year. The states would provide a $45 million match. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1992, federal funding for the program has held at about  
$70 million a year, but the number of children age 16 and older in 
foster care has grown from about 62,000 in 1992 to over 77,000 in 
1998 and is expected to continue to grow at least for the next 
several years. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has also proposed a new state grant program  
to help pay for room and board for youths, age 18 to 21, who are 
out of foster care and enrolled in school or job training. Funding 
would go from $5 million in fiscal 2000, which starts Oct. 1, to 
$20 million in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, of HHS, and William Pinto, adolescent services  
coordinator for Connecticut's Department of Children and Families, 
cited studies that found alarming trends among young people 
recently out of foster care. 
</P>
<P>
	Within two to four years, just half had completed high school,  
less than half were employed, 25 percent had been homeless for at 
least a night, 25 percent of the men had spent time in prison and 
60 percent of the women had at least one child, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``These young people have suffered enough,'' said Pinto, whose  
program serves more than 600 Connecticut youths a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
