<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Italia Mum on Olivetti Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- After meeting for several hours late Wednesday,  
Telecom Italia's board postponed making a statement on its 
long-awaited plan to fend off a hostile takeover effort by Olivetti 
SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom's directors are expected to issue a statement Thursday,  
a company spokeswoman said. The delay added to the drama 
surrounding Olivetti's $57.3 billion bid, which, if successful, 
would be the biggest-ever European telecom deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Olivetti announced its takeover plans on Feb. 20, analysts  
have been expecting Telecom to merge with its 60 percent-owned 
mobile phone subsidiary, Telecom Italia Mobile, to make such a 
takeover more expensive. A merger with TIM would add some $21.8 
billion to the price the much smaller Olivetti would need to pay 
Telecom shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian news agency Ansa reported earlier Wednesday that it  
had obtained a draft copy of the plan calling for the merger. 
Telecom's chief executive Franco Bernabe stated two weeks ago that 
he would ask his board of directors to approve a merger with TIM. 
</P>
<P>
	In other measures aimed at driving up its value, Telecom will  
also offer investors the right to convert their nonvoting savings 
shares into common stock and will seek permission to buy back up to 
10 percent of all capital, ANSA said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report didn't specify whether Telecom Italia would adopt all  
three measures or if its board would be asked to opt for one or 
more of them. 
</P>
<P>
	ANSA said Telecom Italia would also move ahead with asset sales.  
</P>
<P>
	However, a source close to Olivetti claimed Wednesday that any  
of these defensive measures would be illegal under Italian 
regulations unless Telecom first obtained the approval of 30 
percent of its shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that a  
merger between Telecom and its mobile subsidiary would only 
increase the size of what Olivetti would have to buy and would not 
boost Telecom's value to shareholders. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
