<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Guillen Finally Gets Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- Jose Guillen's visa waiver was approved  
by the U.S. State Department, and the Pittsburgh Pirates outfielder 
might arrive at spring training as early as Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Pirates owner Kevin McClatchy had asked Sen. Rick Santorum to  
help Guillen regain his visa. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as Jose gets the visa in his hands, our hope is he'll  
be on the next flight here,'' Pirates general manager Cam Bonifay 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen remained in the Dominican Republic for three weeks,  
missing the start of spring training, because U.S. immigration 
officials questioned the validity of a marriage license he 
presented before trying to return to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both senators really helped move this process along with the  
State Department and made the whole thing happen very quickly,'' 
McClatchy said. ``We are very appreciative of that. It's a relief 
to get this out of the way and get Jose Guillen back to where he 
needs to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following an investigation, the Immigration and Naturalization  
Service refused Monday to reinstate Guillen's visa. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a question about Jose misrepresenting himself  
in documents,'' McClatchy said. ``But this is a 22-year-old kid who 
recently lost his father. He might not have had the guidance that a 
normal 22-year-old would have. He might have made some mistakes, 
though I don't think they were intentional. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to sit down and talk with Jose once he gets here. I  
want to found out everything that happened and see if I can 
possibly provide some counseling or guidance to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Santorum was a strong supporter of the effort to build a new  
stadium for the Pirates and helped obtain federal funding for 
transportation projects near the ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonifay would not say if Guillen will be fined. The mandatory  
reporting date was March 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would be a private matter,'' Bonifay said. ``I do want to  
talk to Jose, though. I'm sure he's done a lot of explaining to a 
lot of people these past couple of weeks. We'll sit down and talk 
about things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen, who is recovering from a shoulder injury sustained in  
winter ball, has already missed so much spring training that he may 
start the season at Triple-A Nashville and miss the Pirates' April 
5 opener against Montreal at Three Rivers Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once Jose gets here, he'll receive the same physical all the  
other players do,'' Bonifay said. ``If he checks out fine 
physically, then we'll put him on a program designed to get him 
into shape to get ready to see game action. How long it will take 
him to get ready for the start of the season remains to be seen 
until he gets here and we see what kind of shape he is in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen has been the Pirates' starting right fielder for two  
seasons after making the jump from Class A to the major leagues 
during 1997. He hit .267 last year with 14 homers and 84 RBIs in 
153 games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
