<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- In an attempt to calm critics who  
claimed he was steamrollering plans for a new constitution, 
Venezuela's president limited his own participation in the process 
on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sovereignty of electing members of the assembly belongs to  
the people and not the president, as some have said in an attempt 
to make me look like a tyrant, an autocrat,'' President Hugo 
Chavez, the leader of a failed 1992 coup attempt, said in a 
nationally broadcast address. 
</P>
<P>
	He provoked a storm of controversy when he took office last  
month and issued a decree calling for a national vote April 25 on 
whether Venezuela should write a new constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	The decree also called for a national referendum asking  
Venezuelans to give Chavez the right to decide how assembly members 
are chosen. Critics claimed it was illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez says a new constitution is needed to fight a corrupt  
political establishment many blame for squandering vast oil 
reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan announced Wednesday, Venezuelans would choose 103  
members of a constituent assembly in open elections. Active 
soldiers and high-level elected officials, including Chavez, would 
be barred from running. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- The president of the central bank said  
Wednesday Brazil should be able to jump-start its sluggish economy 
in the second half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Arminio Fraga said he had ``received good  
signs'' by foreign banks on their exposure in Brazil, estimated at 
$20 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Many had decided to continue extending credit to Brazil and none  
has said credit would be reduced. A few said they planned to 
increase credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil and the International Monetary Fund revised the original  
$41.5 billion rescue package after Brazil floated its currency in 
January. Since then, the real has lost nearly 40 percent of its 
value. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday, the real strengthened for the sixth consecutive day,  
closing at 1.86 per dollar. In late February, the real reached its 
weakest point at 2.23 per dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru's human rights image has been hurt by a  
critical U.S. State Department report and the case of an 
Israeli-born TV station owner forced into exile, a newspaper quoted 
U.S. Ambassador Dennis Jett as saying Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the report released Feb. 26 and the case of Baruch Ivcher  
had ``greatly affected Peru's image abroad,'' the Lima newspaper El 
Sol quoted Jett as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The report called Peru's judicial system corrupt and susceptible  
to government pressure and said President Alberto Fujimori 
interfered with press freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	It highlighted the case of Baruch Ivcher, the Israeli-born  
majority owner of Channel 2, which in 1997 broadcast reports 
linking Peru's military and National Intelligence Service to human 
rights abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	After airing the reports, a court revoked Ivcher's Peruvian  
citizenship, arguing he never renounced his Israeli citizenship. 
Since Peruvian law does not allow foreigners to own TV stations, 
another court stripped Ivcher of his controlling interest in 
Channel 2. He fled to exile in Miami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
