<HEADLINE> Tenn. Senators Back Lamar Alexander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lamar Alexander picked up the endorsements of  
both of his home state's senators Wednesday in his campaign for the 
Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Thompson and Bill Frist endorsed the former Tennessee  
governor, who is making his second bid for the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows not only what to do to succeed in his candidacy, but  
he knows what to do when he gets there,'' Thompson said. ``These 
are the times for this person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He can best lead this country in the next millennium,'' said  
Frist. ``He has the integrity, character and the honor'' to be 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Alexander called for the resignation of National  
Security Adviser Sandy Berger over allegations that Clinton 
administration efforts to boost ties with China delayed a 
longstanding espionage investigation at a research facility. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears that this is one of the most serious national  
security breaches in 50 years,'' Alexander said. ``For his 
unwillingness to act on this serious matter, Mr. Berger should 
resign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berger, traveling with President Clinton in Guatemala, defended  
the administration's work on the investigation as ``appropriate'' 
and swift. ``I have no intention of resigning,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, two other Republican presidential hopefuls also had  
harsh comments on the subject. 
</P>
<P>
	``Berger and others who dragged their feet on this must go,''  
said Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Berger is the responsible authority here,'' Pat Buchanan said.  
``He ought to explain his actions to the country or resign.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
