<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:46:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Intervenes Over Satellite TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Satellite TV customers losing Fox and CBS  
programs would get some relief under a bill passed by a Senate 
panel Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, approved on a voice vote by the Senate Commerce  
Committee, is the latest twist in the dispute between satellite 
companies and broadcasters over the conditions under which viewers 
who get their TV from satellite can watch network programs. 
</P>
<P>
	About 700,000 satellite TV customers already have lost Fox and  
CBS signals under an order from a federal court in Miami. Another 
order by the same court will cut off an additional 1.5 million 
customers from CBS and Fox signals by April 30. None of these 
orders affect NBC, ABC or other networks' affiliates. 
</P>
<P>
	The order affects customers who the court said aren't legally  
entitled to receive the network programs. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Senate bill becomes law, however, customers who lost the  
network programs would once again be able to watch them on their 
satellite systems until Dec. 31, 1999. If the bill becomes law 
before April 30, it would avert a second cutoff, allowing customers 
to continue receiving the CBS and Fox signals until Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	And it would prevent satellite customers from also losing NBC,  
ABC or other networks' affiliates during that period, said the 
committee's counsel, Lauren Belvin. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee agreed Wednesday to add this provision by Sen. Jay  
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., to the satellite bill written by Senate 
Commerce Committee Chairman John McCain, R-Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers are not guilty in this,'' Rockefeller said.  
</P>
<P>
	After Dec. 31, satellite customers living closest to their local  
stations -- as determined by a technical test involving the 
stations' coverage areas -- would be cut off from the network 
programs, Belvin said. But customers living on the edges of the 
stations' coverage areas may be able to continue receiving the 
signals unless federal regulators decide otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would give satellite TV customers, for the first  
time, the right to receive local TV stations on their satellite 
systems. This would help make satellite companies stronger 
competitors with cable companies, which are permitted to deliver 
local TV signals to cable customers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bill doesn't change the existing test for determining  
when satellite customers can legally receive ``distant'' network 
programs. Federal law allows satellite companies to provide distant 
network signals from other broadcast areas to customers only if 
those customers can't receive their local stations using rooftop 
antennas. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellite and broadcasting industries have been at odds for  
years over how to interpret an arcane legal test for determining 
when a satellite customer can't get a local signal. Under it, some 
satellite customers aren't legally permitted to receive network 
programs, yet they can't get a decent picture from their local 
station with an antenna. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., said even though this standard  
``makes no sense,'' the political reality is that trying to change 
it would kill the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcasters said they don't like the committee's bill, but  
stopped short of saying they'll try to kill it. It's not clear when 
the bill will be voted on by the Senate. Similar legislation is 
moving through the House. Some satellite companies and consumer 
groups support the Senate bill. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 303.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
