<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broken Freighter Pulled to Sea Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALDPORT, Ore. (AP) -- One way or another, the Navy is determined  
to make sure the oil-laden bow of the freighter New Carissa never 
reaches shore again. 
</P>
<P>
	The freighter's broken bow section -- which twice ran aground on  
some of Oregon's most pristine beaches -- is again being towed out 
to sea for burial, along with its 130,000 gallons of thick bunker 
fuel, in water 12,000 feet deep. 
</P>
<P>
	A Coast Guard cutter had been scheduled to use its deck gun to  
scuttle the floating derelict. Later, the task was assigned to the 
destroyer USS David R. Ray and its 5-inch guns. 
</P>
<P>
	But today, the Navy said it plans to sink the hull by placing  
demolition charges on board. That likely would entail putting 
people back on board the New Carissa, something Coast Guard 
officers said Monday they hoped to avoid. There was no immediate 
explanation for the change of plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Air strikes also are an option, said Navy Lt. Cmdr. William  
Fenick. 
</P>
<P>
	By 6 a.m. today, the bow section was 90 miles offshore, on its  
way to a burial spot 250 miles from land. 
</P>
<P>
	A temperature of about 34 degrees on the ocean floor is expected  
to further thicken the oil, already near the consistency of 
asphalt, and prevent it from doing any more environmental damage. 
</P>
<P>
	A week ago, the tow cable between the bow section and the tug  
Sea Victory was snapped in a storm about 50 miles offshore. The 
wreck washed ashore at Waldport, 80 miles north of Coos Bay, the 
spot where the whole ship originally ran aground Feb. 4 and broke 
apart. 
</P>
<P>
	It was pulled off the beach Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Worries ashore turned to the estimated 70,000 gallons of oil the  
New Carissa spilled while it was aground at Coos Bay. Much of it 
has yet to wash up, though tar balls have been seen as far away as 
southern Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Biologists said 312 birds have died since the Japanese-owned  
ship first spilled oil Feb. 8. There was oil visible on at least 
139 of the birds. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship's 220-foot stern section still sits mired in the sand  
at Coos Bay. Salvage crews have yet to decide what to do with it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
