<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glitches in Army Parachute System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) -- Some Army paratroopers have stopped  
using a new kind of backup parachute after it failed to open during 
tests on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of the 28,000 members of the 18th Airborne Corps who  
are stationed at Fort Bragg are using an older backup parachute 
while Army safety officials examine the new one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we continue to see this as a fairly short-range  
situation,'' Lt. Col. Rick Spearman said Wednesday. ``Our only 
concern right now is for us to do the prudent thing, the right 
thing -- not place soldiers at unnecessary risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fort Bragg officials said there are no known cases of it failing  
during a jump. Paratroop units at other Army bases, including Fort 
Benning, Ga., continue to use the new model. 
</P>
<P>
	Airborne units began using the Modified Improved Reserve  
Parachute System in November. It has a spring-loaded mechanism to 
help it open. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Fort Bragg scaled back use of the parachutes March  
3 after a soldier pulled his reserve rip cord while on the ground 
and nothing happened. Safety investigators then examined 10 
parachutes and found six did not deploy when the rip cord was 
pulled. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin Aerospace, the manufacturer, said the new parachute has  
saved six lives since Fort Bragg began using it last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
